const gptWebsiteStoryOverridesEn20260627 = {
  "029-lomax-field-recorder": {
    "title": "The Heavy Recorder in the Trunk",
    "summary": "A field recorder shows why some cultural knowledge crosses music, archives, oral history, politics, and memory.",
    "scene": "In the 1930s and 1940s, a young collector drove long roads with recording equipment heavy enough to change the whole trip.",
    "storyBody": "He sat in prisons, on porches, in churches, kitchens, fields, and small rooms, recording songs that rarely entered official culture. At first glance, he seemed to be collecting music. But the recordings also held accents, work rhythms, jokes, local histories, racial violence, migration, memory, and the dignity of people who had often been treated as cultural material rather than cultural authors.\n\nThe work was difficult to place in one box. It was musicology, folklore, archive building, oral history, documentary practice, and also a political claim: every community should have the chance to hear itself preserved. Arts and humanities that do not fit a single category live in this borderland, where classification matters less than care for fragile human expression.\n\nThe trouble was that gestures, materials, sounds, and memories crossed those boxes and answered one another. Once that trouble was recorded seriously, the starting point of the field was no longer the name of a category, but the question of how works carry historical experience, bodily feeling, and ways of seeing into public meaning. This person was Alan Lomax, whose field recordings and cultural equity work preserved and reinterpreted folk music and oral traditions in the United States and around the world.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Arts and humanities outside a single category protect hybrid cultural practices that cross music, memory, archives, oral history, media, and public meaning.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "Whose voice near you might disappear if no one treats it as culture before it becomes famous?"
  },
  "031-bus-stop-price": {
    "title": "Why Dynasties Weaken",
    "summary": "A man who watched tribes, cities, and regimes in unstable times tried to write social behavior as patterned history.",
    "scene": "In fourteenth-century North Africa, a young official moved among courts, tribal camps, and prisons, seeing power rise and collapse firsthand.",
    "storyBody": "His life was never very settled. His family lived through plague, and his official career was repeatedly caught in political storms. He began to doubt that history books were enough when they only recorded who won and who lost.\n\nWhy could some groups hold together? Why did they often loosen after entering wealthy cities? Why did taxation, luxury, education, geography, and shared group spirit change the fate of regimes together? He placed the tribal alliances, city bureaucracies, and dynastic cycles he had seen beside one another, trying to find the forces behind social behavior.\n\nAn early shape of the social and behavioural sciences appears in this line of questioning: people do not act as isolated units; group cohesion, institutions, and environment shape history together. Opinions, rumours, or single records could still help people act at first. But to carry judgment further, investigation, checking, classification, communication, and public explanation had to become learnable work.\n\nThe name of social and behavioural science could wait. On the ground, the need for a new training in investigation, checking, classification, communication, and public explanation was already present. This person was Ibn Khaldun, whose Muqaddimah analysed social organization, dynastic cycles, and asabiyyah, and is often treated as an important early source for social-scientific thought.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Social and behavioural sciences study how choices, groups, institutions, culture, and environment shape action together.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "When a team grows weak, do you only blame individuals, or do you ask what happened to the structure of the group?"
  },
  "032-rumor-before-the-storm": {
    "title": "Drawers for the World's Knowledge",
    "summary": "A palace of paper cards made news and information about more than reporting: it also meant organizing and retrieving the world.",
    "scene": "In late nineteenth-century Brussels, a young lawyer sat in a room piled with paper cards and imagined that all the world's knowledge could be found.",
    "storyBody": "He was not concerned with one piece of news. He was concerned with how human beings could preserve and share everything that had already been written down. Books, papers, reports, images, newspaper clippings, and statistical tables were like fragments scattered on the floor if they could not be classified, numbered, cited, and retrieved.\n\nWith collaborators, he designed the Universal Decimal Classification and built a vast card catalogue, trying to let people in different places ask questions and receive relevant materials. The dream had the limits of its age and carried a Eurocentric shadow, but it caught the core of information work: public knowledge does not flow naturally. It needs indexes, standards, media, institutions, and continual maintenance.\n\nThis was not a moment when old methods had completely failed. Handing social problems to opinion, rumour, or a single record could still let people act first. What pressed against that habit was the fact that people in different positions leave conflicting evidence that cannot simply be ignored.\n\nWhen that blockage returns again and again, the new question becomes: what kind of record lets scattered life enter public judgment? This person was Paul Otlet, who created the Mundaneum and helped push early documentation, knowledge organization, and information science. He is often seen as an important precursor of modern thinking about information organization.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Journalism and information work covers reporting, preservation, retrieval, organization, and circulation so public knowledge can be found, checked, and used.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "If a crucial piece of information cannot be found, has it really entered public life?"
  },
  "038-community-data-project": {
    "title": "The Black Dots Around the Pump",
    "summary": "A disease map placed social investigation, data, local interviews, and public information inside one judgment.",
    "scene": "On the streets of Soho, London, in 1854, cholera cases kept rising, and a doctor used addresses and maps to trace where deaths were occurring.",
    "storyBody": "At the time, many people still believed bad air was the main cause. He turned his attention instead to what people had drunk, where they lived, who had left, who had stayed, and which apparent exceptions actually shared another explanation. He did not complete the investigation alone; a local pastor and residents provided crucial clues through visits and local knowledge.\n\nOnce cases were marked on the map, the black dots around the Broad Street pump grew dense. The judgment was both medical and social-informational: data had to come from the streets, interviews had to correct the map, and the map then had to persuade public authorities to act.\n\nThe interdisciplinary space of social sciences, journalism, and information is clear here. Evidence must be able to cross disciplinary boundaries before it can change a city's decision. But the pressure of the scene was that different positions leave conflicting evidence that cannot be ignored.\n\nBefore the field name became fixed, investigation, checking, classification, communication, and public explanation had already connected the site to judgment. This person was John Snow, whose Broad Street cholera investigation and map analysis became a classic practice in epidemiology, public health, and data visualization. Such origins are often not grand: the scene that old methods cannot carry remains first, and only later do investigation, checking, classification, communication, and public explanation become methods.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Interdisciplinary social science, journalism, and information connect social investigation, data, maps, interviews, and public communication.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "When does a public problem need a map, interviews, and action to appear at the same time?"
  },
  "039-unusual-community-signal": {
    "title": "Why the Fishers Did Not Empty the Lake",
    "summary": "A long observer of shared resources found that real communities often invent rules better than simple theory predicts.",
    "scene": "In the second half of the twentieth century, a researcher read many cases about forests, irrigation canals, and fisheries, and found that they did not always collapse as textbooks predicted.",
    "storyBody": "A popular explanation gave common resources only two endings: either they had to be privatized by the market, or managed uniformly by the state; otherwise everyone would take a little more until the system collapsed. She was not satisfied with a story that tidy.\n\nShe and her colleagues compared irrigation communities, fisheries, pastures, and forests around the world. They found that some communities made their own boundaries, monitoring systems, sanctions, conflict-resolution practices, and layered rules. These communities were not perfect utopias. They could fail. But they proved that social reality was more complex than a two-way split.\n\nThis kind of patience is needed in social sciences, journalism, and information that do not fit a single category. Some institutional knowledge is hidden in local rules, oral agreements, and long observation, and does not necessarily belong to one discipline.\n\nThe details left by this scene also remind researchers that people in different positions leave conflicting evidence that still cannot be ignored. The center of the question shifts: what kind of record lets scattered lives enter public judgment, instead of throwing unusual cases away as exceptions? The name of the field could wait; the scene was already demanding a new training in investigation, checking, classification, communication, and public explanation. This person was Elinor Ostrom, whose work on common-pool resources and institutional analysis earned the Nobel Prize in Economics and changed how people understand collective governance.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Social science and information outside a single category can hold complex phenomena that cross institutions, behaviour, local knowledge, and public information.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "What informal rule near you is more precise than outsiders would expect?"
  },
  "041-cafe-closing-sheet": {
    "title": "A Company Is Not a Machine",
    "summary": "A long observation of a large corporation helped management see organizations as social institutions made of people, purposes, and responsibility.",
    "scene": "In the mid-twentieth century, a young management thinker entered a large automobile company and found that the hard part was not drawing an organization chart, but understanding why an organization acts.",
    "storyBody": "He did not come from engineering, and he was not someone who only looked at financial statements. He cared about a plainer question: as a company becomes larger and larger, who decides its goals? What is a manager responsible for? Are employees only screws in a machine? Where do customers, society, and long-term survival belong?\n\nObserving organizations such as General Motors, he found that management was not as simple as a chain of command. It was the work of keeping knowledge, authority and responsibility, performance, innovation, and human dignity in a relation that could still function. Business and administration became, here, a study of how an organization acts with purpose.\n\nIt had to look at numbers, but also at people. It had to look at efficiency, but also at responsibility. The trouble was that costs, responsibilities, rights, and risks were often hidden until after a decision had been made.\n\nOnce that trouble was recorded seriously, the starting point of the field was no longer a name, but the question of how rules, resources, and responsibilities should be arranged so they could be jointly borne. The names of business and management could wait. Accounts, institutions, cases, boundaries of rights, and organizational design were already demanding a new training on the ground. This person was Peter Drucker, whose Concept of the Corporation and later work helped establish much of the language of modern management thought.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Business and administration study how organizations, processes, responsibility, coordination, performance, and decisions keep collective work sustainable.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "Where does an organization start to fail when it pursues efficiency but cannot name its responsibilities?"
  },
  "042-bicycle-deposit": {
    "title": "When Students First Understood Common Law",
    "summary": "A lecturer organized scattered cases and legal tradition into a learnable system, moving legal education toward public language.",
    "scene": "In eighteenth-century Oxford, a young lawyer faced students and tried to turn the complexity of common law into an ordered course.",
    "storyBody": "At the time, common law was often thought to be something a person could only absorb slowly in law offices and courts. Outsiders had trouble entering it. Cases, customs, terms, and procedures were like a forest: they protected rights, but they also made many people lose their way.\n\nHe began to lecture publicly on the laws of England, arranging rights, property, private wrongs, and public crimes into a systematic account. His book later became enormously influential, and it also carries the limits of its time, especially around colonial and social hierarchy, so it has to be read critically.\n\nBut one key change in law as a discipline had already appeared. Rules were not only a secret technique inside a professional circle. They could be explained, published, argued over, and taught.\n\nThis was not a moment when old methods completely failed. Experience, contracts, or accounts could still let people handle transactions and organizations at first. What pressed against them was the way costs, responsibilities, rights, and risks were often hidden after decisions. When that blockage returned, the question became: how should rules, resources, and responsibilities be arranged so they can be jointly borne? A field does not begin with its name first; it begins with practicable actions such as accounts, institutions, cases, rights boundaries, and organizational design. This person was William Blackstone, whose Commentaries on the Laws of England became a classic text in common-law education and Anglo-American legal thought.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Law studies rules, rights, responsibility, evidence, interpretation, and institutions for handling conflict.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "If only a few professionals can understand the rules, how can ordinary people protect their rights?"
  },
  "048-pop-up-market-rules": {
    "title": "A Report on Cheaper Insurance",
    "summary": "A lawyer brought business data, administration, and public law together to protect ordinary financial life.",
    "scene": "In early twentieth-century Boston, a lawyer heard that working families could not afford reliable insurance and also saw how financial companies used information asymmetry.",
    "storyBody": "He did not treat law as only courtroom technique. For him, law, business, and administration had to answer one question together: how can ordinary people avoid being swallowed by structural weakness in a complex market?\n\nHe studied insurance costs, company profits, the savings-bank system, and public regulation. He proposed savings bank life insurance so that ordinary families could obtain life insurance that was cheaper and more transparent. The plan could not be completed by one discipline alone: it needed financial calculation, legal authorization, administrative execution, and public persuasion.\n\nThe interdisciplinary meaning of business, management, and law appears here. Markets are not naturally fair, and rules do not become effective automatically. They have to be designed so that they can serve real life.\n\nThe pressure was that costs, responsibilities, rights, and risks were often hidden until after decisions had been made. Once that trouble was taken seriously, the field's starting point was no longer its name, but the arrangement of rules, resources, and responsibilities so they could be jointly borne. This person was Louis Brandeis, who promoted savings bank life insurance and other public reforms, and later influenced business regulation and legal public responsibility as a lawyer, reformer, and Justice of the United States Supreme Court.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Interdisciplinary business, management, and law connect organizational design, financial decisions, contracts, regulation, administration, and accountability.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "When a product is too complex for ordinary people to judge its risk, how should law and management intervene?"
  },
  "049-strange-side-business": {
    "title": "Refill Bottles in a Small Shop",
    "summary": "A skincare shop mixed business, ethics, supply chains, and activism until ordinary categories were no longer enough.",
    "scene": "In a British seaside town in the 1970s, a woman entrepreneur opened a small shop where customers brought empty bottles back to be refilled.",
    "storyBody": "She did not follow the ordinary path of the cosmetics industry at the time. Packaging could be simple. Animal testing could be questioned. The story of ingredients could be told to customers. A business could also stand publicly beside environmental and human-rights issues.\n\nHer practice later required complex judgment as well. Brand expansion, supply chains, acquisition, and market storytelling could all make ideals less pure. But the case shows why business, management, and law outside a single category often appear at the boundary.\n\nA product is not only a transaction. It can also be a value claim, a contract relation, a labour condition, an ecological choice, and a public communication. This was not a moment when older methods completely failed. Experience, contracts, or accounts could still let people handle transactions and organizations at first.\n\nWhat pressed against that older way was the fact that costs, responsibilities, rights, and risks were often hidden until after decisions had been made. When that blockage appeared again and again, the new question became: how are rules, resources, and responsibilities arranged so they can be jointly borne? This person was Anita Roddick, who founded The Body Shop and influenced business ethics and brand activism through environmental concerns, opposition to animal testing, and ethical consumerism.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Business, management, and law outside a single category handle mixed arrangements that cross business models, ethics, regulation, communities, and public value.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "When a brand claims a value position, do you read the slogan, or do you examine how it organizes supply chains and responsibility?"
  },
  "051-yogurt-on-the-counter": {
    "title": "Beaks on the Islands",
    "summary": "A long voyage moved biology from classifying species toward asking how life changes with its environment.",
    "scene": "In the 1830s, a young naturalist became seasick aboard ship, collected specimens, and noticed subtle differences among birds, tortoises, and plants from island to island.",
    "storyBody": "When he set out, he was not someone prepared to overturn inherited ideas. He was more like a young man who loved to observe: writing notes, collecting insects, sending specimens back, and weathering the voyage with the crew.\n\nWhat changed him was not one single instant. It was the slow accumulation of many small differences. Nearby islands had birds with different beaks. Fossils and living animals seemed to answer one another. Artificial breeding showed that traits could be selected.\n\nYears later, he organized these clues into a larger explanation: life was not a fixed display case. It gradually changed through variation, heredity, environment, and selection. Biology and related sciences were no longer only naming living things; they also began asking why living things had become the way they were.\n\nConfirming living phenomena by the naked eye or by isolated specimens still had its use. But to carry judgment further, samples, lenses, comparison, records, and repeated observation had to become learnable work. This person was Charles Darwin, who presented the theory of natural selection in On the Origin of Species and became one of the major figures in modern evolutionary biology.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Biological and related sciences study life, species, heredity, adaptation, evolution, and relationships among living systems.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "When you notice a small difference between two similar living things, do you treat it as accident, or as a clue left by the environment?"
  },
  "052-stream-after-rain": {
    "title": "Why Spring Fell Silent",
    "summary": "A book about the loss of birdsong turned an environmental issue from local pest control into an alarm about the whole ecosystem.",
    "scene": "In mid-twentieth-century America, a marine biologist received more and more letters: there were fewer birds, dead fish, and land that felt wrong after spraying.",
    "storyBody": "She had written about the ocean before, and she was skilled at bringing science to ordinary readers. Facing pesticides, she did not only ask whether they could kill the target pest. She asked what happened after they entered soil, water, insects, birds, fish, and human bodies, and how they moved from one place to another.\n\nShe read research, organized cases, endured attacks from the chemical industry, and carefully avoided turning complex ecology into simple alarm. The environmental field becomes clear here: human technology does not act on only one point. It moves through food chains, public policy, commercial interests, and everyday households.\n\nA tool that looks effective may make spring itself fall silent if its long-term costs are not seen. The pressure in the scene is that water sources, fuel, soil, species, and community life on the same piece of land can change together.\n\nThe name can appear later. What first remains is the repeated practice of long-term observation, community records, ecological relationships, and feedback from action. This person was Rachel Carson, whose Silent Spring helped push modern environmental movements and debates over pesticide regulation, becoming a major classic of environmental science and public environmental awareness. The full system would come later; at the starting point, what mattered more was that this scene forced long-term observation, community records, ecological relationships, and action feedback to become gradually fixed as practice.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Environmental science studies how natural systems, pollutants, organisms, water, soil, and human actions affect one another.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "When a solution makes one problem disappear, what quieter signals should still be watched?"
  },
  "053-kitchen-ice-and-steam": {
    "title": "The Ball on the Inclined Plane",
    "summary": "A ball rolling down a slope helped physical science use experiment, measurement, and mathematics to question motion.",
    "scene": "In seventeenth-century Italy, a teacher rolled a small ball down an inclined plane and used a water clock and marks to record how it accelerated.",
    "storyBody": "He was not satisfied with reciting ancient authority on how heavy bodies fall. Real falling was too fast and hard to measure clearly, so he turned the inclined plane into a tool for slowing motion down.\n\nWith the slope, the relation among time, distance, and speed could be observed. Each roll of the small ball seemed to remind him that nature did not have to be argued about only in words; it could also be questioned through designed experiments.\n\nThe spirit of the physical sciences appears here: ordinary motion can be broken into measurable relations, expressed with mathematics, and then tested again by experiment against intuition. Continuing to use authoritative explanations, or treating a phenomenon as an isolated experimental result, still had its use.\n\nBut to carry judgment further, experimental apparatus, measurement, control of conditions, and mathematical expression had to become learnable work. What remained at the scene was not only an experimental setup, but the transformation of apparatus, measurement, condition control, and mathematical expression from personal experience into transmissible training.\n\nThis person was Galileo Galilei, whose work on falling bodies, inclined planes, and astronomical observation helped push modern physical science and experimental method. When students repeat such actions in a laboratory, they learn not only formulas, but how to let nature answer in a way that can be checked.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Physics and related physical sciences connect observation, experiment, measurement, and mathematical description to explain matter, motion, and energy.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "What familiar motion would change meaning if you slowed it down enough to measure it?"
  },
  "054-shared-bill-pattern": {
    "title": "Strange Numerals in an Arithmetic Book",
    "summary": "A book on calculation helped mathematics and statistics move from local tricks toward a shareable symbolic system.",
    "scene": "In ninth-century Baghdad, a scholar near the House of Wisdom organized Indian numerals, equations, and practical calculation problems.",
    "storyBody": "He was not facing a pure game. He was facing real calculations in inheritance, trade, measurement, taxation, and land division. Older methods could calculate, but they were not unified enough, and they did not travel easily.\n\nHe introduced Indian numerals and decimal calculation to Arabic readers, and he systematically discussed methods for solving linear and quadratic equations. The basic meaning of mathematics and statistics becomes clear here: once symbols can be written, taught, and reused, complex relations can leave one person's mind and become a shared social tool.\n\nTreating calculation or numbers as techniques that produce answers still had its use. But to carry judgment further, symbols, proof, data collection, models, and judgment about error had to become learnable work.\n\nLater courses would give the field a name. At the time, the more urgent task was to make symbols, proof, data collection, models, and judgment about error into repeatable practices. This person was Muhammad ibn Musa al-Khwarizmi, whose algebraic writing and works on Indian numerals shaped the later history of concepts such as algebra and algorithm.\n\nCountless classrooms, ledgers, and programs would continue along this road: once a relation is written clearly, more people can check it, improve it, and use it together. What remained later was not only a field name; what had been forced into shape was a body of work around symbols, proof, data collection, models, and judgment about error.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Mathematics and statistics use symbols, procedures, comparison, and proof to make quantity and pattern shareable and checkable.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "When a method becomes easy to write and teach, who gains access to problems that once belonged only to specialists?"
  },
  "058-school-air-quality": {
    "title": "A Ruler Hidden in Starlight",
    "summary": "A person comparing star brightness on photographic plates connected astronomy, mathematics, and statistics into a way to measure cosmic distance.",
    "scene": "At the Harvard College Observatory in the early twentieth century, a woman computer sat before rows of glass plates and compared the brightness of variable stars one by one.",
    "storyBody": "Her job title was not grand. Many women computers were assigned repetitive and delicate recording work. But among the variable stars in the Magellanic Clouds, she found a relation: for certain Cepheid variables, the longer the period of variation, the greater the true brightness.\n\nThat relation worked like a cosmic ruler. If the period was known, brightness could be inferred; from there, distance could be estimated. Natural science, mathematics, and statistics were fully intertwined here: astronomical observation provided the material, mathematical relation organized the pattern, and statistical comparison let the regularity appear.\n\nHer finding later helped human beings measure distances beyond the Milky Way. The trouble is that a hard problem often needs observation, quantitative relation, and cross-disciplinary explanation at the same time.\n\nOnce that trouble is recorded seriously, the starting point of the field is no longer a name, but the question of how measurement, model, and natural evidence can be joined into one judgment. This is not a decorative origin story for interdisciplinary natural science, mathematics, and statistics. It shows how cross-field data, models, diagrams, and verification first held the problem up.\n\nThis person was Henrietta Swan Leavitt, who found the Cepheid period-luminosity relation, a major basis for the modern cosmic distance scale. That is also what is most moving when data and natural science meet: tiny records do not speak automatically, but patient comparison can turn them into a scale.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Statistics helps turn repeated observations into patterns that can support measurement, inference, and comparison beyond what can be seen directly.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "What repeated change might become a ruler if someone recorded it carefully enough?"
  },
  "059-mystery-stain": {
    "title": "How Long Is the Coastline?",
    "summary": "A question about a coastline opened a new rough scale between nature, mathematics, and statistics.",
    "scene": "In the mid-twentieth century, a mathematician stared at a coastline on a map and found that the shorter the ruler, the longer the measured length became.",
    "storyBody": "Traditional geometry liked smooth lines, but the real world's clouds, mountains, trees, rivers, and coasts were not so obedient. Measured with a large ruler, many curves were ignored.\n\nMeasured with a small ruler, details kept appearing, and the length seemed to have no stable endpoint. He developed this kind of rough, repeated, self-similar shape into a new mathematical language.\n\nThis direction was not ordinary geometry, but it was not only physics or statistics either. It helped people describe many irregular forms in nature. Natural science, mathematics, and statistics outside a single category are the right place for such boundary problems: classification has not yet caught up with the phenomenon, but the phenomenon is already demanding new tools.\n\nThe pressure is that roughness, scale, and mixed phenomena keep escaping a single field. This person was Benoit Mandelbrot, who developed fractal geometry and made fractals a major mathematical language for understanding natural forms, complex systems, and problems of scale.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Mathematical and statistical thinking can reveal how scale, measurement choices, and irregular patterns shape what a number means.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "When you hear a precise number, do you also ask what ruler made it precise?"
  },
  "068-repairing-the-club-website": {
    "title": "Why the Anti-Aircraft Gun Lagged",
    "summary": "A problem of control and feedback connected computing, engineering, biology, and communication into a new interdisciplinary language.",
    "scene": "During the Second World War in the 1940s, a mathematician studied how anti-aircraft guns could predict aircraft positions and found that machines had to keep correcting themselves from error.",
    "storyBody": "What he saw was not a single engineering problem. Radar provided information, the gun turret had to move, the target was moving, and the system had to adjust according to feedback from error.\n\nSimilar processes also appeared in the nervous system, animal movement, communication networks, and automatic control. So he began to think of control and communication as one shared problem, developing a language of feedback, information, and system regulation.\n\nThe interdisciplinary meaning of ICT appears here: computing is not only computers, communication is not only wires, and control is not only machines. Life, technology, and organizations may share similar structures. But the details in this scene remind researchers that symbols, noise, structure, and user error can expose problems inside a black box.\n\nThe question shifts its center: how should information be represented, organized, transmitted, and executed so that it is reliable and maintainable, instead of treating anomalies as exceptions to discard? Before the name became fixed, coding, structure, interfaces, permissions, testing, and recovery paths had already connected the scene to judgment.\n\nThis person was Norbert Wiener, who founded cybernetics and made control, communication, feedback, and systems thinking a major foundation for information technology, automation, and interdisciplinary research.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Feedback thinking connects systems that sense, compare, correct, and communicate across technical and living processes.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "Where in your life does a delay make correction harder than the original action?"
  },
  "071-flickering-hall-light": {
    "title": "Why a Roof Cannot Be Beautiful Only on Paper",
    "summary": "An engineer working inside complex buildings showed that engineering is not added after architecture, but thinks with form from the start.",
    "scene": "In twentieth-century Sydney, the shell roof of an opera house drew the architect, government, and engineering team into the same difficulty.",
    "storyBody": "He was not facing an ordinary calculation exercise. The architectural form was bold, budgets and political pressure kept increasing, and the original curved surfaces were difficult to manufacture and support.\n\nThe engineering team had to recombine aesthetic ambition, geometric rules, prefabricated components, load paths, and construction methods until the shells could be divided, manufactured, and installed. The process was not perfect and came with disputes, but it showed that the core of engineering work is not simply building according to drawings.\n\nReal engineering translates between desire and reality: which shapes can be built, which materials can bear them, and which steps can reduce danger. The pressure at the site is that materials, loads, processes, and long-term use will push weaknesses back into view.\n\nEngineering and engineering trades would later have courses and institutions. In this scene, they first unfolded close to materials testing, process control, structural calculation, and safety boundaries.\n\nThis person was Ove Arup, who led the engineering work for the Sydney Opera House and helped shape modern practice in deep collaboration between structural engineering and architectural design. Any bold design that becomes real still goes through a similar translation: desire has to be broken down into materials, budget, schedule, responsibility, and safety boundaries that can be tested.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Engineering links design, materials, structure, calculation, construction, safety, and long-term use under real constraints.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "When an idea looks beautiful on paper, what must the material still be allowed to say?"
  },
  "072-soup-that-travels": {
    "title": "When the Car Chassis Came to the Worker",
    "summary": "A moving assembly line shifted manufacturing from workshop craft toward rhythm, standardization, and mass production.",
    "scene": "In a Detroit factory in 1913, the automobile chassis no longer waited silently for workers to gather around it, but moved slowly along a line.",
    "storyBody": "The problem he wanted to solve was not whether a single automobile could be built. It was how more people could afford one, and how every step of the work could be repeated steadily. The assembly line broke tasks into smaller pieces, standardized parts, fixed the rhythm, and also pulled workers' movements into a strict process.\n\nThe method raised output and lowered costs, while also bringing monotony, control, and pressure on workers. Manufacturing and processing became modern here: a product is not decided only by technical invention, but by process, time, supply chains, worker skill, and management systems together.\n\nThis was not a moment when old methods completely failed. Treating a drawing, a formula, or one success as completion could still let people act at first.\n\nWhat pressed against that habit was the fact that materials, loads, processes, and long-term use would push weaknesses back into the field. When this blockage kept returning, the new question became: how can design still stand under scale, risk, and maintenance?\n\nThis person was Henry Ford, who promoted the moving assembly line at the Highland Park factory and made automobile mass production a major model for twentieth-century manufacturing. Looking at a production line today, one cannot look only at output. One also has to ask how rhythm changes labour, quality, price, and the relation between people and machines.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Manufacturing studies how materials, tools, labour, rhythm, standards, and process design turn ideas into repeatable products.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "When work becomes faster through a system, what happens to the people whose movements become part of that system?"
  },
  "073-crosswalk-at-school": {
    "title": "A Building Must Stand, Work, and Move the Eye",
    "summary": "An old book on architecture joined structure, function, and beauty into a lasting problem for architecture and construction.",
    "scene": "Around the first century BCE in ancient Rome, an architect and engineer reviewed temples, aqueducts, machines, and urban spaces, trying to write building experience for those who would come later.",
    "storyBody": "He did not see architecture only as walls and roofs, and he did not treat beauty as surface decoration. A building had to be strong, had to serve human use, and had to carry the beauty that comes from proportion and order.\n\nMaterials, foundations, orientation, public use, machines, and the scale of the human body were all placed inside the same way of thinking. The basic problem of architecture and construction was named early here: building is not piling things up. It is a durable arrangement among safety, use, technology, climate, bodies, and culture.\n\nThis was not a moment when old methods completely failed. Treating a drawing, formula, or one success as completion could still let people act at first.\n\nWhat pressed against that habit was the fact that materials, loads, processes, and long-term use would push weaknesses back into the field. When that blockage returned, the new question became: how can design still stand under scale, risk, and maintenance?\n\nWhat later became learnable was precisely materials testing, process control, structural calculation, and safety boundaries. They made it unnecessary for every similar site to start over from scratch. This person was Vitruvius, whose De architectura proposed ideas such as firmitas, utilitas, and venustas, deeply shaping architectural theory and education. What students of architecture really practice is the ability to see structure, users, and city life at the same time.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Architecture and construction connect structure, function, material, use, proportion, safety, and human experience.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "Which part of a building fails first if strength, usefulness, and beauty stop speaking to each other?"
  },
  "078-community-kitchen-build": {
    "title": "Can a Dome Use Less Material?",
    "summary": "A geometric dome connected engineering, manufacturing, architecture, and resource use into one experiment.",
    "scene": "In twentieth-century America, a man who loved drawing structural lines and maps kept asking how to cover more space with less material.",
    "storyBody": "He was not only trying to make a strange shape. He was fascinated by efficiency: how tension is distributed, why triangles are stable, how a spherical structure spreads weight, and whether temporary housing and large spaces could be lighter, faster, and cheaper. The geodesic dome placed mathematical geometry, structural engineering, manufacturing joints, architectural space, and resource ethics together.\n\nIt was not a universal answer. Actual use brought problems of waterproofing, maintenance, comfort, and cost. But the value of interdisciplinary engineering appears exactly there: one shape requires geometry, materials, construction, habitation, and social ideals to be tested together.\n\nThis was not a moment when old methods completely failed. Treating a drawing, a formula, or one success as completion could still let people act at first.\n\nWhat pressed against that habit was the fact that materials, loads, processes, and long-term use would push weaknesses back into the field. When that blockage returned again and again, the new question became: how can design still stand under scale, risk, and maintenance?\n\nWhat later became learnable was materials testing, process control, structural calculation, and safety boundaries. They made it unnecessary for every similar site to start over from scratch. This person was Buckminster Fuller, who promoted the geodesic dome and influenced engineering, architecture, and design education through systems design and the idea of doing more with less.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Engineering and architecture can use geometry, modular parts, structure, and resource constraints to turn material into usable space.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "When you need something stronger, do you add more material, or first ask how the parts are arranged?"
  },
  "079-unusual-repair-material": {
    "title": "The City System Behind the Smell",
    "summary": "An urban sewage project shows how uncategorized engineering often unfolds between public health, civil works, politics, and daily life.",
    "scene": "In the London summer of 1858, the stench of the Thames pushed into Parliament, and the city could no longer pretend that sewage was only a problem of smell.",
    "storyBody": "In the London summer of 1858, the stench from the Thames pushed into Parliament, and the city could no longer pretend that sewage was only a matter of smell.\n\nHe faced a systemic trouble made larger by urban growth: toilets, rivers, tides, disease, streets, budgets, political delay, and public fear were all tangled together. The answer was not to clear one ditch. It was to design intercepting sewers, pumping stations, and discharge systems that moved sewage away from the core of city life.\n\nWe can still ask where the pollution was moved and who paid the environmental cost. But the project did make the modern city recognize that infrastructure decides public health. Engineering, manufacturing, and construction that do not fit one neat category often happen at this boundary: civil engineering, sanitation, administration, politics, and urban life being reorganized at the same time.\n\nIf people stayed on the old path, treating a drawing, a formula, or one successful fix as completion could still make things appear to move forward. But materials, loads, and processes were not that obedient. Materials, loads, processes, and long-term use pushed weak points back into the field.\n\nSo the next step could not be only another explanation added after failure. It had to become materials testing, process control, structural calculation, and safety boundaries. This person was Joseph Bazalgette, who designed London's modern sewer system and became an important figure in the history of urban infrastructure and public-health engineering.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Engineering, manufacturing, and construction outside a single category handle complex projects that cross infrastructure, public health, materials, building work, and governance.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "Why is a city's most important engineering often considered successful only when you can no longer smell it or see it?"
  },
  "081-balcony-tomato-plan": {
    "title": "Seeds Were No Longer Scattered by Hand",
    "summary": "A seed drill moved farming from experience-based scattering toward systematic control of spacing, depth, and efficiency.",
    "scene": "In an eighteenth-century English field, a farmer saw seed being scattered by hand, with much eaten by birds and much falling at the wrong depth.",
    "storyBody": "In an eighteenth-century English field, a farmer saw seed being scattered by hand. Much of it was eaten by birds. Much of it fell at the wrong depth.\n\nHe was not only trying to make a new machine. He was disturbed by the waste he saw on the land. If seed could enter the soil at a fixed depth and a fixed distance, it would be more likely to germinate, and later weeding and management would be easier.\n\nHe improved the seed drill and made sowing more orderly. Looking back, mechanization also raised new questions about uniformity and land management. But the story makes clear that the basic problem of agriculture was never as simple as throwing seed into the ground.\n\nIt involved tools, soil, timing, labour, and the precise arrangement of the conditions for life. This was not a moment when the old way had completely failed.\n\nSeeing land, crops, or animals first as a matter of output could still let people act. What pushed back was that soil, water, disease, behaviour, and season would carry the consequences into the next round.\n\nWhen that difficulty returned again and again, the new question became: which life conditions make results keep improving or keep getting worse? This person was Jethro Tull, who promoted the seed drill and row sowing, and became an important figure in the history of British agricultural improvement.\n\nAgricultural technology still circles the same question: how to raise efficiency without handing land, seed diversity, and human judgment over to a single tool.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Agriculture that is not further subdivided attends to land, crops, tools, labour, yield, and the long-term conditions of care.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "Does whether a seed germinates depend on luck, or on how people arrange its entrance into the soil?"
  },
  "082-fallen-branch-trail": {
    "title": "Forests Cannot Be Counted Only as Timber",
    "summary": "A forestry reformer moved forest management from cutting revenue toward long-term public resources and professional governance.",
    "scene": "In late nineteenth-century America, a young man returned from studying forestry in Europe and saw vast forests being governed by the logic of short-term cutting.",
    "storyBody": "In the late nineteenth-century United States, a young man returned after studying forestry in Europe and saw large forests being governed by the logic of short-term cutting.\n\nHe was not against using forests. He was against treating a forest as a one-time mine. Timber, water sources, soil, fire, wildlife, and local economies all needed long-term management.\n\nHe promoted professional forestry, national forests, and the idea of sustained yield, arguing that natural resources should be managed for the public interest. We should also criticize the ways early conservation often ignored Indigenous people and local communities. But a core problem of forestry as a discipline stands out here: the time scale of a forest is much longer than a business cycle.\n\nThe trouble was that soil, water, disease, behaviour, and season would carry consequences into the next round. Once that trouble was recorded seriously, the starting point of the field was no longer the name of the field, but the question of which life conditions make results keep improving or keep getting worse.\n\nThis person was Gifford Pinchot, an important American forestry reformer, the first chief of the U.S. Forest Service, and a major promoter of conservation forestry. The warning is still sharp in resource management: if you look only at immediate gain, a forest can grow shorter in the ledger and emptier in reality.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Forestry attends to forest resources, timber, ecology, water and soil conservation, fire risk, biodiversity, and long-term management.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "If a forest lives longer than several generations, who is qualified to make a short-term decision for it?"
  },
  "083-fish-market-morning": {
    "title": "Every Generation Thinks the Sea Was Always This Empty",
    "summary": "A fisheries scientist's warning showed how decline in ocean resources can be hidden by memory itself.",
    "scene": "In the late twentieth century, a fish researcher heard young fishers say the catch was still normal, yet found a very different ocean in old records.",
    "storyBody": "In the late twentieth century, a researcher of fish heard younger fishers say that the catch was still fairly normal. In older records, he saw a very different sea.\n\nHe recognized a danger: every generation treats the number of fish it saw in youth as normal. If the baseline keeps falling, people may continue to feel that things are acceptable inside a sea that has already grown poorer.\n\nHe proposed the idea of the shifting baseline, warning that fisheries cannot look only at this year and last year. They need a longer ecological memory. Fisheries research here is not only about how many fish are caught. It must also understand how populations, food webs, fishing pressure, policy, and human memory shape the ocean together.\n\nSeeing land, crops, or animals first as a matter of output still has its use. But to make judgment go further, field experiments, breeding, ecological care, and long-term management have to become learnable work.\n\nThis person was Daniel Pauly, who proposed shifting baseline syndrome and influenced modern fisheries science and ocean conservation through global fisheries data research. This is also why many environmental problems are hard to notice: loss does not always happen at once. It is slowly accepted through the habits of one normal generation after another.\n\nThe complete system would come later. At the beginning, the more important point was that the scene already forced people to fix field experiments, breeding, ecological care, and long-term management into practice bit by bit.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Fisheries attend to aquatic ecology, fish populations, harvesting, aquaculture, cold chains, policy, and food supply.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "Could the natural state you think is normal already be the result of decline in the generation before you?"
  },
  "084-dog-that-stopped-eating": {
    "title": "The Sick Horse at the First Veterinary School",
    "summary": "A livestock disease crisis moved veterinary knowledge from folk experience toward systematic education and public economic safety.",
    "scene": "In eighteenth-century France, repeated cattle and horse diseases caused heavy losses, and a person concerned with horsemanship and animal illness saw agriculture and the military both pulled into the problem.",
    "storyBody": "In eighteenth-century France, repeated diseases among cattle and horses caused heavy losses. A man concerned with horsemanship and animal disease saw agriculture and the army being pulled into the same problem.\n\nAn animal's illness did not affect only one owner. Horses mattered to transport and the army. Cattle mattered to ploughing, food, and family income.\n\nTraditional horse-doctoring had value, but it lacked systematic anatomy, pathology, teaching, and public disease prevention. He pushed for the establishment of specialized schools so that animal medicine could become a profession people could be trained in, study, and pass on.\n\nThe veterinary field appears clearly here. It cares for individual animals, but it also protects herds, food, agricultural economies, and the safety of human-animal life together. Yet the pressure in the field was that soil, water, disease, behaviour, and season would carry consequences into the next round.\n\nThis person was Claude Bourgelat, who founded a veterinary school in Lyon, one of the earliest modern veterinary schools in the world, and is regarded as an important founder of modern veterinary education. Veterinary work still stands at this crossing point: the health of one animal is often tied to food safety, public health, and the ethics of living with animals.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Veterinary medicine studies animal disease, diagnosis, treatment, public health, herd health, and the relationship between people and animals.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "When one animal becomes sick, is the impact only on that animal, or on the whole food and living system around it?"
  },
  "088-farm-visit-class": {
    "title": "She Saw the Shadow That Frightened the Cow",
    "summary": "An autistic woman designer brought animal behavior, engineering, livestock work, and welfare into one practice of field observation.",
    "scene": "In late twentieth-century ranches and slaughterhouses, a young woman stood beside livestock passages and noticed that cattle were frightened by reflections, shadows, and sudden turns.",
    "storyBody": "In late twentieth-century ranches and slaughterhouses, a young woman stood beside livestock passages and noticed that cattle were frightened by glare, shadows, and sudden turns.\n\nHer way of sensing the world was different from many people's, and it made her more able to notice an animal's fear in space. She did not simply blame the animals for being disobedient. She lowered herself toward their line of sight and looked at light, sound, floor texture, slipping, turns, and human movements.\n\nShe designed curved chutes and lower-stress handling systems, placing animal behaviour, engineering design, livestock production, and ethical care inside one practice. This interdisciplinary field does not only ask how to raise efficiency. It also asks how people can reduce fear and suffering while using animals.\n\nSeeing land, crops, or animals first as a matter of output still has its use. But to make judgment go further, field experiments, breeding, ecological care, and long-term management have to become learnable work.\n\nThis person was Temple Grandin, known for livestock facility design and animal-welfare advocacy, and for advancing interdisciplinary practice among agriculture, engineering, veterinary work, and animal behaviour. Students can learn from this that real expertise does not mean forcing a living system into obedience. It means being willing to recheck the design from the position of another body.\n\nWhat remained later was not only a field name. What the scene forced into being was a set of work around field experiments, breeding, ecological care, and long-term management.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Interdisciplinary agricultural, forestry, fisheries, and veterinary study connects production, ecology, engineering, animal health, welfare, and resource management.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "If you looked at a passage from an animal's point of view, would human efficiency also have to be redefined?"
  },
  "089-unusual-animal-garden": {
    "title": "Seeds Inside the Ice",
    "summary": "A global seed vault shows that agricultural knowledge can be genetic protection and future risk management at the same time.",
    "scene": "In the early twenty-first century on Norway's Svalbard archipelago, people carried seed samples from around the world into a vault inside a frozen mountain.",
    "storyBody": "In the early twenty-first century, on Norway's Svalbard archipelago, people sent seed samples from around the world into a vault inside a frozen mountain.\n\nThe project looked like a warehouse, but it was not only storage. Each seed sample represented a crop genetic resource. It also carried an agricultural memory from some region, and a possible adaptation for the future.\n\nWar, disaster, climate change, disease, and market uniformity can all make seed diversity disappear. Agriculture, forestry, fisheries, and veterinary work that does not fit a single category needs exactly this kind of boundary awareness. It is not simply planting, and not only research or diplomacy. It is a food system preserving choices for the future.\n\nYet the pressure in the field was that soil, water, disease, behaviour, and season would carry consequences into the next round. This person was Cary Fowler, who long promoted crop diversity conservation and, as one of the key advocates of the Svalbard Global Seed Vault, influenced the global preservation of plant genetic resources.\n\nAs climate and supply chains become unstable, this kind of preservation is not only a scientific project. It is also an arrangement of responsibility toward the future.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Agriculture, forestry, fisheries, and veterinary work outside a single category includes practices that cross genetic resources, food security, ecological risk, and long-term preservation.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "When people preserve a seed for the future, are they preserving food, or preserving the right to choose?"
  },
  "091-cough-in-the-waiting-room": {
    "title": "Observation Beside the Bed",
    "summary": "Ancient physicians pulled treatment away from mysterious explanation and toward observation, records, and professional ethics.",
    "scene": "Around the fifth century BCE, among Greek islands and city-states, a physician came close to patients with fever, pain, and difficult breathing, first watching how they actually changed.",
    "storyBody": "Around the fifth century BCE, among Greek islands and city-states, a physician came close to patients with fever, pain, and difficult breathing, and first watched how they actually changed.\n\nIn his time, illness was often explained as divine punishment or mysterious force. He and the companions in that tradition turned attention toward more concrete matters: when symptoms began, how pulse and breathing changed, how diet, season, place, and constitution were related, and how a physician should judge cautiously without harming the patient.\n\nMany texts were not all written by one person, and they carried the limits of their age. Still, an important turn in the field of health had appeared: caring for the body required observation, experience, records, and ethical restraint, not only magic or authority.\n\nThis was not a moment when the old way had completely failed. Reducing a health problem to one symptom, one treatment, or one act of aid could still let people act first.\n\nWhat pushed back was that bodily change is often tangled with environment, institutions, relationships of care, and dignity. When that difficulty returned again and again, the new question became: how can care be made reliable among risk, evidence, and a person's life?\n\nThe name could appear later. What came first were observations, diagnosis, care records, institutional support, and ethical judgment that had to be practiced repeatedly.\n\nThis person was Hippocrates. The Hippocratic tradition he represents became an important source for Western medical observation, clinical ethics, and the professional image of the physician. The earliest thing medical learning has to protect is this: first see the person as a changing body, then decide carefully how knowledge should intervene.\n\nThe complete system would come later. At the beginning, the more important point was that the scene already forced observation, diagnosis, care records, institutional support, and ethical judgment to be fixed into practice bit by bit.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Health that is not further subdivided attends to bodily condition, disease, prevention, care, risk, and health judgment.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "When someone says they feel unwell, is the most responsible first step to explain, or to observe?"
  },
  "092-key-under-the-mat": {
    "title": "A Report from Cradle to Grave",
    "summary": "A wartime report moved welfare from scattered relief toward social systems designed around risks across a whole life.",
    "scene": "In Britain in 1942, while the war was still going on, an economist placed poverty, disease, unemployment, and old age into the same report.",
    "storyBody": "In Britain in 1942, while the war was still going on, an economist placed poverty, disease, unemployment, and old age into the same report.\n\nHe was not facing one family's single difficulty. He was facing risks that appeared again and again in society: no work, sickness, old age, many children, and insufficient income. Older forms of relief were often scattered, humiliating, and unable to cover the different stages of a life.\n\nHe proposed a more systematic vision of social insurance and a welfare state, trying to fight the so-called five giants: want, disease, ignorance, squalor, and idleness. Welfare here was not charity. It was the way a modern society could share risk, protect a minimum level of security, and guard human dignity.\n\nThe trouble was that bodily change is often tangled with environment, institutions, relationships of care, and dignity. Once that trouble was recorded seriously, the starting point of the field was no longer its name, but the question of how to make reliable care among risk, evidence, and a person's life.\n\nThe word welfare could come later. Observation, diagnosis, care records, institutional support, and ethical judgment were already demanding a new training in the field. This person was William Beveridge. His 1942 Beveridge Report deeply influenced Britain's welfare state and modern systems of social security.\n\nArguments about welfare are still not only about money. They ask whether a society is willing to leave a structure that can catch someone when that person falls, becomes sick, grows old, or loses work.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Welfare that is not further subdivided attends to social support, risk sharing, dignity, care, and basic security for living.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "How does a society prove that it recognizes a person not only when that person succeeds?"
  },
  "098-after-discharge-plan": {
    "title": "Pain Is Not the Last Thing to Handle",
    "summary": "A doctor listening to terminal patients' total pain helped health and welfare rethink the end of care.",
    "scene": "In twentieth-century Britain, a woman who had worked as a nurse and social worker and later studied medicine sat beside dying patients and listened carefully as they spoke about pain and loneliness.",
    "storyBody": "In twentieth-century Britain, a woman who had worked as a nurse and social worker and later studied medicine sat beside dying patients and listened carefully as they spoke about pain and loneliness.\n\nShe found that the patient's suffering was not only inside the body. Pain, fear, family relationships, religious questions, economic pressure, and the feeling of being abandoned could pile together.\n\nIf medicine remembered care only after cure had failed, it was already too late. She proposed the understanding of total pain and built hospice care, placing symptom control, psychological support, family presence, social work, and dignity inside one system.\n\nThe interdisciplinary meaning of health and welfare is very clear here. A person is not a set of organs, and not a welfare form. Even at the end of life, a person still needs to be seen whole. This was not a moment when the old way had completely failed.\n\nReducing a health problem to one symptom, one treatment, or one act of aid could still let people act first. What pushed back was that bodily change is often tangled with environment, institutions, relationships of care, and dignity.\n\nWhen that difficulty returned again and again, the new question became: how can care be made reliable among risk, evidence, and a person's life? This person was Cicely Saunders. She founded St Christopher's Hospice and laid an important foundation for modern hospice and palliative care.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Interdisciplinary health and welfare study connects medicine, nursing, psychology, social support, family, and human dignity.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "When cure is no longer possible, how can care still protect a person's wholeness?"
  },
  "099-neighborhood-listening-chair": {
    "title": "She Brought Battlefield Care Back to Peace",
    "summary": "A wartime relief organizer opened a mixed space where health, welfare, disaster response, volunteers, and public emergency work meet.",
    "scene": "During the American Civil War in the 1860s, a woman worked near the battlefield distributing supplies, searching for the wounded, and carrying messages of life and death back to families.",
    "storyBody": "During the American Civil War in the 1860s, a woman worked near the battlefield distributing supplies, searching for the wounded, and carrying messages of life and death back to families.\n\nShe was not only doing temporary kindness. War showed her that care for the wounded, supply coordination, information about missing people, volunteer organization, and relief after disaster needed lasting institutions. Each crisis should not have to begin again from chaos.\n\nAfter the war, she continued to push for a more stable humanitarian relief organization, extending care from the battlefield to disaster, public emergency, and social support. Health and welfare that are not otherwise classified often stand at this boundary. They are not an ordinary hospital and not a single welfare agency. In crisis, they connect care, information, supplies, and organizational capacity.\n\nThis was not a moment when the old way had completely failed. Reducing a health problem to one symptom, one treatment, or one act of aid could still let people act first.\n\nWhat pushed back was that bodily change is often tangled with environment, institutions, relationships of care, and dignity. When that difficulty returned again and again, the new question became: how can care be made reliable among risk, evidence, and a person's life?\n\nThis is not a search for a beautiful origin for uncategorized health and welfare. It is a way to see how observation, diagnosis, care records, institutional support, and ethical judgment first held the problem up. This person was Clara Barton. She founded the American Red Cross and helped bring the United States into the international Red Cross humanitarian relief system.\n\nDisaster relief and community support still continue this line. Goodwill without training, records, and coordination can scatter when the emergency truly arrives. What remained later was not only a field name. What the scene forced into being was work around observation, diagnosis, care records, institutional support, and ethical judgment.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Health and welfare outside a single category handle support practices that cross medical care, relief, information, volunteer organization, and public emergency response.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "After a crisis, how can temporary goodwill become an institution that protects people faster next time?"
  },
  "101-haircut-before-wedding": {
    "title": "The Red Door of the Salon",
    "summary": "A woman entrepreneur turned personal service from private grooming into brand, training, and modern consumer experience.",
    "scene": "In early twentieth-century New York, a young woman learned skincare, sales, and customer communication in a beauty salon, and discovered that serving the body also served identity.",
    "storyBody": "In early twentieth-century New York, a young woman learned skin care, sales, and customer communication inside beauty salons, and discovered that serving the body also meant serving identity.\n\nShe understood that customers were not coming only to buy a jar of cream. They wanted to be received with care, to learn how to look after themselves, and to enter a new image of urban womanhood.\n\nShe built salons, trained salespeople, standardized products and service language, and organized personal service into a repeatable experience system. The process was also tangled with consumerism, class, and beauty pressure.\n\nBut it showed that personal service was not a lower-level side industry. It was a place where body, emotion, identity, trust, and business organization met. The pressure on the scene was that waiting, space, information, permission, and bodily feeling all determined whether a service could hold.\n\nOnly when process design, frontstage and backstage cooperation, physical evidence, and experience correction entered training did judgment in the field stop depending only on the intuition of a few individuals. This person was Elizabeth Arden. She built a global beauty brand and salon service system, deeply influencing modern personal care and the beauty-service industry.\n\nMany personal services work this way: they seem to handle appearance or small needs, while actually handling trust, identity, bodily boundaries, and the feeling of being respected. The complete system would come later. At the beginning, the more important point was that this scene had already forced process design, frontstage and backstage cooperation, physical evidence, and experience correction to become fixed little by little.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Personal services involve bodies, appearance, comfort, communication, identity, and service experiences close to everyday life.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "When a service touches the body directly, does it also touch a person's image of self?"
  },
  "102-clean-hands-station": {
    "title": "City Air, Sewage, and the Laboratory",
    "summary": "A hygienist institutionalized public health training, making hygiene a professional knowledge of cities and workplaces.",
    "scene": "In nineteenth-century German cities, dense population, sewage, and infectious disease made it impossible for medicine to remain only beside the sickbed.",
    "storyBody": "In nineteenth-century German cities, dense population, sewage, and infectious disease made it impossible for medicine to remain only at the bedside.\n\nHe cared about air, water, housing, sewage disposal, and the urban environment. He also built systems of experiment and teaching, so hygiene was not merely an everyday habit of cleanliness, but a public profession that could be researched, taught, and debated. Some of his theories were later corrected, especially after the development of germ theory.\n\nBut his effort to bring hygiene into universities, laboratories, and urban governance shows the basic meaning of hygiene and occupational health services: prevention must happen before disease appears. It happens in water, air, buildings, work, and institutions. The trouble was that waiting, space, information, permission, and bodily feeling determine whether a service can hold.\n\nOnce that trouble was recorded seriously, the starting point of the field was no longer its name, but the question of how the whole path lets people remain safe, clear, and truly seen. This is not a search for a beautiful origin for hygiene and occupational health services. It is a way to see how process design, frontstage and backstage cooperation, physical evidence, and experience correction first held the problem up.\n\nThis person was Max von Pettenkofer. He established the Munich tradition of hygiene research and is regarded as one of the important pioneers of modern hygiene and public-health education. Hygiene services still need this wide view. If air, water, waste, laboratories, and institutions are handled separately, risk returns through the cracks.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Hygiene and occupational health services that are not further subdivided attend to prevention, environment, workplaces, cleanliness, and group health conditions.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "Does health service begin after you fall ill, or has it already been working before illness appears?"
  },
  "103-night-watch-call": {
    "title": "Why Police Should Wear Uniforms",
    "summary": "An interior reformer moved security service from temporary repression toward visible and accountable public policing.",
    "scene": "On nineteenth-century London streets, rapid urban expansion, crime, poverty, crowding, and public fear made older forms of policing increasingly inadequate.",
    "storyBody": "On the streets of nineteenth-century London, rapid urban growth, crime, poverty, crowding, and public fear made older ways of keeping order feel less and less adequate.\n\nHe was not trying to solve one arrest. He was asking how a city could maintain public order without becoming a barracks. Older policing could press down disorder for a time and allow power to act quickly.\n\nIts limits became clear on London streets: poverty, crowding, gaps in patrol, and public fear kept returning, and temporary repression did not easily become long-term trust. The new police needed recognizable uniforms, regular patrol, discipline, a principle of prevention, and public cooperation.\n\nThe uniform was not for show. It made power on the street identifiable, and therefore easier to question. The problem changed from how to catch bad people to how the power that protects the public can itself be constrained by rules, transparency, and responsibility.\n\nThe system would later still carry disputes about class control, abuse of power, and oversight, and must be viewed critically. But one origin problem of security service had already appeared: protection cannot rely only on force. It also needs recognizable duty, limited authority, training, and public trust.\n\nThis person was Robert Peel. He founded the London Metropolitan Police and made modern principles of public policing an important starting point in the history of security services. This does not make the police automatically legitimate.\n\nOn the contrary, uniforms and patrols place power in public view and bring the duty of supervision into the institution. Only when the public can recognize, complain, question, and expect consistent rules does public order stop being mere repression and begin to approach a public service.\n\nIn this way, safety first became more clearly subject to the reverse inspection of public rules.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Security services that are not further subdivided attend to risk recognition, prevention, response, order, trust, and limits on power.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "How can a security system protect people without letting the power of protection lose its boundaries?"
  },
  "104-missed-connection": {
    "title": "Why a Subway Line Can Bend on a Map",
    "summary": "A subway map shifted transport service from true distance toward whether passengers can make quick decisions.",
    "scene": "In 1930s London, an engineering draftsman looked at the complex Underground lines and found that maps drawn by real geography were difficult for passengers to read.",
    "storyBody": "In London in the 1930s, an engineering draughtsman looked at the complicated Underground lines and noticed that maps drawn according to real geography were hard for passengers to read.\n\nHe boldly gave up exact distance. He drew lines as horizontal, vertical, or at forty-five degrees, simplified the spacing between stations, and made transfer relationships clear. At first, the diagram did not fit the traditional intuition of a map. But it fit the real needs of passengers inside a transport system: where am I, where do I change, and how do I go to the next stop?\n\nTransport service here was not only the movement of vehicles. It also included information design, promises about time, accessibility, and human judgment under pressure. If a system cannot be understood, then even when it runs on time, it can still leave people lost.\n\nSeeing service as the completion of one reception, one act of protection, one trip, or one response still has its use. But to make judgment go further, process design, frontstage and backstage cooperation, physical evidence, and experience correction have to become learnable work.\n\nThis person was Harry Beck. He designed the London Underground diagram, a classic case in modern transport information design and service experience. Transport systems still work this way: what is truly usable is not only that the vehicle moves, but that people can still make clear choices when they are hurried, unfamiliar with the place, and under pressure.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Transport services attend to the movement of people and goods, transfers, reliability, information design, safety, and time coordination.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "Is a transport system truly usable because the route is short, or because people can understand it under pressure?"
  },
  "108-festival-operations-plan": {
    "title": "The Invisible Work Behind a Service Blueprint",
    "summary": "A marketing scholar split service into frontstage, backstage, and evidence so interdisciplinary service could be designed and improved.",
    "scene": "In the 1980s, a researcher observed service sites and found that customers saw only the part of the whole system that rose above the surface.",
    "storyBody": "In the 1980s, a researcher observed service scenes and noticed that what customers saw was only the part of the whole system above the waterline.\n\nA hotel check-in, bank account opening, or repair appointment looked like a few lines of conversation. Behind it were forms, systems, training, inventory, authorization, waiting time, and failure recovery. She proposed the service blueprint, drawing customer actions, frontstage contact, backstage processes, and physical evidence together.\n\nWith this, service was no longer only a matter of whether someone's attitude was good. It became a system that could be analyzed, designed, and coordinated across departments. The meaning of interdisciplinary service study also became clear: operations, psychology, space, information, people, and technology all had to work at the same time.\n\nThis was not a moment when the old way had completely failed. Seeing service as the completion of one reception, one act of protection, one trip, or one response could still let people act first.\n\nWhat pushed back was that waiting, space, information, permission, and bodily feeling determine whether service can hold. When that difficulty returned again and again, the new question became: how does the whole path make people safe, clear, and truly seen?\n\nThis person was G. Lynn Shostack. She proposed service blueprinting, which became an important methodological source in service design and service marketing.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Interdisciplinary service study connects operations, experience, personnel, space, information, technology, and quality management.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "When a service fails, is the problem really the person at the front, or was it already buried in the blueprint?"
  },
  "109-service-that-had-no-name": {
    "title": "Do Not Rush to Advise on the Phone",
    "summary": "A listening hotline shows that some services matter most because they hold a person before any formal category is ready.",
    "scene": "In 1950s London, a pastor read in the newspaper about young people driven toward despair by isolation and shame, and began imagining a telephone line anyone could call.",
    "storyBody": "In London in the 1950s, a pastor read in the newspaper about young people driven toward despair by isolation and shame, and began to imagine a telephone line that anyone could call.\n\nHe found that many people could not first walk into a hospital, police station, welfare agency, or church. They might need only someone who would not judge them, would not rush to lecture them, and would be willing to listen through the night.\n\nVolunteers were trained to answer calls. The main point was not to give an answer immediately, but to keep the caller from bearing the most dangerous and lonely moment alone. Such a service was hard to classify. It was not ordinary medicine, not formal counselling, not security, and not domestic service.\n\nBut it held open a narrow passage among many systems. Services that are not otherwise classified need room for this kind of apparently nameless but crucial support.\n\nThe pressure in the scene was that waiting, space, information, permission, and bodily feeling determine whether service can hold. This person was Chad Varah. He founded Samaritans, making crisis listening hotlines an important form of modern volunteer service and emotional support.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Services outside a single category include practical roles that cross medical care, counselling, community, volunteering, and immediate support.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "If a service only listens until you finish speaking, why might it still change the ending of a night?"
  },
  "0111-education-science": {
    "title": "The Small Chairs Children Moved Themselves",
    "summary": "Small chairs in an ordinary apartment helped education move from commanding children to observing how learning happens.",
    "scene": "In 1907, in an ordinary apartment building in San Lorenzo, Rome, a group of children left unsupervised during the day were brought into a new classroom.",
    "storyBody": "In 1907, inside an ordinary apartment building in Rome's San Lorenzo district, a group of children who had no one to care for them during the day were brought into a new classroom.\n\nThe woman doctor who took over the classroom had not, when young, treated becoming a teacher as her only path. She first studied engineering, later turned to medicine, and entered a medical school that very few women could enter at the time.\n\nWhile working in hospitals and psychiatric institutions, she saw that some children considered unable to learn had actually gone for a long time without an environment suited to their hands, senses, and attempts. When she came to this apartment classroom, she did not rush to arrange the children in neat rows.\n\nSmall chairs, small tables, a stove, and some materials locked in a cabinet were there. Some children wiped tables. Some cared for the little garden. Some repeatedly touched a letter board. She stood nearby and watched: which material a child would pick up, when they could stay quiet for a long time, and when an adult interruption scattered learning instead.\n\nShe gradually discovered that children were not empty cups waiting to be filled. The height of tables and chairs, the sequence of materials, whether the body could move freely, and whether adults were willing to observe first all changed the way learning happened.\n\nThe details left by this scene remind researchers that children, materials, and situations keep changing how learning occurs. The question shifted its center: how can we observe learning conditions and then design an environment where understanding can happen, instead of throwing unusual cases away as exceptions?\n\nThis person was Maria Montessori. She opened the Casa dei Bambini in Rome and developed Montessori education, making observation of children, prepared environments, and respect for developmental rhythm important threads in education science.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Education science uses observation, evidence, and design to study how learning happens, not only to prescribe how others should learn.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "If a child has not entered learning, do you first demand more effort, or first examine whether the environment gives the child a path into learning?"
  },
  "0112-training-for-pre-school-teachers": {
    "title": "The Wooden Ball Rolled Toward the Child",
    "summary": "A wooden ball moved early childhood education from watching children toward understanding play, materials, and development.",
    "scene": "In 1837, in a small house in Bad Blankenburg, Germany, an educator placed wooden balls, blocks, paper pieces, and garden activities in front of children.",
    "storyBody": "In 1837, in a small house in Bad Blankenburg, Germany, an educator placed wooden balls, blocks, paper pieces, and garden activities in front of children.\n\nMany adults saw children playing and thought it was only amusement. This educator did not hurry to pull them back to so-called serious learning.\n\nHe saw one child grasp a wooden ball and roll it away. Another child stacked blocks, knocked them down, and began again.\n\nAnother child threaded string through paper, as if slowly using the fingers to understand shape, direction, and order. He stopped and watched a little longer than other people did.\n\nWhen young, he had not moved straight from school into school. He had encountered nature, minerals, architecture, and measurement, and had also studied ideas about children's education.\n\nPerhaps for that reason, when he looked at young children, he did not see only immature children. He saw body, material, space, and rhythm working together. The question began to change: were children really only playing?\n\nOr were they using hands, eyes, voices, and bodies to practice understanding the world? Later, he began to design a set of materials and activities so that children could sense shape, number, relation, and nature through play, while the adults caring for them could learn how to accompany rather than interrupt.\n\nSeeing education as adults handing content to students still has its use. But to make judgment go further, observation records, environment design, developmental judgment, and teaching reflection have to become learnable work.\n\nWhat remained at the scene was not only that observation records, environment design, developmental judgment, and teaching reflection moved from personal experience into transmissible training. Many years later, when people looked back to the beginning of kindergarten, they often mentioned this name: Friedrich Froebel.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Training for preschool teachers attends to early childhood development, care, safety, play, early learning, and how adults accompany children into the world.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "When a child is playing, do you see amusement, or a kind of learning that needs to be understood and guided?"
  },
  "0113-teacher-training-without-subject-specialisation": {
    "title": "The Teacher School with Only Three Students",
    "summary": "A teacher school that began with only a few students shifted teaching from knowing content toward training teachers themselves.",
    "scene": "In July 1839, when a new school opened in Lexington, Massachusetts, the first group of students was so small that it hardly looked like a school.",
    "storyBody": "In July 1839, when a new school opened in Lexington, Massachusetts, its first group of students was so small that it hardly looked like a school.\n\nThe school's first leader had long worked between schools and churches. He had run a school on an island and had served as a minister. He had seen too many small troubles in real classrooms: children lost focus, became afraid, moved at different speeds, and a class could fall into disorder because one problem had not been explained clearly.\n\nAt the time, many people assumed that if a person could read, calculate, and behave morally, that person could naturally become a teacher. But he increasingly understood that a teacher was not someone who simply stood temporarily at the front of a room. A teacher had to learn how to ask questions, how to arrange a lesson, how to observe whether students had really understood, and how to make discipline not fear, but an order in which learning could continue.\n\nThe first students were few, and that made the experiment feel even more like a quiet question: do teachers also need to be trained systematically? If people stayed on the old path and treated education as adults handing content to students, things could appear to continue.\n\nBut materials and pauses in learning were not that obedient. Children, materials, and situations keep changing how learning happens. So the next step could not be only another explanation added afterward. It had to develop observation records, environment design, developmental judgment, and teaching reflection.\n\nThis person was Cyrus Peirce. Invited by Horace Mann, he led the Lexington normal school, helping teacher training without subject specialization shift from knowledgeable people going to teach toward teachers themselves needing training.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Teacher training without subject specialization trains general teaching ability, classroom organization, observation of learning, feedback, communication, and understanding of child development.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "What teaching ability belongs to no single subject, yet decides whether every subject can happen?"
  },
  "0114-teacher-training-with-subject-specialisation": {
    "title": "The Professor Brought Higher Mathematics Back to School",
    "summary": "Felix Klein showed that subject teachers need to translate disciplinary depth into paths students can enter.",
    "scene": "In early twentieth-century Gottingen, a professor of mathematics noticed that secondary-school mathematics teachers often stood between two bridges: university mathematics on one side, and the problem directly before students on the other.",
    "storyBody": "In early twentieth-century Göttingen, a professor of mathematics noticed that secondary-school mathematics teachers often stood between two bridges: university mathematics on one side, and the problem directly in front of students on the other.\n\nThis mathematician had already become famous in geometry when he was young. Later, in Göttingen, he organized lectures, seminars, and research institutions. The deeper he moved into university mathematics, the more he felt that school mathematics should not be only chopped-up formulas.\n\nA function, a curve, or a proof may feel natural to an expert and still look like a wall to a student. A teacher who can only solve harder problems may not necessarily be able to teach students.\n\nBut if teachers can see the structure, connections, and origins behind school mathematics, they can translate abstract knowledge into a path students can enter step by step. So he brought the idea of elementary mathematics from a higher standpoint to teachers, not to show off difficulty, but to let disciplinary depth return to the classroom.\n\nThe trouble was that children, materials, and situations keep changing how learning happens. Once that trouble was recorded seriously, the starting point of the field was no longer its name, but how to observe learning conditions and then design an environment where understanding can happen.\n\nThis person was Felix Klein. He advanced mathematics teacher education and international reform in mathematics education, helping subject-specialized teacher training recognize that a teacher must know the answer and also know how students reach it.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Subject-specialized teacher training combines deep disciplinary understanding with teaching methods, so teachers know how to teach a subject to people entering it for the first time.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "What kind of knowledge lies between understanding a subject and helping someone else learn it?"
  },
  "0119-education-not-elsewhere-classified": {
    "title": "Workers Wrote Their Own Words on the Board",
    "summary": "The night school in Angicos made education not only a literacy technique but an entrance into renaming life and entering society.",
    "scene": "On a night in Angicos, Brazil, in 1963, sugarcane workers sat in a literacy class after work, and the blackboard held not strange sample sentences but words from their own lives.",
    "storyBody": "In 1963, at night in Angicos, Brazil, sugarcane workers sat in a literacy class after work. The words on the blackboard were not strange textbook sentences. They were words from their own lives.\n\nThis educator had experienced poverty and hunger as a child. He later recalled that sometimes a person did not fail to learn because he was stupid, but because living conditions had pressed attention and dignity too low. As an adult, he first taught language, then worked in adult education, and increasingly distrusted classrooms that treated students as empty cans.\n\nTraditional literacy lessons often began with textbook sentences, as if the world had first been shut outside the door. He did the reverse: first listen to what people usually said, what words appeared in their work, what they feared, and what they wanted to change. Then these words became the entrance into literacy and discussion.\n\nWhile learning letters, people also began discussing land, labour, rights, and silence. Literacy was no longer only a technique. It became the ability to speak one's own life again.\n\nThe trouble was that children, materials, and situations keep changing how learning happens. Once that trouble was recorded seriously, the starting point of the field was no longer its name, but how to observe learning conditions and then design an environment where understanding can happen.\n\nBefore the name became fixed, observation records, environment design, developmental judgment, and teaching reflection had already connected the scene to judgment. This person was Paulo Freire. Through the Angicos adult literacy work and Pedagogy of the Oppressed, he influenced adult education, critical pedagogy, and community learning.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Education outside a single category holds forms of education that truly support learning but do not fit standard school, curriculum, or subject labels.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "What learning happens outside formal courses, yet truly changes how a person sees the world?"
  },
  "0211-audio-visual-techniques-and-media-production": {
    "title": "Workers Leaving the Factory Gate",
    "summary": "An ordinary image at a factory gate helped film move from technical experiment into collective viewing experience.",
    "scene": "In 1895, at the gate of a French photographic equipment factory, workers left after work, in a scene so ordinary that it hardly looked like a major event.",
    "storyBody": "In 1895, at the gate of a photographic equipment factory in France, workers left after work. The scene was so ordinary that it almost did not look like a major event.\n\nThe two brothers had grown up inside the photographic industry. Their family made photosensitive materials and photographic equipment. They were not trying, at the beginning, to make grand films. There were no stars, no elaborate plot, and no huge set.\n\nWhat shook people was a small technical question: how could continuous photographs be captured, developed, projected, and shown to a group of strangers at the same time, so that they could see time moving? They connected machine, film, projection, and public viewing, and made ordinary scenes such as workers leaving a factory, a train arriving, and a baby eating suddenly carry new force.\n\nViewers were not only looking at images. In a dark room, they experienced movement, time, and attention together. Audio-visual technique became clear here: technology is not cold equipment. It changes how people remember something, believe something, and watch something together.\n\nThe trouble was that gestures, materials, sounds, and memories cross these boxes and answer one another. Once that trouble was recorded seriously, the starting point of the field was no longer its name, but how works produce meaning while carrying historical experience, bodily feeling, and ways of seeing.\n\nThis is not a search for a beautiful origin for audio-visual techniques and media production. It is a way to see how close reading, comparison, material analysis, and interpretive traditions first held the problem up. These people were Auguste Lumiere and Louis Lumiere. They improved and promoted the cinematograph, and their projection practice in 1895 became a key starting point in the history of film and audio-visual media.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Audio-visual techniques and media production attend to image, sound, editing, devices, circulation, and how technology helps create perceivable reality.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "When an ordinary instant is recorded by a machine, is it still the same instant?"
  },
  "0212-fashion-interior-and-industrial-design": {
    "title": "Wild Plants on the Wallpaper",
    "summary": "A plant pattern on wallpaper made design more than decoration: it became a question about labour, living, and dignity.",
    "scene": "In nineteenth-century Britain, a young man who loved poetry and medieval stories entered rooms of the industrial age and kept feeling that everyday objects were losing the human hand.",
    "storyBody": "In nineteenth-century Britain, a young man who loved poetry and medieval stories walked into rooms of the industrial age and kept feeling that everyday objects were losing the human hand.\n\nHe was not simply opposed to machines. He opposed the rough cutting apart of the relationship between people and things. Beauty should not belong only to galleries. Tablecloths, wallpaper, chairs, pages, curtains, and the proportions of a room also shape how a person lives.\n\nSo he began studying dyes, textiles, carpentry, printing, and pattern. He let plant branches and leaves climb back onto walls, and let the rhythm of handwork return inside the home. His ideal carried contradictions: handmade goods were often expensive and could not necessarily be bought by ordinary people.\n\nBut the question he raised remains sharp: if the objects of daily life have no dignity, how can people learn beauty and freedom in everyday life? Design here was no longer only about looking good. It asked about the relation among materials, labour, users, and social ideals.\n\nThe pressure in the scene was that gestures, materials, sounds, and memories cross these boxes and answer one another. The name could appear later.\n\nWhat came first were close reading, comparison, material analysis, and interpretive traditions that had to be practiced again and again. This person was William Morris. As one of the central figures of the Arts and Crafts movement, he influenced modern ideas of interior and industrial design through furniture, wallpaper, textiles, and book design.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Fashion, interior, and industrial design place body, space, materials, function, production, and aesthetics inside one question.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "Are the things you use every day only manufactured, or have they also been carefully understood?"
  },
  "0213-fine-arts": {
    "title": "Why the Apple Would Not Stay Still",
    "summary": "An apple studied again and again moved fine art from representing the world toward studying perception itself.",
    "scene": "In late nineteenth-century southern France, the son of a banking family returned again and again to the canvas, staring at apples, tablecloths, and a mountain.",
    "storyBody": "In southern France in the late nineteenth century, the son of a banking family returned to the canvas again and again, staring at apples, tablecloths, and a mountain.\n\nHe had been coldly received in Paris and rejected by the exhibition system for a long time. When other people painted apples, they might aim for likeness.\n\nWhen he painted apples, it was as if he were asking why vision itself would not stay steady. The tabletop tilted slightly, the plate seemed about to slide, blocks of colour pushed against one another, and the mountain became structure in the light.\n\nMany people at first did not understand. They thought the paintings were clumsy, incomplete, and not pleasing enough. But he gradually let later artists see that painting did not have to only copy the object in front of the eye. It could take seeing apart and reorganize it into form, colour, weight, and time.\n\nFine art here became an extremely honest training: what exactly have I seen, and by what method do I place it on the canvas?\n\nIf people stayed on the old path, arranging works by author, period, style, or type could still make things appear to continue. But images, sounds, and objects were not that obedient. Gestures, materials, sounds, and memories cross these boxes and answer one another.\n\nSo the next step could not be only another explanation added afterward. It had to develop close reading, comparison, material analysis, and interpretive traditions. This person was Paul Cezanne. Through still lifes, landscapes, and structured seeing, he influenced modern painting and was later regarded by artists as an important bridge toward modernism.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Fine arts train observation, composition, colour, materials, form, and the reinterpretation of the visible world.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "If you look at the same apple again and again, could it begin to unsettle your understanding of seeing?"
  },
  "0214-handicrafts": {
    "title": "An Unnamed Ceramic Bowl",
    "summary": "An unnamed ceramic bowl turned handicraft from a small skill into thought about material, labour, and everyday beauty.",
    "scene": "In early twentieth-century Japan, as cities modernized rapidly, a young thinker paused before Korean ceramics and ordinary folk objects.",
    "storyBody": "In the early twentieth century, as Japanese cities modernized rapidly, a young thinker stopped in front of Korean ceramics and ordinary folk objects.\n\nWhat he saw was not expensive antiques or court treasures, but bowls, plates, textiles, and wooden objects used by ordinary people. They were often unsigned, inexpensive, clear in purpose, and simple in shape, yet they carried a quiet force that could not be replaced by display.\n\nBetween industrialization and elite art, he began to defend these unnamed things. The beauty of handicraft was not only a performance of skill. It was something settled together by material, use, local tradition, and long repeated labour. This view still needs to be read critically, because folk craft can easily romanticize labourers.\n\nBut it at least reminds us that knowledge does not live only in the master's signature. It also lives in palms, kiln fire, tools, and the marks left by everyday use. The details of this scene remind researchers that gestures, materials, sounds, and memories cross these boxes and answer one another.\n\nThe question shifted its center: how does a work produce meaning while carrying historical experience, bodily feeling, and ways of seeing, instead of throwing unusual cases away as exceptions? What later became learnable was exactly close reading, comparison, material analysis, and interpretive traditions. They let the next similar scene avoid beginning again from scratch.\n\nThis person was Yanagi Soetsu. He proposed the idea of mingei and advanced the Japanese folk craft movement, making the handicrafts of ordinary people an important object of modern aesthetics and cultural study.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Handicrafts connect materials, touch, tradition, function, regional experience, and everyday beauty.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "Why might a bowl without an artist's signature still change the history of taste?"
  },
  "0215-music-and-performing-arts": {
    "title": "Why Actors Should Not Only Shout Toward the Audience",
    "summary": "An actor's dissatisfaction with hollow performance grew into a major method of modern actor training.",
    "scene": "In late nineteenth-century Moscow, a young man who loved the stage stood in the theatre and grew increasingly unable to bear exaggerated, hollow performances concerned only with showing off the voice.",
    "storyBody": "In Moscow in the late nineteenth century, a young man who loved the stage stood in the theatre and became increasingly unable to bear exaggerated, hollow performances that cared only about showing off the voice.\n\nHe did not come from poverty. His family had the means to let him encounter theatre. Precisely because of that, he saw early the most false parts of the stage. Actors stood near the front, waited for the prompter to feed them lines, and then threw the lines toward the audience in beautiful voices.\n\nCharacters did not truly listen to one another. So he began recording his own failures: when emotion was merely pretended, when the body moved before understanding, and when a character's goal allowed a performance to stop falling apart.\n\nHe treated the rehearsal room as a laboratory. Actors had to ask what they wanted in this moment, and practice attention, action, motive, and truthful exchange. Performing arts here were no longer only talent and voice. They became a set of inner actions that could be trained again and again.\n\nThis was not a moment when the old way had completely failed. Arranging works by author, period, style, or type could still let people act first.\n\nWhat pushed back was that gestures, materials, sounds, and memories cross these boxes and answer one another. When that difficulty returned again and again, the new question became: how does a work produce meaning while carrying historical experience, bodily feeling, and ways of seeing?\n\nA field does not begin with its name. It begins with practicable actions such as close reading, comparison, material analysis, and interpretive traditions. This person was Konstantin Stanislavski. He co-founded the Moscow Art Theatre and developed the Stanislavski system, which deeply influenced modern theatre and film acting training.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Music and performing arts attend to the relationships among sound, body, rhythm, role, live presence, training, and audience.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "When does a performance begin to feel like real life rather than a skilled display?"
  },
  "0219-arts-not-elsewhere-classified": {
    "title": "The Urinal Turned Around",
    "summary": "A displaced everyday object made the boundary of art itself part of the work.",
    "scene": "In New York in 1917, an artist turned an ordinary plumbing fixture around, signed it with a pseudonym, and sent it to an exhibition that claimed to be open.",
    "storyBody": "In New York in 1917, an artist turned an ordinary plumbing fixture in a different direction, signed it with a pseudonym, and submitted it to an exhibition that claimed to be open.\n\nWhen young, he had already grown tired of judging art only by skill and style. The object had not been sculpted, and it had no beauty in the traditional sense.\n\nIts force came from selection, displacement, naming, exhibition position, and institutional reaction. The exhibition rules said that payment was enough for a work to be shown, yet the work was not displayed.\n\nThe argument began there: is art inside the object, or inside the artist's choice, the viewer's judgment, the exhibition institution, and the question itself? Art that is not otherwise classified often stands in this awkward place.\n\nIt makes the catalogue uncomfortable, but also forces the catalogue to admit that some works matter not because they look like art, but because they expose the boundary of art. Arranging works by author, period, style, or type still has its use.\n\nBut to make judgment go further, close reading, comparison, material analysis, and interpretive traditions have to become learnable work. Art outside fixed categories would later have courses and institutions.\n\nIn this scene, it first unfolded against close reading, comparison, material analysis, and interpretive traditions. This person was Marcel Duchamp. Through Fountain and the idea of the readymade, he deeply changed twentieth-century understandings of the work, the artist, and the institution.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Arts outside a single category hold cross-media, conceptual, temporary, and difficult-to-archive forms of creation.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "If something was not handmade but forces you to redefine art, can it still be a work?"
  },
  "0221-religion-and-theology": {
    "title": "A Monk's Letter to the Bishop",
    "summary": "A theological challenge to indulgences moved a religious question from the pulpit into public history.",
    "scene": "In Germany in 1517, a young theology teacher heard ordinary people talk about indulgences and became increasingly uneasy.",
    "storyBody": "In Germany in 1517, a young theology teacher heard ordinary people talking about indulgences and grew more and more uneasy.\n\nHe had originally been an intensely serious man inside a monastery, almost painfully sensitive to sin, conscience, and salvation. He did not begin by wanting to create a storm across Europe. He began with a pastoral problem: if people thought money could buy peace for the soul, then what had repentance, faith, grace, and church authority become in their understanding?\n\nSo he wrote propositions for academic debate and sent them to church authorities. They were soon printed and spread. The history that followed was far more complex than he could originally control. It brought renewal of faith, and also conflict, political use, and painful division.\n\nReligion and theology show their weight here. They are not abstract words. They are how ordinary people's fear, hope, authority, and interpretation of texts organize life. This was not a moment when the old way had completely failed.\n\nArranging works by author, period, style, or type could still let people act first. What pushed back was that gestures, materials, sounds, and memories cross these boxes and answer one another.\n\nWhen that difficulty returned again and again, the new question became: how does a work produce meaning while carrying historical experience, bodily feeling, and ways of seeing? Before the name became fixed, close reading, comparison, material analysis, and interpretive traditions had already connected the scene to judgment.\n\nThis person was Martin Luther. His Ninety-five Theses became one of the symbolic starting points of the Protestant Reformation and deeply changed European religion, education, and public culture.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Religion and theology study faith, ritual, sacred texts, doctrine, community, salvation, and ultimate meaning.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "When a religious practice leads ordinary believers to misunderstand faith itself, should theology remain silent?"
  },
  "0222-history-and-archaeology": {
    "title": "The Sealed Door Beneath the Steps",
    "summary": "Behind a sealed doorway was not a single treasure, but a whole problem of evidence, preservation, and how the past enters the present.",
    "scene": "In the dust of Egypt's Valley of the Kings in 1922, a man who had long worked on excavations had nearly lost his funding, yet still asked workers to keep clearing what looked like ordinary ground.",
    "storyBody": "In 1922, in the dust of Egypt's Valley of the Kings, a man who had worked on excavations for years was almost losing his funding, yet still had workers keep clearing a patch of ground that looked ordinary.\n\nHe was not a scholar who had come straight from a university lectern. When young, he entered Egyptian archaeological sites through his skill in drawing, copying wall paintings, recording details, and learning how to protect fragile evidence in sand and soil. Years of searching had exhausted people, and his funder was close to giving up.\n\nThen the workers found one stone step. Clearing continued downward, and a sealed doorway appeared. When the opening was made, what lay inside was not a simple answer, but thousands of objects that had to be numbered, protected, studied, and moved.\n\nThat moment is often remembered as an exclamation. But real archaeology is not only seeing a miracle. It is also the slow, restrained, systematic work after excitement, allowing the past to speak. If people stayed on the old path and arranged works by author, period, style, or type, things could appear to continue.\n\nBut images, sounds, and objects were not that obedient. Gestures, materials, sounds, and memories cross these boxes and answer one another. So the next step could not be only another explanation added afterward. It had to develop close reading, comparison, material analysis, and interpretive traditions.\n\nWhat remained at the site was not only that close reading, comparison, material analysis, and interpretive traditions moved from personal experience into transmissible training. This person was Howard Carter. In 1922 he led the discovery of Tutankhamun's tomb, bringing a nearly intact ancient Egyptian royal burial to world attention and moving archaeological preservation, recording, and public imagination into a new stage.\n\nWhat remained later was not only a field name. What the scene forced into being was a set of work around close reading, comparison, material analysis, and interpretive traditions.",
    "knowledgePoint": "History and archaeology use evidence, remains, time, materials, and narrative to understand the past, while carefully handling how the past is brought back into the present.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "When we discover the past, are we possessing it, or beginning to bear responsibility for interpreting it?"
  },
  "0223-philosophy-and-ethics": {
    "title": "The Man in the Market Who Kept Asking",
    "summary": "A relentless questioner made philosophy less a display of answers than a test of reasons.",
    "scene": "In fifth-century BCE Athens, a man from an ordinary craft family often spoke with people in marketplaces, gymnasia, and banquets.",
    "storyBody": "In Athens in the fifth century BCE, a man from an ordinary artisan family often spoke with people in markets, gymnasiums, and banquets.\n\nHe left no books of his own, and he was not like teachers who took fees and offered a ready-made set of answers. He was more like an uncomfortable neighbour. When a general spoke of courage, he asked what courage was.\n\nWhen a political figure spoke of justice, he asked whether justice could contradict itself. When young people said they wanted to live well, he asked whether the good life was only success and reputation.\n\nMany people became irritated by his questions, because questions could pull apart polished speech and show that a person had not actually thought clearly. Philosophy and ethics here were not abstract games far from life. They brought everyday judgment back before reasons: on what grounds do I live this way?\n\nHow am I responsible to others? Am I willing to let my own ideas be questioned?\n\nArranging works by author, period, style, or category still has its use. But to make judgment go further, close reading, comparison, material analysis, and interpretive traditions have to become learnable work.\n\nPhilosophy and ethics would later have courses and institutions. In this scene, they first unfolded against close reading, comparison, material analysis, and interpretive traditions.\n\nThis person was Socrates. Through sustained question and answer, he formed the Socratic method and became an important source figure for Western philosophy and ethical inquiry.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Philosophy and ethics study values, reasons, responsibility, knowledge, the good, justice, and the assumptions behind action.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "When you say I know, do you really know what you know?"
  },
  "0229-humanities-except-languages-not-elsewhere-classified": {
    "title": "She Listened to Her Hometown Again",
    "summary": "A person returning home made porch jokes and local tales part of humanities memory.",
    "scene": "In the 1920s, a young woman who had left a small town in the American South returned with anthropological training to familiar porches and street corners.",
    "storyBody": "In the 1920s, a young woman who had left a small town in the American South returned with anthropological training to familiar porches and street corners.\n\nAs a child she had heard many stories: jokes, legends, exaggerated metaphors, evening talk, and voices where religion and daily life mixed together. After leaving home, she entered the academic world and learned interviewing, recording, and analysis.\n\nBut the real difficulty was returning among people she knew. She could not treat them as specimens, and she could not speak for them only through nostalgia. She sat on porches, chatted with people, listened to jokes, recorded dialect, and wrote her own position into the text.\n\nThe materials were like literature, folklore, ethnography, history, and language study at once. They could not be gathered under a single label. Humanities that are not otherwise classified need exactly this sensitivity: some knowledge must enter through the voices of living people speaking.\n\nArranging works by author, period, style, or category still has its use. But to make judgment go further, close reading, comparison, material analysis, and interpretive traditions have to become learnable work.\n\nThis person was Zora Neale Hurston. In works such as Mules and Men, she recorded African American folklore and connected literature, anthropology, and oral tradition into a distinctive humanistic practice. What remained later was not only a field name. What the scene forced into being was work around close reading, comparison, material analysis, and interpretive traditions.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Humanities outside a single category handle questions of meaning, texts, folklore, memory, and human experience that are difficult to place inside one field.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "When someone studies her own culture, is she an observer, or is she also hearing herself again?"
  },
  "0231-language-acquisition": {
    "title": "The Little Creature Called Wug",
    "summary": "A nonexistent creature helped researchers see that children do not only memorize language; they generate rules.",
    "scene": "In the mid-twentieth century, a young researcher sat before children and took out a picture of an unfamiliar little creature.",
    "storyBody": "In the mid-twentieth century, a young researcher sat in front of children and took out a picture of an unfamiliar little animal.\n\nShe did not first ask whether the children could recite grammar terms. Instead, she gave them a word they had never heard. There was one small animal in the picture, and she said it was a wug.\n\nThen another one appeared. She asked: now there are two, what are they called? If a child produced the plural form, it meant the child was not merely imitating words already heard, but carrying a rule into a new situation.\n\nThe experiment was simple, almost like a game, but it struck the core of language acquisition. Children are not passive copies of adult speech. They draw patterns out of the language environment and use them with words they have never encountered. Mistakes, invented words, and hesitation can let us see language growing.\n\nThe trouble was that gestures, materials, sounds, and memories cross these boxes and answer one another. Once that trouble was recorded seriously, the starting point of the field was no longer its name, but how works produce meaning while carrying historical experience, bodily feeling, and ways of seeing.\n\nThis person was Jean Berko Gleason. The Wug Test she designed became one of the classic experiments in research on children's language acquisition.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Language acquisition attends to how people gain language through input, use, rules, errors, feedback, and social situations.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "When a child says something wrong, could that mistake be proof that a rule has already been learned?"
  },
  "0232-literature-and-linguistics": {
    "title": "A Word Is Not Just a Label on a Thing",
    "summary": "A classroom about relations among words moved language from a list of names into a system of meaning.",
    "scene": "In early twentieth-century Geneva, a language teacher repeatedly reminded students in class that language is not a list of names for objects.",
    "storyBody": "In Geneva in the early twentieth century, a language teacher repeatedly reminded students in class that language was not a list of names for objects.\n\nEarly in his career, he studied Indo-European languages and knew ancient sound changes and comparative grammar well. But when teaching general linguistics, he pushed the question deeper.\n\nWhy does a word have meaning? Not because it is naturally tied to an object, but because a sound form and a concept are joined by social convention inside a language system, and because the word can be recognized through its difference from other words.\n\nThe view sounds quiet, but the change was enormous. Images in literature, names in everyday life, rhythm in poetry, and identity in society could all be seen as parts of sign relations. Linguistics no longer only traced etymologies. It also began to study how systems, differences, and meaning are generated.\n\nThe pressure in the scene was that gestures, materials, sounds, and memories cross these boxes and answer one another. Later courses would name it. What was more urgent at the time was turning close reading, comparison, material analysis, and interpretive traditions into repeatable practice.\n\nThis person was Ferdinand de Saussure. His students edited and published Course in General Linguistics, making signifier and signified, along with structural linguistics, important foundations for twentieth-century language and literary theory.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Literature and linguistics study texts, narrative, sound, signs, structure, meaning, and language rules.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "If a word's meaning comes from its difference from other words, can you still treat language as a dictionary list?"
  },
  "0239-languages-not-elsewhere-classified": {
    "title": "Leaves That Could Speak",
    "summary": "A silversmith wondering why paper could speak eventually gave a people a way to write their own language.",
    "scene": "In the early nineteenth century, a Cherokee silversmith saw white soldiers use paper to send messages and felt that the papers were like talking leaves.",
    "storyBody": "In the early nineteenth century, a Cherokee silversmith saw white soldiers use paper to pass messages and felt that those papers were like talking leaves.\n\nAt first, he could not read or write any existing script. But he was caught by one question: why could marks on paper let people far away hear a message, while his own people had to depend on oral transmission? People around him mocked him and even suspected witchcraft.\n\nThe life of his household was also strained by his long experiments. He first tried to draw a sign for every word, but later found there were too many to remember.\n\nSlowly, he turned toward sound. He broke the language into syllables and designed a sign for each syllable. After years of experiment, the system finally became simple enough for ordinary people to learn quickly.\n\nIt allowed laws, letters, newspapers, religious texts, and family messages to move in the people's own language. It also gave the language one more path to preserve itself under great historical pressure. The details left by this scene remind researchers that gestures, materials, sounds, and memories cross these boxes and answer one another.\n\nThe question shifted its center: how does a work produce meaning while carrying historical experience, bodily feeling, and ways of seeing, instead of throwing unusual cases away as exceptions? A field does not begin with its name. It begins with practicable actions such as close reading, comparison, material analysis, and interpretive traditions.\n\nThis person was Sequoyah. He created the Cherokee syllabary, giving the Cherokee Nation its own writing system in the 1820s, and became one of the rare classic cases in language history of a writing system successfully invented by one person.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Languages outside a single category attend to language practices that do not fit standard language courses, dominant writing traditions, or one language label.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "What happens when a community without a writing tradition suddenly gains a way to write its own language?"
  },
  "0311-economics": {
    "title": "The Tiny Pin",
    "summary": "A pin brought economics down from abstract wealth into division of labour, prices, and cooperation among strangers.",
    "scene": "In eighteenth-century Scotland, a professor of moral philosophy who often walked through the streets became more and more fascinated by ordinary transactions in shops, workshops, and ports.",
    "storyBody": "In eighteenth-century Scotland, a professor of moral philosophy who often walked through the streets became more and more fascinated by ordinary transactions in shops, workshops, and ports.\n\nHe was not a man sitting in a counting house thinking only about profit. But he kept feeling that questions such as why bread arrives on the table, why wages are set as they are, and why a small commodity can be sold far away were not only private matters for merchants.\n\nIn his book, he wrote about a very small example: a pin. If one person did everything alone, from drawing out the wire, cutting it, sharpening it, and boxing it, output would be very limited.\n\nIf many people divided the work and each performed one small step, the speed would suddenly become astonishing. The example is often remembered because it lets people see that wealth does not appear from nowhere, and is not created only by one clever person.\n\nIt comes from division of labour, tools, the size of the market, price signals, and continuous cooperation among many strangers who are not personally close. Yet the pressure in the scene was that people in different positions leave conflicting evidence that still cannot be ignored.\n\nThis person was Adam Smith. In 1776 he published The Wealth of Nations and became one of the important founders of modern economics.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Economics studies scarcity, division of labour, prices, incentives, exchange, and how resources are arranged in society.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "When you see a cheap small object, do you think about how many strangers cooperated behind it?"
  },
  "0312-political-sciences-and-civics": {
    "title": "Democracy in the Town Meeting",
    "summary": "A foreign observer saw in American town meetings that politics is not only elections, but repeated practice in public life.",
    "scene": "In 1830s America, a young French aristocrat sat beside local meetings and listened carefully as ordinary residents argued about roads, schools, and taxes.",
    "storyBody": "In the United States in the 1830s, a young French aristocrat sat beside local meetings and listened carefully as ordinary residents argued over roads, schools, and taxes.\n\nHe had originally come to examine the prison system, but he was soon drawn to smaller scenes. People organized themselves in churches, newspapers, associations, and town meetings. They argued and also cooperated.\n\nThey remained wary of government, yet were willing to spend time on public affairs. He saw that democracy was not a slogan, but a whole set of habits: association, speech, compromise, local self-government, worry about majority power, and the awkward process through which ordinary people learn public judgment.\n\nPolitical science and civics became concrete here, because institutions are not only written in constitutions. They also live in how citizens attend meetings, read news, organize associations, and limit power. If people stayed on the old path and handed social problems to opinion, rumour, or a single record, things could appear to continue.\n\nBut archives, maps, and human voices were not that obedient. People in different positions leave conflicting evidence that still cannot be ignored. So the next step could not be only another explanation added afterward. It had to develop investigation, checking, classification, communication, and public explanation.\n\nThis person was Alexis de Tocqueville. In Democracy in America, he analyzed American democracy, associational life, and the danger of majority tyranny, and became an important classic figure in political science and civic studies.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Political science and civics attend to how public decision-making, power, institutions, participation, rights, and responsibilities organize common life.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "If democracy does not happen only on voting day, where did you practice public judgment today?"
  },
  "0313-psychology": {
    "title": "The Metronome in the Laboratory",
    "summary": "A small metronome helped psychology move from philosophical reflection toward experiment that could be trained and measured.",
    "scene": "In Leipzig in 1879, a room held timers, metronomes, reaction keys, and students asked to report their experiences carefully.",
    "storyBody": "In Leipzig in 1879, a room held timers, a metronome, response keys, and a group of students asked to report their experiences carefully.\n\nThe teacher had been trained in medicine and physiology, and he also knew philosophical questions well. He cared about consciousness, but was not satisfied with arguing only in books about what the mind was.\n\nHe asked students to hear sounds, see points of light, press keys, record reaction time, and practice describing their sensations as accurately as possible. From a later perspective, these methods had limits and were far from modern psychology.\n\nBut the key turn had already happened: mental activity could enter the laboratory. It could be studied through designed tasks, recorded time, compared differences, and treated as a process in which body and experience happened together. Psychology was no longer only abstract talk about the soul. It began to become an empirical science of attention, sensation, reaction, and consciousness.\n\nThe trouble was that people in different positions leave conflicting evidence that still cannot be ignored. Once that trouble was recorded seriously, the starting point of the field was no longer its name, but what kind of record lets scattered life enter public judgment.\n\nWhen investigation, checking, classification, communication, and public explanation entered training, judgment in the field stopped depending only on the intuition of a few individuals. This person was Wilhelm Wundt. He established a laboratory for experimental psychology in Leipzig and is widely regarded as an important founder of modern experimental psychology.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Psychology studies behaviour, emotion, cognition, development, interaction with the environment, and how human experience can be observed and measured.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "Can a reaction you think belongs only inside the mind also be explained through time, setting, and body?"
  },
  "0314-sociology-and-cultural-studies": {
    "title": "House by House in Philadelphia",
    "summary": "An urban investigation showed sociology that prejudice cannot replace door-to-door evidence.",
    "scene": "In late nineteenth-century Philadelphia, a young scholar carried forms and a pen into a Black community that many people discussed through stereotypes.",
    "storyBody": "In late nineteenth-century Philadelphia, a young scholar carried forms and a pen into a Black community that many people discussed through stereotypes.\n\nHe knew that if he listened only to newspapers and politicians, the community would be reduced to the problem itself. So he did something slow: he visited households, recorded occupations, income, education, housing, migration, and neighbourhood relations, and placed maps, statistics, and life narratives together.\n\nHe was not treating people as numbers. He was using numbers to resist lazy prejudice. He was also not blaming poverty on one group, but asking how job opportunities, discrimination, housing conditions, and city institutions produced consequences.\n\nSociology and cultural studies gained a sharp sense of reality here. Culture and social structure are not empty words. They land on which street, which job, which room, and which refused opportunity. If people stayed on the old path and handed social problems to opinion, rumour, or a single record, things could appear to continue.\n\nBut archives, maps, and human voices were not that obedient. People in different positions leave conflicting evidence that still cannot be ignored. So the next step could not be only another explanation added afterward. It had to develop investigation, checking, classification, communication, and public explanation.\n\nSociology and cultural studies would later have courses and institutions. In this scene, they first unfolded against investigation, checking, classification, communication, and public explanation.\n\nThis person was W.E.B. Du Bois. His The Philadelphia Negro became an important classic in American urban sociology, empirical social research, and race studies.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Sociology and cultural studies attend to how norms, identity, groups, cultural difference, and social structure shape people's opportunities and lives.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "How much of your judgment about a group comes from evidence, and how much from a phrase you have heard repeated?"
  },
  "0319-social-and-behavioural-sciences-not-elsewhere-classified": {
    "title": "The Children's Food Map",
    "summary": "A child nutrition project showed that some behaviour problems must be read through family, school, community, and policy at once.",
    "scene": "In the American South in the 1930s, a researcher entered schools and homes and found that children's lunch boxes held more social clues than nutrition alone.",
    "storyBody": "In the American South in the 1930s, a researcher entered schools and homes and found that children's lunchboxes held more than nutrition. They held social clues.\n\nShe had training in psychology and anthropology, yet became increasingly unwilling to break human behaviour into isolated variables. What children ate did not depend only on whether a mother knew about nutrition. It also depended on income, racial segregation, school systems, local food habits, farm production, and government programs.\n\nShe conducted interviews, observed tables, recorded household arrangements, and studied how policy entered the kitchen. This work was hard to place only inside psychology, sociology, education, or public health, because it cared about how behaviour happened inside a real social ecology.\n\nSocial and behavioural sciences that are not otherwise classified need this kind of eye. When a problem crosses individual, family, institution, and culture, classification should serve understanding rather than block it. This was not a moment when the old way had completely failed.\n\nHanding social problems to opinion, rumour, or a single record could still let people act first. What pushed back was that people in different positions leave conflicting evidence that still cannot be ignored.\n\nWhen that difficulty returned again and again, the new question became: what kind of record lets scattered life enter public judgment? This person was Margaret Mead. She connected anthropology, child development, food habits, and social policy, and influenced how social-behavioural research understands culture and everyday life.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Social and behavioural sciences outside a single category handle complex behavioural phenomena that cross psychology, culture, family, institutions, and policy.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "How many layers of social conditions might be acting together behind a problem that looks like a personal habit?"
  },
  "0321-journalism-and-reporting": {
    "title": "She Checked Every Name",
    "summary": "A reporter's line-by-line verification of violence made journalism a resistance to public lies.",
    "scene": "In the late nineteenth-century American South, a young teacher and journalist heard that a friend had been lynched, and before anything beyond anger, she did one slow thing: she checked the facts.",
    "storyBody": "In the late nineteenth-century American South, a young woman who worked as a teacher and newspaper person heard that a friend had been killed by lynching. Beyond anger, she first did one slow thing: she checked.\n\nShe did not accept the language commonly used by white newspapers at the time, and she did not turn fear into a vague accusation. She collected newspaper clippings, checked names, places, and excuses, compared cases, and asked how alleged crimes were manufactured to defend violence.\n\nShe wrote articles, published pamphlets, and gave speeches. Because of that work, she was threatened and forced to leave her city. Journalism and reporting in her hands were not the neutral repetition of the language of power. They built a connection among evidence, courage, and public responsibility.\n\nReal journalistic work sometimes means continuing to check facts one by one after most people have already accepted a lie. If people stayed on the old path and handed social problems to opinion, rumour, or a single record, things could appear to continue.\n\nBut archives, maps, and human voices were not that obedient. People in different positions leave conflicting evidence that still cannot be ignored. So the next step could not be only another explanation added afterward. It had to develop investigation, checking, classification, communication, and public explanation.\n\nThis person was Ida B. Wells. Through anti-lynching investigative reporting and public advocacy, she became an important figure in the history of American investigative journalism, the civil rights movement, and journalistic responsibility.\n\nOrigins like this are often not grand. A scene that the old method cannot carry remains first; only later do investigation, checking, classification, communication, and public explanation slowly become methods.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Journalism and reporting focus on fact-checking, interviews, evidence, narrative, public information, and responsibility toward power.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "When a society has grown used to one story, who is still willing to check it line by line?"
  },
  "0322-library-information-and-archival-studies": {
    "title": "Every Book Should Find Its Reader",
    "summary": "A librarian reimagined the library as a public system that actively connects books and people, not only a storage room.",
    "scene": "In India in the 1920s, a young mathematics teacher moved into library work and found that orderly shelves did not mean knowledge was truly being used.",
    "storyBody": "In India in the 1920s, a young mathematics teacher moved into library work and discovered that orderly shelves did not mean knowledge was truly being used.\n\nHe saw that many libraries were like quiet warehouses. Books were well protected, but they did not necessarily reach the people who needed them. His mathematical training made him love order, but the library scene made him understand that order must serve the reader.\n\nHe proposed several simple but deep principles: books are for use; every reader has a book; every book has its reader; save the time of the reader; the library is a growing organism.\n\nThese lines sound gentle, but they changed the center of information work. Cataloguing, classification, lending, opening hours, and librarian service were not only internal techniques. They were ways for social memory and personal questions to meet.\n\nThe details left by this scene remind researchers that people in different positions leave conflicting evidence that still cannot be ignored. The question shifted its center: what kind of record lets scattered life enter public judgment, instead of throwing unusual cases away as exceptions?\n\nWhat remained in the scene was not only investigation, checking, classification, communication, and public explanation moving from personal experience into transmissible training. This person was S. R. Ranganathan. He proposed the Five Laws of Library Science and developed Colon Classification, becoming one of the important founders of library and information science.\n\nWhat remained later was not only a field name. What the scene forced into being was work around investigation, checking, classification, communication, and public explanation.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Library, information, and archival studies focus on organization, preservation, retrieval, accessibility, and long-term public memory.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "Is a system built to preserve materials, or to help the people who need them find them in time?"
  },
  "0329-journalism-and-information-not-elsewhere-classified": {
    "title": "The First Text on the Crisis Map",
    "summary": "A temporary information platform showed that public information can emerge between journalism, technology, and community action.",
    "scene": "After Kenya's 2007 election, street violence and rumors spread together, and a young lawyer wrote an idea online: could people report what was happening around them?",
    "storyBody": "After the 2007 Kenyan election, street violence and rumours spread at the same time. A young lawyer wrote an idea online: could people report what was happening around them?\n\nThe problem she saw was not something traditional newspapers could solve alone. Events were scattered, messages were confused, and many people had mobile phones but no safe channel for sending location, danger, and requests for help into public view.\n\nSo developers, volunteers, and citizens built a platform that connected text messages, web reports, and a map. It was not the same as a news agency, not only a technology product, and not a government archive.\n\nIn crisis, it turned scattered eyewitness accounts into visible information, while also exposing the difficult problems of verification, bias, and safety. Journalism and information that are not otherwise classified exist exactly in this borderland. When reality is too fast, too scattered, and too dangerous, public knowledge needs a new container.\n\nThe details left by this scene remind researchers that people in different positions leave conflicting evidence that still cannot be ignored. The question shifted its center: what kind of record lets scattered life enter public judgment, instead of throwing unusual cases away as exceptions?\n\nJournalism and information outside fixed categories would later have courses and institutions. In this scene, they first unfolded against investigation, checking, classification, communication, and public explanation.\n\nThis person was Ory Okolloh. She proposed and advanced the early idea of Ushahidi, making crowdsourced crisis mapping an important case where journalism, information technology, and civic action meet.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Journalism and information outside standard categories include public information practices that do not fully fit traditional media, archives, or standard information systems.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "In a chaotic moment, how can information appear quickly without giving up verification and protection?"
  },
  "0411-accounting-and-taxation": {
    "title": "Both Sides of the Merchant's Ledger",
    "summary": "A bookkeeping chapter in an arithmetic book moved trade from memory and trust toward a checkable system.",
    "scene": "In Renaissance Italy, a friar and mathematics teacher saw that goods, debts, and cash were always moving through merchants' ledgers.",
    "storyBody": "In Renaissance Italy, a friar and mathematics teacher saw that in merchants' ledgers, goods, debts, and cash were always in motion.\n\nUrban trade was becoming more complex. Relying only on memory to know who owed whom, where goods came from, and where money went had become dangerous. He wrote the double-entry bookkeeping method that merchants were using into a book, explaining that every transaction should enter the ledger from two directions: one side records the source, and the other records where it goes.\n\nThe method did not make commerce morally perfect. But it made errors, deception, costs, and responsibility easier to find. The core of accounting and taxation appears here: numbers do not merely record wealth. In society, they build evidence that can be explained, checked, and borne as responsibility.\n\nThe trouble was that costs, responsibilities, rights, and risks are often hidden after a decision has been made. Once that trouble was recorded seriously, the starting point of the field was no longer its name, but how rules, resources, and responsibilities should be arranged so they can be jointly borne.\n\nThis person was Luca Pacioli. In his 1494 Summa de arithmetica, he systematically introduced double-entry bookkeeping and was later called one of the important founders of accounting.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Accounting and taxation make income, costs, assets, liabilities, tax obligations, and responsibility recordable, explainable, and checkable.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "When money enters both sides of a ledger, has it also entered responsibility?"
  },
  "0412-finance-banking-and-insurance": {
    "title": "The Insurance Question in the Death Table",
    "summary": "An astronomer organized city death records so risk, time, and money could be placed more reliably in one table.",
    "scene": "In the late seventeenth century, a man used to calculating comet orbits began reading one city's records of births and deaths seriously.",
    "storyBody": "In the late seventeenth century, a man used to calculating the paths of comets began to read seriously through the birth and death records of a city.\n\nHe was not asking whether an individual destiny could be predicted. He was asking whether many lifespans placed together would reveal a pattern useful for public judgment. Annuities and insurance had long depended on rough estimates, and prices were often unfair.\n\nSo he arranged age and death data from Breslau and calculated the probability that people of different ages would continue to live. This work made a core problem in finance, banking, and insurance clear: money does not flow only through space. It also flows through time and risk.\n\nInsurance does not eliminate uncertainty. It uses large records, probability, and contracts to spread uncertainty. If people stayed on the old path, using experience, contracts, or accounts to handle transactions and organizations first, things could appear to continue.\n\nBut ledgers, contracts, and the consequences of responsibility were not that obedient. Costs, responsibilities, rights, and risks are often hidden after a decision has been made. So the next step could not be only another explanation added afterward. It had to develop accounts, institutions, cases, boundaries of rights, and organizational design.\n\nWhen finance, banking, and insurance became teachable fields, what was truly preserved was exactly those accounts, institutions, cases, rights boundaries, and organizational designs. This person was Edmond Halley. The life table he made became an important early achievement in the history of actuarial science and life-insurance pricing.\n\nInsurance, pensions, and public budgets still face the same thing. No one can predict an individual fate, but population data changes how society shares risk. The complete system would come later.\n\nAt the beginning, the more important point was that the scene had already forced accounts, institutions, cases, boundaries of rights, and organizational design to become fixed bit by bit.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Finance, banking, and insurance study how time, risk, credit, money flows, and protective mechanisms affect choices.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "When you buy insurance, are you buying money, time, or a shared way to bear uncertainty?"
  },
  "0413-management-and-administration": {
    "title": "She Did Not Want Workers Only to Obey",
    "summary": "A thinker moving between community centres and factories turned management from controlling others toward solving problems together.",
    "scene": "In early twentieth-century Boston, a woman social thinker moved among community work, business meetings, and public affairs.",
    "storyBody": "In early twentieth-century Boston, a woman social thinker moved back and forth among community work, business meetings, and public affairs.\n\nShe saw that conflict was often handled as winning or losing: the boss commands and the worker obeys; departments fight for resources, and whoever speaks louder wins.\n\nBut she increasingly believed that real management should not only suppress conflict. It should organize different experiences so that the problem itself could lead people toward a new solution. She proposed power with rather than power over, emphasizing coordination, participation, situational judgment, and shared responsibility.\n\nHer thought was not as visible for a time as scientific management, but it later influenced organizational behaviour, leadership, and collaborative management. Management and administration in her work were not cold processes. They were ways to rearrange people's experience, power, and goals into a structure where cooperation could happen.\n\nThis was not a moment when the old way had completely failed. Using experience, contracts, or accounts to handle transactions and organizations first could still let people act.\n\nWhat pushed back was that costs, responsibilities, rights, and risks are often hidden after a decision has been made. When that difficulty returned again and again, the new question became: how should rules, resources, and responsibilities be arranged so they can be jointly borne?\n\nWhat later became learnable was exactly accounts, institutions, cases, boundaries of rights, and organizational design. They let the next similar scene avoid beginning again from scratch. This person was Mary Parker Follett. Through her thought on collaboration, power, and the integration of conflict, she became an important early figure in modern management.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Management and administration attend to how organizations, processes, responsibility, coordination, execution, and cooperation around common goals work.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "When facing conflict, are you looking for who wins, or for how the problem itself requires everyone to change?"
  },
  "0414-marketing-and-advertising": {
    "title": "A Small Habit in a Toothpaste Advertisement",
    "summary": "A toothpaste campaign moved marketing from exaggerated slogans toward testing, psychological triggers, and repeatable action.",
    "scene": "In early twentieth-century America, an advertising man stared at newspaper layouts and sales numbers, increasingly doubting that pretty sentences alone could sell things.",
    "storyBody": "In the early twentieth-century United States, an advertising man stared at newspaper pages and sales numbers and trusted less and less in selling things through pretty sentences alone.\n\nHe treated advertising as an experiment that could be tested, not as pure inspiration. He cared whether a headline could make someone stop, whether coupons could track response, and whether a product promise could enter a person's daily habit.\n\nWhen promoting toothpaste, the advertisement did not only say the product was good. It caught the feeling of the film on the surface of the teeth, so that people would use their tongue every day to check whether they needed cleaning. This method also has to be criticized, because marketing can help people understand needs, but it can also manufacture anxiety and desire.\n\nStill, it made the disciplinary features of marketing and advertising visible: attention, evidence, behavioural triggers, trust, and ethical boundaries are always tangled together. This was not a moment when the old way had completely failed.\n\nUsing experience, contracts, or accounts to handle transactions and organizations first could still let people act. What pushed back was that costs, responsibilities, rights, and risks are often hidden after a decision has been made.\n\nWhen that difficulty returned again and again, the new question became: how should rules, resources, and responsibilities be arranged so they can be jointly borne? This person was Claude Hopkins. Through Scientific Advertising and the Pepsodent promotion case, he influenced modern advertising testing, direct-response marketing, and consumer-behaviour communication.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Marketing and advertising study demand, positioning, communication, attention, behaviour, trust, and commercial ethics.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "Is an advertisement helping you see a real need, or manufacturing a new anxiety for you?"
  },
  "0415-secretarial-and-office-work": {
    "title": "The Keyboard Rearranged the Office",
    "summary": "The typewriter turned office work from handwritten letters into a system of speed, format, copying, and professional roles.",
    "scene": "In nineteenth-century America, a newspaper editor and inventor repeatedly adjusted a machine that jammed keys, wanting words to fall onto paper faster.",
    "storyBody": "In nineteenth-century America, a newspaper editor and inventor repeatedly adjusted a machine whose keys kept jamming, hoping that words could land on paper faster.\n\nHe was not facing a romantic literary problem. He was facing very ordinary office pains: too many letters, handwriting that was hard to read, copies that were hard to make, and a speed that could not keep up with commercial exchange. The early machine was heavy and unstable, and the key arrangement changed again and again.\n\nBut once the typewriter entered the office, document formats, communication speed, record preservation, secretarial roles, and gendered divisions of labour were all changed. Secretarial and office work were not a collection of miscellaneous tasks. They were infrastructure for organizational memory, communication rhythm, and document reliability.\n\nEvery agenda, memo, contract copy, and piece of correspondence helped the organization avoid operating only through personal memory. The details left by this scene remind researchers that costs, responsibilities, rights, and risks are often hidden after a decision has been made.\n\nThe question shifted its center: how should rules, resources, and responsibilities be arranged so they can be jointly borne, instead of throwing unusual cases away as exceptions? This person was Christopher Latham Sholes. He took part in inventing and promoting early practical typewriters, with a lasting influence on modern office documents and secretarial work.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Secretarial and office work attend to how documents, communication, schedules, processes, records, and organizational memory support daily operation.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "Which seemingly minor documents in an organization actually keep everyone from being swallowed by confusion?"
  },
  "0416-wholesale-and-retail-sales": {
    "title": "The Store Where Customers Picked Goods Themselves",
    "summary": "A self-service grocery changed shelves, price tags, customer movement, and the basic imagination of retail.",
    "scene": "In Memphis in 1916, a grocer watched clerks behind the counter constantly fetch goods for customers and felt the whole process was too slow and too expensive.",
    "storyBody": "In Memphis in 1916, a grocer watched clerks behind the counter keep fetching goods for customers, and felt that the whole process was too slow and too expensive.\n\nAt the time, shopping often meant that a clerk retrieved goods from behind the counter. The customer spoke, the clerk picked up the item, and price and choice were separated by the counter. He reversed the store's path: let customers push through a turnstile, move along shelves, take goods themselves, see packaging and prices clearly, and then pay at the exit.\n\nThe change was not simply saving labour. It rewrote the field logic of wholesale and retail sales. Display, packaging, impulse buying, inventory, price tags, theft prevention, and checkout became one system. Customers gained more freedom, and they were also guided by new shelf design.\n\nThe trouble was that costs, responsibilities, rights, and risks are often hidden after a decision has been made. Once that trouble was recorded seriously, the starting point of the field was no longer its name, but how rules, resources, and responsibilities should be arranged so they can be jointly borne.\n\nThis person was Clarence Saunders. He founded Piggly Wiggly and pushed the self-service supermarket model into commercial practice, deeply influencing modern retail sales. Retail design still asks similar questions: when customers complete part of the service themselves, how are convenience, cost, trust, and the feeling of being watched redistributed?",
    "knowledgePoint": "Wholesale and retail sales attend to how goods circulation, display, pricing, inventory, customer relations, and the buying scene are designed.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "When you think you are freely choosing goods, what arrangements has the shelf already made for you?"
  },
  "0417-work-skills": {
    "title": "How to Hold a Brick Without Wearing Out",
    "summary": "Researchers of work movement shifted work skills from endurance toward practices that can be observed, improved, and made safer for the body.",
    "scene": "On construction sites and in kitchens in the early twentieth century, a husband and wife held stopwatches and cameras and carefully watched how people reached, bent, and picked up tools.",
    "storyBody": "In early twentieth-century construction sites and kitchens, a husband and wife held stopwatches and cameras and carefully observed how people reached, bent, and picked up tools.\n\nThey were not only trying to make people work faster. The real questions were why the same task exhausted one person and felt smooth to another;\n\nwhy workers had to perform so many unnecessary motions; and why household labour was treated as a natural habit not worth studying.\n\nThey filmed bricklaying motions, analyzed the path of the hand, and also studied kitchen height, tool placement, and rest. We should still be alert to efficiency studies being used to squeeze workers harder. But one important reminder they left remains valid: work skill is not born naturally, and it is not only a matter of good attitude.\n\nIt includes movement, tools, time, communication, protection of the body, and learning feedback. The details left by this scene remind researchers that costs, responsibilities, rights, and risks are often hidden after a decision has been made.\n\nThe question shifted its center: how should rules, resources, and responsibilities be arranged so they can be jointly borne, instead of throwing unusual cases away as exceptions? These people were Frank Gilbreth and Lillian Gilbreth. Through motion study and research on work processes, they influenced industrial engineering, ergonomics, and modern work-skills training.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Work skills attend to communication, cooperation, time, task boundaries, tool use, and reliable action in professional settings.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "When you think you are not trying hard enough, could it be that the movement, tool, or process needs to be redesigned?"
  },
  "0419-business-and-administration-not-elsewhere-classified": {
    "title": "A Small Loan at the Village Table",
    "summary": "A rural microloan experiment crossed the boundaries of traditional banking, charity, and community organization.",
    "scene": "In Bangladesh in the 1970s, an economics teacher walked into a village and found that textbook theories of poverty could not explain the debt behind one bamboo stool.",
    "storyBody": "In Bangladesh in the 1970s, an economics teacher walked into a village and found that textbook theories of poverty could not explain the debt behind a bamboo stool.\n\nHe saw craftspeople working hard every day, yet because the money for raw materials came from high-interest lenders, they stayed locked inside tiny profits. Traditional banks rejected them for lacking collateral. Charity did not necessarily change the relations of production.\n\nSo he tried lending very small amounts and observed whether people could build new possibilities through mutual-aid groups, repayment discipline, and local trust. The model later won wide praise and also faced criticism about debt pressure, gender burden, and commercialization.\n\nBut it did show that some practices in business and administration are hard to place inside standard boxes. It looked like finance, and also like a development project, a social organization, and an institutional experiment.\n\nThis was not a moment when the old way had completely failed. Using experience, contracts, or accounts to handle transactions and organizations first could still let people act.\n\nWhat pushed back was that costs, responsibilities, rights, and risks are often hidden after a decision has been made. When that difficulty returned again and again, the new question became: how should rules, resources, and responsibilities be arranged so they can be jointly borne?\n\nThis person was Muhammad Yunus. He founded Grameen Bank and promoted microcredit, making social enterprise and microfinance an important case on the boundary of business and administration.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Business and administration outside a single category hold mixed practices that cross finance, organizations, development, community, and governance.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "When is a business tool opening opportunity, and when might it create a new dependence?"
  },
  "0511-biology": {
    "title": "Tiny Animals in the Rainwater",
    "summary": "A drop of seemingly clear water pushed the scale of nature downward through a small lens.",
    "scene": "In Delft in the 1670s, a homemade single lens, a fine needle, and a drop of stored rainwater lay on a table by the window.",
    "storyBody": "In Delft in the 1670s, a homemade single lens, a fine needle, and a drop of stored rainwater sat on a table by the window.\n\nThe window glass thinned the northern light, and the small brass plate grew warm between the fingers. The man who traded in cloth had first ground lenses in order to see the thickness of threads, broken fibres, and flaws on the cloth surface.\n\nTo the naked eye, clear water was only clear water. If it turned cloudy, people would usually say it had gone bad.\n\nThat day, he lifted a drop of stored rainwater toward the needle point, brought it close to the small lens, adjusted the light, and held his breath to find the focus. Inside the drop, tiny points suddenly turned and moved. Some seemed to paddle; some flashed away and hid.\n\nThe old question was simple: is this water clean? But if something also moved inside clear water, then clarity to the naked eye was no longer the whole world.\n\nHe changed to another water sample, waited a few days and looked again, and wrote the shapes and movements of the different little things into letters. Slowly, the question changed its wording: not only whether the water had spoiled, but whether invisible life could be brought before evidence through tools, samples, and repeated observation.\n\nThe trouble was that once scale changes, boundaries that had seemed clear suddenly stop being enough. Once that trouble was recorded seriously, the starting point of the field was no longer its name, but how invisible or constantly varying life enters repeatable observation.\n\nThe signature was Antonie van Leeuwenhoek.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Life does not exist only at the scale the naked eye can confirm. When tools change the scale of observation, tiny life can enter the checkable natural world through samples, repeated observation, form, and movement records.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "If something is too small for the naked eye, what repeated action would let it move from guesswork into evidence?"
  },
  "0512-biochemistry": {
    "title": "Fermentation Without Living Cells",
    "summary": "A bottle of crushed yeast juice showed biochemistry that life processes could be driven by molecular machinery.",
    "scene": "In late nineteenth-century Berlin, a researcher crushed and filtered yeast cells, originally only wanting to preserve an extract, but found that the liquid began bubbling on its own.",
    "storyBody": "In Berlin at the end of the nineteenth century, a researcher crushed and filtered yeast cells. He had only meant to preserve the extract, but the liquid began to bubble on its own.\n\nAt the time, many people believed fermentation had to depend on intact living cells. But that bottle of cell-free yeast juice still turned sugar into alcohol and carbon dioxide, as if reminding people that behind life activity there were smaller chemical executors.\n\nHe checked repeatedly that it was not contamination and not leftover cells secretly working. The discovery pushed the question from whether the cell was alive to what inside the cell was catalyzing the reaction.\n\nThe door of biochemistry was pushed open. Life was not a mysterious force separate from matter. It was continually maintained by enzymes, molecules, energy, and reaction networks. The trouble was that once scale changes, boundaries that had seemed clear suddenly stop being enough.\n\nOnce that trouble was recorded seriously, the starting point of the field was no longer its name, but how invisible or constantly varying life enters repeatable observation. The name biochemistry could come later. Samples, lenses, comparison, records, and repeated observation were already demanding a new training in the field.\n\nThis person was Eduard Buchner. He discovered cell-free fermentation, advanced the development of enzymology, and received the 1907 Nobel Prize in Chemistry for this work. Biotechnology still continues this turn: life processes can be studied as reaction systems, but every application has to ask again about safety and boundaries.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Biochemistry studies molecules, enzymes, reactions, energy conversion, and material change inside life.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "When a living phenomenon is broken down to the molecular level, does it become colder, or more precise?"
  },
  "0519-biological-and-related-sciences-not-elsewhere-classified": {
    "title": "Colour Jumping on Corn Kernels",
    "summary": "A long-undervalued corn experiment helped life science see that genes do not always sit quietly in place.",
    "scene": "In a mid-twentieth-century cornfield, a woman scientist observed kernel colors one by one and recorded patterns that changed like spots.",
    "storyBody": "In a cornfield in the middle of the twentieth century, a woman scientist observed kernel colours one by one, recording patterns that changed like spots.\n\nHer work was quiet and lonely. Chromosomes under the microscope, ears of corn in the field, and pedigree charts on paper were connected by her year after year.\n\nMany people expected genes to be like letters fixed in place. From unusual colours and breakage patterns, she saw another possibility: some genetic factors could move and could regulate the expression of other genes. The discovery was not fully understood at first, because it went beyond the mainstream imagination of the time.\n\nBiological and related sciences that are not otherwise classified often appear in exactly this kind of edge discovery. The problem crossed genetics, cells, development, and regulation, and for a time had no comfortable box. Yet the pressure in the scene was that once scale changes, boundaries that had seemed clear suddenly stop being enough.\n\nThis person was Barbara McClintock. She discovered transposable elements and later received the 1983 Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine. Origins like this are often not grand. A scene that the old method cannot carry remains first; only later do samples, lenses, comparison, records, and repeated observation slowly become methods.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Biological and related sciences outside a single category handle complex phenomena that cross genetics, cells, development, ecology, or scales of life.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "If an unusual phenomenon goes unbelieved for years, would you still keep looking at it carefully?"
  },
  "0521-environmental-sciences": {
    "title": "The Curve Drawn by Mountain Instruments",
    "summary": "A long measurement of carbon dioxide let environmental science see the breathing of the whole Earth in one curve.",
    "scene": "On Mauna Loa in Hawaii in 1958, a young chemist sent air samples into instruments and cared about stability after the decimal point.",
    "storyBody": "On Mauna Loa in Hawaii in 1958, a young chemist sent air samples into instruments and cared about stability after the decimal point.\n\nWhat he did looked dull: calibrate instruments, exclude local pollution, repeat measurements, and preserve a long-term record. Yet precisely this almost stubborn exactness made the year-by-year rise of carbon dioxide in the atmosphere impossible to ignore.\n\nThe curve also carried seasonal rise and fall, like the rhythm of Earth's vegetation breathing: down in spring and summer, up in autumn and winter. Environmental science showed its power here not through one dramatic disaster, but through continuous, comparable, trustworthy data that turned invisible global change into public evidence.\n\nThe details left by this scene remind researchers that water sources, fuel, soil, species, and community life on the same piece of land change together. The question shifted its center: how can ecological change and human action be placed back into the same field judgment, instead of throwing unusual cases away as exceptions?\n\nThis person was Charles David Keeling. The long Mauna Loa carbon dioxide record he established formed the Keeling Curve, one of the core pieces of evidence in climate-change science.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Environmental science studies the relationships among pollution, resources, climate, ecology, and human activity, and relies on long-term measurement and models to judge change.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "What kind of change has to be measured for many years before people can no longer keep ignoring it?"
  },
  "0522-natural-environments-and-wildlife": {
    "title": "The Grass Stem in the Chimpanzee's Hand",
    "summary": "A field observation changed understandings of wild animal behaviour and made conservation more than a species list.",
    "scene": "In a Tanzanian forest in 1960, a young woman sat under trees and waited for a long time until chimpanzees were willing to come close.",
    "storyBody": "In a Tanzanian forest in 1960, a young woman sat under trees and waited for a long time until chimpanzees were willing to come near.\n\nAt first, she did not have traditional doctoral training. She entered the forest with notebooks, binoculars, and enormous patience. For many days, the animals only kept their distance.\n\nLater she saw a chimpanzee push a grass stem into a termite mound and then carry the termite-covered stem to its mouth. The small movement mattered greatly: tool use could no longer be easily described as something only humans did.\n\nMore importantly, long observation gave each animal individual personality, kinship relations, conflict, care, and learning. Research on natural environments and wildlife was therefore not only counting how many animals there were. It also had to understand habitat, behaviour, social relations, and human disturbance.\n\nThis was not a moment when the old way had completely failed. Breaking environmental problems into single troubles such as water, trees, land, or pollution could still let people act first.\n\nWhat pushed back was that water sources, fuel, soil, species, and community life on the same piece of land change together. When that difficulty returned again and again, the new question became: how can ecological change and human action be placed back into the same field judgment?\n\nThis person was Jane Goodall. Her long-term chimpanzee research at Gombe changed primate behaviour studies and public understanding of wildlife conservation.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Natural environments and wildlife attend to habitats, species behaviour, conservation, ecological balance, and the effects of human activity.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "When you discover that an animal can learn and use a tool, how does your idea of human specialness change?"
  },
  "0529-environment-not-elsewhere-classified": {
    "title": "Seedlings and Water Buckets in Women's Hands",
    "summary": "A tree-planting movement showed that environmental problems can also be problems of land, water, gender, democracy, and community organization.",
    "scene": "In Kenya in the 1970s, a woman trained in biology heard rural women say that firewood was farther away, water was scarcer, and the soil was growing thinner.",
    "storyBody": "In Kenya in the 1970s, a woman trained in biology heard rural women say that firewood was farther away, water was scarcer, and the soil was growing thinner.\n\nShe did not treat these complaints as scattered difficulties of daily life. Trees had been cut, water sources had worsened, soil was washing away, women were walking farther for fuel, and family life and local politics were both being pulled in.\n\nSo she began with the plainest action: organize women to raise seedlings, plant trees, and care for them. Tree planting also became an entrance into education, income, community rights, and democratic participation. The environmental field that is not otherwise classified often appears this way. It is not only ecology, and not only poverty reduction, women's rights, or political reform. It is all of these tangled on the same piece of land.\n\nThe details left by this scene remind researchers that water sources, fuel, soil, species, and community life on the same land change together. The question shifted its center: how can ecological change and human action be placed back into the same field judgment, instead of throwing unusual cases away as exceptions?\n\nEnvironment outside fixed categories would later have courses and institutions. In this scene, it first unfolded against long observation, community records, ecological relations, and action feedback.\n\nThis person was Wangari Maathai. She founded the Green Belt Movement and received the 2004 Nobel Peace Prize for environmental protection, women's empowerment, and democratic action.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Environment outside a single category handles complex environmental practices that cross water, soil, ecology, community, policy, and social fairness.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "When is a tree not only a tree, but a crossing point of water, time, income, and public rights?"
  },
  "0531-chemistry": {
    "title": "What Was Missing After Burning",
    "summary": "A commitment to burning and weighing moved chemistry from older terms toward mass, elements, and reactions.",
    "scene": "In eighteenth-century Paris, a tax official and scientist repeatedly weighed metals, air, and residues after burning in his laboratory.",
    "storyBody": "In eighteenth-century Paris, a tax official and scientist repeatedly weighed metals, air, and residues after burning inside his laboratory.\n\nThe phlogiston theory popular at the time explained burning as something escaping. But his balance kept pulling the question back to matter itself: if mass increased after burning, did that mean some part of the air had joined the reaction?\n\nHe and his collaborators improved instruments, named oxygen and hydrogen, organized the concept of elements, and pushed chemical language away from vague tradition toward a more checkable system. Chemistry here was not mysterious alchemy. It was precise weighing, closed systems, naming rules, and relations among reactions.\n\nThe pressure in the scene was that instruments, conditions, and repeated results expose natural relations that old explanations have not covered. Chemistry would later have courses and institutions.\n\nIn this scene, it first unfolded against experimental apparatus, measurement, control of conditions, and mathematical expression. This person was Antoine Lavoisier. Through combustion theory, conservation of mass, and reform of chemical naming, he became one of the important founders of modern chemistry.\n\nWhen students first look seriously at a reaction, they learn not only the names of substances, but how conservation, measurement, and evidence change explanation together.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Chemistry studies the composition, properties, reactions, energy changes, and conditions of change in matter.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "When you change a substance, do you look only at the result, or ask where every part went?"
  },
  "0532-earth-sciences": {
    "title": "The Continents Split Like a Puzzle",
    "summary": "A meteorologist's map intuition helped earth science reimagine continents, oceans, and deep time.",
    "scene": "In the early twentieth century, a scientist who studied weather and the polar regions looked at a world map and noticed that the coasts of South America and Africa looked like edges that could fit together.",
    "storyBody": "In the early twentieth century, a scientist who studied weather and the polar regions looked at a world map and noticed that the coasts of South America and Africa looked like edges that could be fitted together.\n\nHe was not an authority inside the orthodox geological circle. Beyond the coastlines, he compared fossil distributions, rock layers, traces of ancient climates, and glacial evidence. He proposed that the continents had once been joined and later drifted apart.\n\nMany geologists opposed the idea at first, especially because he could not explain a reliable mechanism for continental movement. The theory was neglected for a long time, until evidence of seafloor spreading, paleomagnetism, and plate tectonics gave it new force.\n\nEarth science here shows patience: a good question can sometimes appear before a complete mechanism, and Earth's history is far more active than the feeling of still ground under our feet. This was not a moment when the old way had completely failed.\n\nFollowing authoritative explanations or treating phenomena as isolated experimental results could still let people act first. What pushed back was that instruments, conditions, and repeated results expose natural relations that old explanations have not covered.\n\nWhen that difficulty returned again and again, the new question became: how can matter, energy, and motion be tested through experiment and mathematical relations? A field does not begin with its name. It begins with practicable actions such as experimental apparatus, measurement, control of conditions, and mathematical expression.\n\nThis person was Alfred Wegener. He proposed the theory of continental drift, providing a key intellectual predecessor for the later development of plate tectonics.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Earth sciences study rocks, water, climate, landforms, Earth's interior, and changes in Earth systems over long timescales.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "For how long might the apparently stable ground beneath you have been moving?"
  },
  "0533-physics": {
    "title": "Between the Apple and the Moon",
    "summary": "An ordinary question about falling placed motion on Earth and orbits in the sky inside one set of physical rules.",
    "scene": "In seventeenth-century England, a young scholar left the university during the plague and returned to the countryside, continuing to think alone about light, motion, and mathematics.",
    "storyBody": "In seventeenth-century England, a young scholar left the university during the plague and returned to the countryside, where he continued thinking alone about light, motion, and mathematics.\n\nThe story is often told as the moment an apple hit his head. What matters more is that he was willing to connect two worlds: why does an apple fall, and why does the Moon not fly straight away, but circle the Earth? If the same attraction acted on objects on the ground and on heavenly bodies, then nature was not governed by two separate sets of rules.\n\nHe used mathematics to express laws of motion and universal gravitation, organizing experience, geometry, and astronomical observation into a new system. Physics here displayed a powerful imagination: the most ordinary fall might belong to the same problem as motion on the scale of the universe.\n\nThis was not a moment when the old way had completely failed. Following authoritative explanations or treating phenomena as isolated experimental results could still let people act first.\n\nWhat pushed back was that instruments, conditions, and repeated results expose natural relations that old explanations have not covered. When that difficulty returned again and again, the new question became: how can matter, energy, and motion be tested through experiment and mathematical relations?\n\nA field does not begin with its name. It begins with practicable actions such as experimental apparatus, measurement, control of conditions, and mathematical expression. This person was Isaac Newton. In Philosophiae Naturalis Principia Mathematica, he proposed the laws of motion and the theory of universal gravitation, laying the foundation for classical mechanics.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Physics studies motion, energy, force, matter, and natural laws, using models to explain phenomena from everyday life to the scale of the universe.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "What ordinary action near you might be connected to a larger law of nature?"
  },
  "0539-physical-sciences-not-elsewhere-classified": {
    "title": "Current Beside the Magnetic Needle",
    "summary": "A deflection on a lecture table loosened the boundary of physical science as electricity and magnetism began to share one story.",
    "scene": "In Copenhagen in 1820, a teacher discovered during a classroom demonstration that a magnetic needle suddenly deflected beside a current-carrying wire.",
    "storyBody": "In Copenhagen in 1820, during a classroom demonstration, a teacher discovered that a magnetic needle beside a current-carrying wire suddenly deflected.\n\nHe had originally meant to demonstrate an electrical experiment, but a small movement that seemed accidental caught him: when current passed, the magnetic needle no longer quietly pointed north. The phenomenon suggested that electricity and magnetism might have a deep connection.\n\nLater experimenters took up the problem and gradually unfolded the relations among current, magnetic field, induction, and force. Physical sciences not otherwise classified often appear at just such crossings. The case did not belong completely to the old study of electricity or completely to magnetism. It appeared when phenomena forced the classification to change.\n\nScientific progress is sometimes not a matter of putting a new label on an old drawer, but of admitting that the drawer itself has to be remade. Following authoritative explanations or treating a phenomenon as an isolated experimental result still has its use.\n\nBut to make judgment go further, experimental apparatus, measurement, control of conditions, and mathematical expression have to become learnable work. The name can appear later.\n\nWhat came first were experimental apparatus, measurement, control of conditions, and mathematical expression that had to be practiced repeatedly. This person was Hans Christian Oersted. He discovered the magnetic effect of electric current and helped push the development of electromagnetism as a unified field of study.\n\nMany new fields still appear this way: a small phenomenon first makes an old classification uncomfortable, and only later slowly forces out new questions and new language.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Physical sciences outside a single category hold studies that cross matter, energy, fields, experimental phenomena, and disciplinary boundaries.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "When a small deflection suddenly makes two fields meet, do you first correct the experiment, or correct the classification?"
  },
  "0541-mathematics": {
    "title": "From a Point to a Geometric World",
    "summary": "A book beginning with definitions and postulates made mathematics into a shared structure of step-by-step proof.",
    "scene": "In third-century BCE Alexandria, a teacher faced students and arranged points, lines, circles, and angles into a strict path.",
    "storyBody": "In Alexandria in the third century BCE, a teacher faced students and arranged points, lines, circles, and angles into a strict path.\n\nHe did not begin with the most splendid figures, but with the smallest things: what is a point, what is a line, what can be assumed, and what must be proved. One proposition followed another, like bricks building a geometric system.\n\nWhat mattered was not only the conclusion, but that anyone could walk backward along the reasons and check whether each step held. Mathematics showed its distinctive power here: it turned intuition into proof, figures into structure, and personal cleverness into a shareable order of reasoning.\n\nThe trouble was that once the same set of quantities enters proof, structure, or uncertainty, it asks deeper questions. Once that trouble was recorded seriously, the starting point of the field was no longer its name, but how quantity, structure, and reasoning could become a checkable public language.\n\nThis person was Euclid. He compiled Elements, one of the most important classics in the history of geometry, proof traditions, and mathematics education. Learning proof still has this value: it teaches people not only to get an answer, but to build belief on reasons that others can walk back and inspect.\n\nOrigins like this are often not grand. A scene that the old method cannot carry remains first; only later do symbols, proof, data collection, models, and error judgment slowly become methods.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Mathematics uses quantity, structure, space, patterns, and proof to clarify relationships.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "When a conclusion has to be proved step by step, does it also train you to believe more honestly?"
  },
  "0542-statistics": {
    "title": "He Started Counting People in the Streets",
    "summary": "A person who watched the sky turned to city records, helping statistics become a tool for understanding social patterns.",
    "scene": "In early nineteenth-century Brussels, the night sky was often not clear enough, and a young astronomer had to wait for the clouds to clear before recording star positions on paper.",
    "storyBody": "In Brussels in the early nineteenth century, the night sky was often not clear enough. A young astronomer could only wait for the clouds to move away and then record the positions of stars on paper.\n\nAstronomical observation always had error. Slowly, this young man learned that not every deviation had to be treated as failure.\n\nWhen many deviations were placed together, they could instead reveal a distribution. Later, he brought that patience back from the sky to the city.\n\nBirths, deaths, marriages, height, and criminal records had been scattered through registers. He arranged those numbers column by column. One person's life cannot be explained by a table, but many people's records placed together can reveal a certain social shape.\n\nHe proposed the idea of the average man, which was influential and also dangerous. Averages can make disorder readable, but they can also flatten real differences. This was not a moment when the old way had completely failed.\n\nTreating calculation or numbers as techniques for producing answers could still let people act first. What pushed back was that once the same set of quantities enters proof, structure, or uncertainty, it asks deeper questions.\n\nWhen that difficulty returned again and again, the new question became: how can quantity, structure, and reasoning become a checkable public language? This person was Adolphe Quetelet. He brought statistical methods into the study of social phenomena and left the source of the later BMI in the Quetelet Index.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Statistics studies data collection, variation, uncertainty, inference, bias, and the patterns behind many individual records.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "When you see an average, what do you most want to know: what it helps you see, or what it hides?"
  },
  "0611-computer-use": {
    "title": "The Mouse First Pointed at the Screen",
    "summary": "A public demonstration shifted computer use from typed commands toward interaction among screen, pointer, and collaborative tools.",
    "scene": "In an office, a new employee stared blankly at the computer desktop. The meeting would begin in five minutes, and the supervisor asked him to open the customer sheet organized yesterday.",
    "storyBody": "In an office, a new employee stared blankly at the computer desktop. The meeting would start in five minutes, and the manager needed him to open the client spreadsheet he had organized yesterday.\n\nHe remembered saving it, and he remembered that the filename contained final. But there were three similar files on the desktop: client_table_final, client_table_final2, and client_table_final_confirmed.\n\nAt first he thought this was only a small problem. Knowing how to use a computer meant opening software, typing, saving files, and sending email, didn't it? These actions looked simple, almost too simple to count as a skill that needed learning. As long as the computer was not broken, a person could always find things slowly.\n\nBut the meeting would not wait while he looked slowly. The first file was an old version, the second file was missing two columns of data, and the third would not open because it was stored in a folder that had failed to sync. After the manager called once from the meeting room, he realized that saving a file did not mean it could be found and used correctly.\n\nA colleague came over. Instead of clicking around randomly for him, she first asked: who did you send it to yesterday? Did you save it on the shared drive? Which one has the right modification time? They opened the file manager, sorted by date, and checked sync status. Finally they found the correct version and renamed it client_table_2026-06_meeting_version.\n\nThe difficulty of computer use is not only whether someone can click buttons. It includes file naming, version control, search, backup, permissions, email attachments, shortcuts, basic security, and common software operations. The more common digital tools become, the easier it is to underestimate their influence on work order.\n\nWhen the meeting began, the new employee finally opened the correct spreadsheet. The data on the screen had not become smarter, but the file name, location, and version had finally become clear. After that day, he no longer treated the desktop as a temporary dumping ground, because he knew that not finding a file could become a real work risk.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Computer use attends to digital tools, file management, office software, information security, and effective operation of everyday digital tasks.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "When you say you know how to use a computer, do you mean you can open software, or that you can make digital work stable, clear, and traceable?"
  },
  "0612-database-and-network-design-and-administration": {
    "title": "Why Tables Should Relate to One Another",
    "summary": "A database researcher freed data from messy files, making tables, relations, and queries into reliable systems.",
    "scene": "In the late 1960s, an IBM researcher looked at enterprise data systems and found that programs and data were tangled together like threads.",
    "storyBody": "In the late 1960s, an IBM researcher looked at enterprise data systems and saw programs and data tangled like a ball of thread.\n\nMany data systems at the time depended on complex file structures. Applications had to know how data was stored, and a small structural change could pull a whole patch of code with it. He proposed using a relational model to represent data: treat data as tables, make relations and constraints explicit, and query through a higher-level language instead of letting every program get lost in storage details.\n\nThe core of database and network design and administration became clear: when many people share information, structure, independence, consistency, and query ability matter more than temporary saving. If people stayed on the old path and treated the machine as a black box that could calculate, store, and transmit, things could appear to continue.\n\nBut symbols and system failures were not that obedient. Symbols, noise, structure, and user errors expose problems inside the black box. So the next step could not be only another explanation added afterward. It had to develop encoding, structure, interfaces, permissions, testing, and recovery paths.\n\nWhat remained at the site was not only that encoding, structure, interfaces, permissions, testing, and recovery paths moved from personal experience into transmissible training. This person was Edgar F. Codd. He proposed the relational model, laying the theoretical foundation for relational databases and deeply influencing SQL and modern data management systems.\n\nEvery shared spreadsheet, account system, and application backend still answers this question: how can data be trusted by many people through structure rather than memory?",
    "knowledgePoint": "Database and network design and administration attend to data structures, connections, permissions, reliability, queries, and maintenance.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "When many people must trust the same data at the same time, should it rely on memory, or on structure?"
  },
  "0613-software-and-applications-development-and-analysis": {
    "title": "She Saw That the Machine Could Do More Than Count",
    "summary": "Beside a machine not yet built, Ada Lovelace saw early shadows of instructions, symbols, and executable ideas.",
    "scene": "In a London drawing room in 1833, people spoke in low voices. Near papers and teacups on the table, a machine made of gears, shafts, and metal pieces drew the attention of visitors.",
    "storyBody": "In a London drawing room in 1833, people spoke in low voices. Near papers and teacups on the table, a machine made of gears, shafts, and metal pieces drew the attention of visitors.\n\nThe girl was only seventeen. She stood beside the machine, watched people gather around, and listened to them talk about calculation, speed, and precision.\n\nAt the time, calculation tables were often computed by hand, one step at a time, and errors were not rare. If a machine could calculate faster than people, that was already enough to excite many observers.\n\nBut she stayed with the thought a little longer. She was not thinking only about how much this machine could calculate. She asked another question: if numbers could represent not only quantity, but also notes, patterns, relations, and rules, then was the machine really processing only numbers?\n\nThat question did not become an answer immediately. Years later, she translated an article introducing the Analytical Engine.\n\nTranslation would normally only require restating the original. But she wrote longer and longer notes, trying to explain how the machine could calculate Bernoulli numbers step by step: which number to take first, which operation to perform next, when to repeat, and when to stop. Those tables were not code in the modern sense, but they were already very close to breaking human intention into steps a machine could execute.\n\nThe details left by this scene remind researchers that symbols, noise, structure, and user errors expose problems inside the black box. The question shifted its center: how can information be represented, organized, transmitted, and executed so that it is reliable and maintainable, instead of throwing unusual cases away as exceptions?\n\nMany years later, when people looked back for the earliest shadow of a computer program, they often returned to that translation and the Notes after it. The name signed there was Ada Lovelace.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Software and application development and analysis are not only about writing code; they connect requirements, logic, symbols, interfaces, testing, and improvement into a reliable process that lets machines execute human ideas.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "When machines begin to execute human ideas, is the hardest part making the machine smart enough, or making humans state their ideas clearly enough?"
  },
  "0619-information-and-communication-technologies-icts-not-elsewhere-classified": {
    "title": "Piano Rolls and the Compiler",
    "summary": "A naval mathematician pulled programming languages away from machine detail and closer to human expression, widening the boundary of ICT.",
    "scene": "In the mid-twentieth century, a woman mathematician worked beside early computers and saw programmers trapped by machine code and wiring details.",
    "storyBody": "In the middle of the twentieth century, a woman mathematician worked beside early computers and saw programmers trapped by machine code and wiring details.\n\nShe liked making abstract problems operational, and she believed computers should not belong only to the few people who could memorize machine instructions. She advanced ideas of automatic programming and compilers, so that people could express business calculation tasks in a form closer to English, and the machine could translate them into executable instructions.\n\nMany people at first doubted that a machine could possibly understand such language. But this path changed the possibilities of software production and of ordinary organizations using computers. Information and communication technologies that are not otherwise classified often hold this kind of cross-boundary invention. It is language design, and also tools, education, business process, and computing culture.\n\nYet the pressure in the scene was that symbols, noise, structure, and user errors expose problems inside the black box. This is not a search for a beautiful origin for ICT outside standard categories. It is a way to see how encoding, structure, interfaces, permissions, testing, and recovery paths first held the problem up.\n\nThis person was Grace Hopper. She advanced early compilers and the development of COBOL, becoming a key figure in the history of modern programming languages and the spread of computing. Low-code tools and AI programming continue the same line: once the entrance to technology becomes lower, it matters even more that more people can express, check, and take responsibility clearly.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Information technology outside a single category holds digital practices and tool innovations that do not fit standard software, network, or use labels.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "When the language of a tool moves closer to human language, who is allowed into the technical world for the first time?"
  },
  "0711-chemical-engineering-and-processes": {
    "title": "After the Beaker Was Scaled Up",
    "summary": "A success in a small beaker can become a question of heat transfer, mixing, control, and safety inside a production tank.",
    "scene": "In a laboratory, a cleaning-agent formula performed well in a small beaker, but the production supervisor asked whether it would remain stable when scaled to one thousand liters.",
    "storyBody": "In the laboratory, a cleaning-product formula worked well in a small beaker. The color stayed stable, the smell was acceptable, and the reaction finished quickly. When the research team handed the sample to the factory, the production supervisor asked only one question: would it still behave this way at one thousand liters?\n\nLaboratory success can make a problem feel solved. The proportions are clear, the steps are written down, the reaction happens, and the product seems effective. The beaker result looks reliable, as if production only requires multiplying the ingredients by the same ratio.\n\nBut a factory tank is not just a larger beaker. Mixing speed changes, heat leaves the liquid more slowly, the order of addition can create local concentration differences, and heat from the reaction can accumulate in a large volume. Foam that disappears in seconds in a beaker can become an overflow risk after scale-up; a manual dropwise step in the laboratory may require pumps, valves, and monitoring instruments on a production line.\n\nThe supervisor asks the team to run a pilot trial. They put the formula into a smaller test tank and record temperature change, mixing time, foam height, and impurity levels. In the first trial, the temperature rises faster than expected, and the operator has to pause the feed. The formula is not wrong, but the process route is not stable enough.\n\nChemical engineering and processes focus on this turn from 'the reaction can happen' to 'production can continue.' They handle reactors, heat transfer, mass transfer, fluids, separation, control, safety, cost, and waste. Once chemical change leaves the beaker, it enters a field shared by equipment, workers, and risk.\n\nAfter several adjustments, the team changes the order of addition and adds cooling control. The cleaner can finally be produced steadily. When the researcher looks again at the small beaker, she knows the real challenge was not making the reaction happen once, but making it repeat safely in a larger world.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Chemical engineering and processes turn laboratory reactions into safe, controllable, scalable, and maintainable production processes, including reactors, heat and mass transfer, fluids, separation, control, safety, cost, and waste.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "When a solution works at small scale, do you ask which conditions may become new risks after scale-up?"
  },
  "0712-environmental-protection-technology": {
    "title": "Safety in the Tap",
    "summary": "A public health engineer helped make water treatment one of the city's most crucial invisible protection systems.",
    "scene": "In early twentieth-century American cities, tap water entered homes, but bacteria, pipe networks, and disinfectant dosage still made people uneasy.",
    "storyBody": "In American cities in the early twentieth century, tap water entered homes, but bacteria, pipe networks, and disinfectant doses still made people uneasy.\n\nHe cared not only about making water clear, but about how hundreds of thousands of people could drink water that was safe enough every day. Chlorine could kill bacteria, but dose, contact time, taste, pipe contamination, and public trust all had to be handled precisely.\n\nEnvironmental protection technology here was not one beautiful device, but a whole set of engineering judgment: testing, disinfection, delivery, monitoring, and maintenance had to work steadily over a long time. Ideally, people would never think about it, because when they did, something had often already gone wrong.\n\nYet the pressure in the scene was that materials, loads, processes, and long-term use push weaknesses back into the field. What remained in the scene was not only materials testing, process control, structural calculation, and safety boundaries moving from personal experience into transmissible training.\n\nThis person was Abel Wolman. With Linn Enslow, he developed methods for controlling chlorine dosage in water supplies, advancing modern urban drinking-water disinfection and public-health engineering. Every technology that protects the environment still has to pass through this step: the device is not the answer itself. Long-term operation, maintenance, and responsibility decide whether it has truly protected people.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Environmental protection technology uses engineering methods to reduce pollution, treat waste, protect water, air, and soil, and protect public health.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "If an environmental protection technology succeeds every day, are you more likely to forget that it exists?"
  },
  "0713-electricity-and-energy": {
    "title": "The Long Road of Alternating Current",
    "summary": "A man who imagined rotating machines helped electricity move from local lighting toward long-distance energy systems.",
    "scene": "In the late nineteenth century, an immigrant engineer worked between American factories and laboratories, with the rotating magnetic field constantly in his mind.",
    "storyBody": "In the late nineteenth century, an immigrant engineer worked between American factories and laboratories, his mind constantly turning over the idea of rotating magnetic fields.\n\nDirect-current systems could light part of a city, but long-distance transmission was difficult. This young man imagined that current could change direction periodically, and that transformers could raise and lower voltage so electricity could travel farther.\n\nHis alternating-current motor and polyphase system did not only solve one machine problem. They changed the basic structure of generation, transmission, industrial power, and household electricity. Electricity and energy became visibly systemic here: energy was not the instant convenience inside a socket, but a network made of generators, lines, standards, business competition, and public safety.\n\nIf people stayed on the old path and treated a drawing, a formula, or one success as completion, things could appear to continue. But materials, loads, and processes were not that obedient. Materials, loads, processes, and long-term use push weaknesses back into the field.\n\nSo the next step could not be only another explanation added afterward. It had to develop materials testing, process control, structural calculation, and safety boundaries. This person was Nikola Tesla. His patents for alternating-current motors and polyphase AC systems had a key influence on the development of modern alternating-current power systems.\n\nArguments about energy systems still face similar questions: generation method, transmission distance, standards, cost, and safety all decide whether a technology can enter ordinary life.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Electricity and energy attend to generation, transmission and distribution, efficiency, storage, safety, and how energy systems support life and industry.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "When you press a switch, what whole energy system is working for you behind it?"
  },
  "0714-electronics-and-automation": {
    "title": "The Steam Engine Regulated Itself",
    "summary": "A spinning governor made automation look like a machine listening to its own state.",
    "scene": "In an eighteenth-century workshop, a steam engine ran too fast and then too slow, forcing workers to keep watching its speed.",
    "storyBody": "In an eighteenth-century workshop, a steam engine sometimes ran too fast and sometimes too slow, and workers had to keep watching its speed.\n\nWhen he improved the steam engine, he faced not only the problem of power, but also the problem of stability. If a machine lost control whenever the load changed, the factory could not operate reliably.\n\nThe centrifugal governor sensed speed changes through rotating balls. When speed rose, it reduced the steam; when speed fell, it opened again, allowing the machine to correct itself according to its own condition. The device looked mechanical, but it contained the core idea of automation: sensing, feedback, adjustment, and control.\n\nElectronics and automation later entered circuits, sensors, and software, but this early mechanical feedback already showed that machines could do more than execute commands. They could keep comparing a target with reality. Yet the pressure in the scene was that materials, loads, processes, and long-term use push weaknesses back into the field.\n\nWhen materials testing, process control, structural calculation, and safety boundaries entered training, judgment in the field no longer depended only on the intuition of a few people. This person was James Watt. He improved the steam engine and used the centrifugal governor, making feedback control a classic example in the history of automation and control engineering.\n\nFrom thermostats to autonomous driving, systems still handle the same core problem: a system must see its own deviation before it can correct action ahead of danger. The complete system would come later.\n\nAt the beginning, the more important point was that the scene had already forced materials testing, process control, structural calculation, and safety boundaries to become fixed bit by bit.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Electronics and automation study how circuits, control, sensing, machines, and automated systems perceive and act.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "When a machine can adjust its behaviour according to its own error, where is the boundary between it and an ordinary tool?"
  },
  "0715-mechanics-and-metal-trades": {
    "title": "When Screws Could Finally Fit One Another",
    "summary": "A lathe moved mechanics and metalwork from hand-fitting toward standardization and repeatable manufacturing.",
    "scene": "In a late eighteenth-century London workshop, a young mechanic repeatedly improved the lathe, wanting screw threads to stop depending only on a master's hand feel.",
    "storyBody": "In a London workshop at the end of the eighteenth century, a young mechanic repeatedly improved a lathe, trying to make screw threads depend less on the feel of the master craftsperson.\n\nBefore precision manufacturing, parts often had to be adjusted by hand, and once broken they were difficult to replace. A screw looked small, but it decided whether a machine could be disassembled, repaired, and reproduced.\n\nHe improved the screw-cutting lathe, making thread cutting more accurate and more consistent, and helping the machine tool become a mother machine that could make other machines. Mechanics and metal trades become foundational here: modern industry is not only inventing one machine, but making parts, standards, tools, and workers' skills form a repeatable manufacturing system.\n\nThe details left by this scene remind researchers that materials, loads, processes, and long-term use push weaknesses back into the field. The question shifted its center: how can design still stand under scale, risk, and maintenance, instead of throwing unusual cases away as exceptions?\n\nMechanics and metal trades would later have courses and institutions. In this scene, they first unfolded against materials testing, process control, structural calculation, and safety boundaries.\n\nThis person was Henry Maudslay. He developed precision screw-cutting lathes and machine-tool technology, and is regarded as one of the important founders of Britain's machine-tool industry and precision mechanical manufacturing. Standard parts in manufacturing still remind us that efficiency does not come only from faster machines. It also comes from many parts being reliably replaceable, checkable, and able to work together.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Mechanics and metal trades attend to structure, parts, machining, repair, precision, and the transmission of force.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "If a small screw cannot be reliably reproduced, what does the whole machine lose?"
  },
  "0716-motor-vehicles-ships-and-aircraft": {
    "title": "Twelve Seconds Over the Dunes",
    "summary": "A brief flight made vehicle design confront lift, control, engines, and human judgment at the same time.",
    "scene": "On the sand dunes of North Carolina in 1903, two brothers from a bicycle shop pushed a wooden frame, cloth wings, and an engine into the sea wind.",
    "storyBody": "On the dunes of North Carolina in 1903, two brothers from a bicycle shop pushed a wooden frame, cloth wings, and an engine toward the sea wind.\n\nThey did not simply attach an engine to wings. Before that, they had built wind-tunnel experiments, tested airfoils, studied gliding, and focused especially on one key problem: after taking off, how could a machine be controlled?\n\nMany failures taught them that an aircraft was not the victory of a single part. It was coordination among lift, thrust, structural weight, control surfaces, and the pilot's bodily judgment. Motor vehicles, ships, and aircraft work in this way: a moving system has to place speed, stability, safety, materials, and environment together.\n\nThose twelve seconds were not long, but they proved that powered, controlled, sustained flight by a heavier-than-air machine was possible. The trouble was that materials, loads, processes, and long-term use push weaknesses back into the field.\n\nOnce that trouble was recorded seriously, the starting point of the field was no longer its name, but how design could still stand under scale, risk, and maintenance. A field does not begin with its name. It begins with practicable actions such as materials testing, process control, structural calculation, and safety boundaries.\n\nThese people were Orville Wright and Wilbur Wright. Their 1903 flight at Kitty Hawk made them key figures in the history of aircraft development.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Motor vehicles, ships, and aircraft attend to vehicle design, maintenance, operation, safety, and environmental constraints.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "Before a vehicle can move faster, must it first learn how not to lose control?"
  },
  "0719-engineering-and-engineering-trades-not-elsewhere-classified": {
    "title": "The Fighter Plane Coughed",
    "summary": "A small metal washer shows how uncategorized engineering practice often appears between field failure and rapid repair.",
    "scene": "During the Second World War in the 1940s, a woman engineer heard pilots complain that fighter engines briefly lost power after diving.",
    "storyBody": "During the Second World War in the 1940s, a woman engineer heard pilots complain that after a fighter plane dived, the engine would briefly lose power.\n\nThe problem did not fit a slow, orderly research-and-development process. Pilots needed reliable power immediately in the air. The engine had abnormal fuel delivery during negative-G manoeuvres, and there was no time for a complete redesign.\n\nShe studied the carburettor problem and designed a simple restrictor so that fuel flow would not lose control at the critical moment. The small part was not a glamorous invention, but it gave the aircraft a practical improvement while waiting for a more thorough solution.\n\nEngineering and engineering trades outside standard categories often work like this. Field constraints, temporary repair, safety verification, and manufacturing feasibility together force engineers to make judgments reliable enough for the moment. If people stayed on the old path and treated a drawing, a formula, or one success as completion, things could appear to continue.\n\nBut materials, loads, and processes were not that obedient. Materials, loads, processes, and long-term use push weaknesses back into the field. So the next step could not be only another explanation added afterward. It had to develop materials testing, process control, structural calculation, and safety boundaries.\n\nWhen materials testing, process control, structural calculation, and safety boundaries entered training, judgment in the field no longer depended only on the intuition of a few people. This person was Beatrice Shilling. The R.A.E. restrictor she designed helped ease the negative-G fuel-delivery problem in the Merlin engine and became a classic story of field solution in aircraft engineering.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Engineering trades outside a single category handle technical practices that do not fit standard engineering branches but still require safety, manufacturing, and field judgment.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "When is a temporary repair a risk, and when is it engineering wisdom tested by constraints?"
  },
  "0721-food-processing": {
    "title": "Why the Soup in the Bottle Did Not Spoil",
    "summary": "A contest to feed an army moved food processing from kitchen experience toward preservation, sealing, and time management.",
    "scene": "In early nineteenth-century France, a confectioner put food into glass bottles, heated and sealed them, and watched how long they could be preserved.",
    "storyBody": "In France at the beginning of the nineteenth century, a confectioner placed food into glass bottles, heated and sealed them, and then watched how long they could last.\n\nHe did not know how later microbial theory would explain all of this. He faced a more practical problem: armies and long voyages needed food that did not spoil so quickly.\n\nAfter years of experiment, he found that placing food in bottles, heating it, and sealing it could greatly extend preservation time. Food processing appears here as a technology of time and safety. Flavour was only the beginning. The real difficulty lay in microbes, temperature, containers, sealing, transport, and repeatable process.\n\nThe details left by this scene remind researchers that materials, loads, processes, and long-term use push weaknesses back into the field. The question shifted its center: how can design still stand under scale, risk, and maintenance, instead of throwing unusual cases away as exceptions?\n\nThis person was Nicolas Appert. He invented an early canning and preservation method and published related practices in 1810, becoming an important pioneer in the history of food preservation and processing. Food processing still works along this line: tasting good is only the beginning. Safety, time, transport, labels, and trust decide whether food can leave the kitchen.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Food processing turns raw ingredients into food that is safe, stable, transportable, storable, and saleable.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "How can good food withstand time, distance, and invisible life?"
  },
  "0722-materials-glass-paper-plastic-and-wood": {
    "title": "Rubber No Longer Feared Heat and Cold",
    "summary": "An accidental heating turned rubber from a sticky nuisance into a dependable part of modern industry.",
    "scene": "In nineteenth-century America, an inventor deep in debt kept experimenting with natural rubber, unable to solve the problem that it hardened in winter and turned sticky in summer.",
    "storyBody": "In nineteenth-century America, an inventor deep in debt kept working with natural rubber. The same problem always returned: it hardened in winter and turned sticky in summer.\n\nHe was not moving smoothly inside a tidy laboratory. He kept trying through failure, poverty, and obsession. Natural rubber had elasticity, but it was too controlled by temperature to become a reliable industrial material.\n\nLater, rubber and sulfur changed under heat. The material became more stable, more durable, and better suited to manufacturing. The key point in materials work appears here. Glass, paper, plastics, wood, and rubber are not only surfaces or appearances. They have structure, performance, processing conditions, and environments of use.\n\nTo truly understand a material means knowing how it behaves under pressure, temperature, time, and repeated use. The details left by this scene remind researchers that materials, loads, processes, and long-term use push weaknesses back into the field.\n\nThe question shifted its center: how can design still stand under scale, risk, and maintenance, instead of throwing unusual cases away as exceptions? Before the name became fixed, materials testing, process control, structural calculation, and safety boundaries had already connected the scene to judgment.\n\nThis person was Charles Goodyear. He discovered the vulcanization process for rubber, making rubber a more stable and usable material in modern industry. Material choices still change life in this way: one adjustment in a formula can give tires, wires, soles, and medical supplies new reliability.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Materials study attends to the properties, processing, performance, and uses of materials such as glass, paper, plastics, and wood.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "When choosing a material, are you choosing how it looks, or how it behaves under pressure?"
  },
  "0723-textiles-clothes-footwear-and-leather": {
    "title": "The Loom Read Punched Cards",
    "summary": "A machine that wove patterns from cards brought textiles, automation, and later computing ideas unexpectedly together.",
    "scene": "In early nineteenth-century Lyon, a weaver's son saw that complex patterns required great labor and made textile production expensive and slow.",
    "storyBody": "In Lyon at the beginning of the nineteenth century, the son of a weaver saw that complex patterns required a great deal of labour and made textile production expensive and slow.\n\nHe improved the loom so that punched cards controlled the order in which warp threads were lifted. The holes in the cards were not the pattern itself, but they acted like executable instructions, telling the machine when to let which thread pass.\n\nThe field of textiles here was not only cloth and leather. It also included fibre structure, pattern, machine, labour, and repeatable production. The invention brought efficiency, and it also raised workers' fear of losing jobs.\n\nTechnical progress is never only a matter of smarter machines. It also changes human work. Yet the pressure in the scene was that materials, loads, processes, and long-term use push weaknesses back into the field.\n\nThe name could appear later. What came first were materials testing, process control, structural calculation, and safety boundaries that had to be practiced repeatedly.\n\nThis person was Joseph Marie Jacquard. He promoted the Jacquard loom, which allowed complex woven patterns to be controlled through punched cards and also influenced automation and early ideas of computing. Programming and automation still carry an echo of this loom: when a pattern is written as instructions, the boundary among handwork, machine, and symbol changes.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Textiles, clothing, footwear, and leather attend to fibres, structure, comfort, safety, craft, and materials close to the body.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "When a pattern becomes instructions that a machine can read, how much distance remains between craft and computation?"
  },
  "0724-mining-and-extraction": {
    "title": "Wooden Ladders and Air in the Mine",
    "summary": "A book on mining moved extraction from guarded recipes toward recorded techniques, risks, and environmental knowledge.",
    "scene": "In a mining region of Central Europe in the sixteenth century, a physician and scholar went down near the mines and observed how miners ventilated, drained water, supported shafts, and smelted ore.",
    "storyBody": "In a mining region of Central Europe in the sixteenth century, a physician and scholar went down near the mines and observed how miners ventilated, drained water, supported shafts, and smelted ore.\n\nWhat he saw was not the romance of underground treasure, but dangerous labour: collapse, poisonous gas, standing water, ore sorting, smelting fumes, and tools wearing down. So he wrote mining, geology, machinery, metallurgy, and labour sites into systematic knowledge, with images, so experience could be passed on and discussed.\n\nThe core of mining and extraction appears here. For resources to enter society from underground, they must pass through discovery, extraction, safety, environment, and supply chains, with costs at every step. If people stayed on the old path and treated a drawing, a formula, or one success as completion, things could appear to continue.\n\nBut materials, loads, and processes were not that obedient. Materials, loads, processes, and long-term use push weaknesses back into the field. So the next step could not be only another explanation added afterward. It had to develop materials testing, process control, structural calculation, and safety boundaries.\n\nWhen materials testing, process control, structural calculation, and safety boundaries entered training, judgment in the field no longer depended only on the intuition of a few people. This person was Georgius Agricola. His De Re Metallica systematically recorded sixteenth-century mining and metallurgical practice and became a classic work in the history of mining engineering.\n\nWhen people talk about resource extraction, it is still not enough to ask whether something can be dug out. We also have to ask how people breathe underground, how land recovers, and who bears the risk.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Mining and extraction attend to resource discovery, extraction, safety, environmental impact, and supply chains.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "When a product looks clean, who has carried its underground story?"
  },
  "0729-manufacturing-and-processing-not-elsewhere-classified": {
    "title": "Why the Factory Had to Stop",
    "summary": "A seemingly counterintuitive production method moved manufacturing from blindly doing more toward continually finding waste.",
    "scene": "In a twentieth-century Japanese automobile factory, an engineer saw that high inventory did not mean the process was healthy.",
    "storyBody": "In a Japanese automobile factory in the twentieth century, an engineer saw that high piles of inventory did not mean the process was healthy.\n\nTraditional instinct might say that machines should never stop and that more inventory means more safety. He observed the opposite: overproduction hides problems, waiting consumes time, and movement and rework consume people.\n\nIf something abnormal happened on the production line, the problem should be made visible instead of being pushed downstream. He advanced practices such as just-in-time, kanban, and continuous improvement, making manufacturing not only the processing of objects but also the design of a learning system.\n\nManufacturing and processing that are not otherwise classified often handle this kind of mixed knowledge across process, management, field skill, and quality. Treating a drawing, formula, or one success as completion still has its use.\n\nBut to make judgment go further, materials testing, process control, structural calculation, and safety boundaries have to become learnable work. The name for manufacturing and processing outside standard categories could come later, but materials testing, process control, structural calculation, and safety boundaries were already demanding a new training in the field.\n\nThis person was Taiichi Ohno. He developed the Toyota Production System and had a long influence on lean production and modern manufacturing management. The complete system would come later.\n\nAt the beginning, the more important point was that the scene had already forced materials testing, process control, structural calculation, and safety boundaries to become fixed bit by bit.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Manufacturing and processing outside a single category hold questions that cross production processes, quality, field management, and mixed processing practices.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "When should a factory pursue nonstop operation, and when should it stop so the problem can appear?"
  },
  "0731-architecture-and-town-planning": {
    "title": "She Stood on the Corner Watching the Sidewalk",
    "summary": "An ordinary observer of city blocks made planning see sidewalks, neighbours, and everyday safety again.",
    "scene": "In mid-twentieth-century New York, a writer pushed a stroller down the street and noticed how children, shopkeepers, neighbors, and strangers shared the sidewalk.",
    "storyBody": "In New York in the middle of the twentieth century, a writer pushing a stroller along the street noticed how children, shopkeepers, neighbours, and strangers shared the sidewalk.\n\nMany planners at the time were fascinated by large-scale clearance, zoning, and expressways, and saw old neighbourhoods as chaotic and inefficient. She saw another order in daily life: the eyes of small shops, movement through short blocks, the vitality created by mixed uses, people appearing at different times, and relationships of mutual watching among neighbours who did not necessarily know one another.\n\nArchitecture and town planning here returned from the bird's-eye diagram to the height of the human body. A city is not only for cars, models, and development indicators. It is first a living field where people keep meeting, pausing, detouring, watching over one another, and arguing.\n\nIf people stayed on the old path and treated a drawing, a formula, or one success as completion, things could appear to continue. But materials, loads, and processes were not that obedient. Materials, loads, processes, and long-term use push weaknesses back into the field.\n\nSo the next step could not be only another explanation added afterward. It had to develop materials testing, process control, structural calculation, and safety boundaries. This person was Jane Jacobs. Her The Death and Life of Great American Cities changed modern urban planning's understanding of streets, communities, and mixed use.\n\nWhat remained later was not only a field name. What the scene forced into being was work around materials testing, process control, structural calculation, and safety boundaries.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Architecture and town planning attend to space, movement, public life, safety, users, and long-term urban development.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "Was a familiar street brought to life by a plan, or by the people who use it every day?"
  },
  "0732-building-and-civil-engineering": {
    "title": "Steel Cables on the Bridge and Notes Beside the Bed",
    "summary": "The building of a great bridge shows that civil engineering is not only structural calculation but long organization and field responsibility.",
    "scene": "In nineteenth-century New York, after work began on a bridge across the East River, the chief engineer fell ill, but the construction site could not stop.",
    "storyBody": "In nineteenth-century New York, after work began on a bridge across the East River, the chief engineer fell ill, but the construction site could not stop.\n\nShe was not officially an engineer, yet after her husband became unable to go to the site because of decompression sickness, she took on the work of carrying calculations, materials information, cable instructions, caisson details, and construction orders between people. She learned technical details, communicated with workers, politicians, and the engineering team, and maintained the project's continuity amid doubt.\n\nBuilding and civil engineering here were not the drawing of one lone genius. They were a long commitment made of structural mechanics, materials, construction risk, public funding, illness, and communication. The bridge truly crossed not only the river, but also the long distance between design and reality.\n\nThis was not a moment when the old way had completely failed. Treating a drawing, formula, or one success as completion could still let people act first.\n\nWhat pushed back was that materials, loads, processes, and long-term use push weaknesses back into the field. When that difficulty returned again and again, the new question became: how can design still stand under scale, risk, and maintenance?\n\nThis person was Emily Warren Roebling. She played a key engineering coordination role in the later construction of the Brooklyn Bridge and became an important woman in the history of civil engineering. Origins like this are often not grand. A scene that the old method cannot carry remains first; only later do materials testing, process control, structural calculation, and safety boundaries slowly become methods.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Building and civil engineering place structures, roads, bridges, water, electricity, and public safety into physical systems.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "When a bridge is completed, whose learning, care, and persistence are buried in the structure along with steel and stone?"
  },
  "0811-crop-and-livestock-production": {
    "title": "The Peanut Was Not a Poor Crop",
    "summary": "A botanist who came from hardship joined crop production and soil recovery into one problem.",
    "scene": "In the early twentieth-century American South, an agricultural teacher walked onto land exhausted by cotton, holding peanuts, sweet potatoes, and soil samples.",
    "storyBody": "In the American South at the beginning of the twentieth century, an agricultural teacher walked onto land exhausted by cotton, holding peanuts, sweet potatoes, and soil samples.\n\nHe knew that farmers were not failing because they were not trying hard enough. They were trapped by a single crop, poverty, and soil degradation. Long-term cotton planting consumed the land and made household income fragile.\n\nHe studied legumes, crop rotation, soil improvement, and alternative uses, and promoted the planting and processing of peanuts, sweet potatoes, and other crops to farmers. Crop and livestock production here was not only a competition over yield. It was the relation among land, nutrition, markets, household income, and ecological recovery.\n\nYet the pressure in the field was that soil, water, disease, behaviour, and season carry consequences into the next round. When field experiments, breeding, ecological care, and long-term management entered training, judgment in the field no longer depended only on the intuition of a few people.\n\nThis person was George Washington Carver. At Tuskegee Institute, he promoted crop rotation, soil improvement, and research into uses for peanuts and other crops, becoming an important figure in the history of American agricultural education. Crop and livestock production still needs this view: a crop does not exist alone. It changes together with soil, markets, nutrition, pests and disease, and farmers' income.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Crop and livestock production attends to planting, animal raising, yield, health, soil, and food systems.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "When can a crop that is looked down on become an entrance for land and families to recover?"
  },
  "0812-horticulture": {
    "title": "A Plum Tree Opened Too Many Possibilities",
    "summary": "A plant breeder moved horticulture from tending gardens toward selection, hybridization, and long patience.",
    "scene": "In late nineteenth-century California, a young man came from the East to a milder climate and began experimenting with fruit trees, flowers, and seeds.",
    "storyBody": "In California at the end of the nineteenth century, a young man came from the East to a mild climate and began experimenting with fruit trees, flowers, and seeds.\n\nHe did not treat horticulture only as keeping plants beautiful. Every plant had differences: which one was sweeter, which one was more cold-resistant, which one had a more unusual flower colour, and which one suited the local market. These things had to be observed, selected, and propagated.\n\nHe bred plums, potatoes, cacti, and many ornamental plants, while also leaving debates about the commercialization of breeding and scientific rigor. Horticulture here shows its double nature clearly: it is aesthetic care, and also a practice in which heredity, environment, market, and time shape plants together.\n\nSeeing land, crops, or animals first as output still has its use. But to make judgment go further, field experiments, breeding, ecological care, and long-term management have to become learnable work.\n\nThis person was Luther Burbank. Known for extensive plant breeding and new horticultural varieties, he influenced American horticulture and the culture of plant improvement. Horticulture still keeps this patience: pruning, grafting, and selection are not about controlling life, but about slowly negotiating with plant conditions over many seasons.\n\nThe complete system would come later. At the beginning, the more important point was that the scene had already forced field experiments, breeding, ecological care, and long-term management to become fixed bit by bit.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Horticulture attends to ornamental plants, fruits and vegetables, soil, pruning, propagation, light, and spatial care.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "When you care for a plant, are you making it obey, or cooperating with its possibilities?"
  },
  "0819-agriculture-not-elsewhere-classified": {
    "title": "A Single Straw Can Be a Philosophy",
    "summary": "A farmer's long experiment brought natural farming, ecology, and way of life into the borderland of agriculture.",
    "scene": "In twentieth-century rural Japan, a man trained in plant pathology returned to his family's fields and began to doubt whether modern agriculture was becoming too complex.",
    "storyBody": "In the Japanese countryside in the twentieth century, a person trained in plant pathology returned to his family's fields and began doubting whether modern agriculture was becoming more and more complicated.\n\nHe did not oppose excessive intervention because he did not understand science. On the contrary, he had seen how pathology and agricultural technology explained plants, and he also saw farmers becoming increasingly dependent on tillage, fertilizers, pesticides, and labour. In rice fields, he experimented with no-tillage, straw cover, mixed sowing, and reduced outside inputs, letting the field become a more self-regulating ecological system.\n\nThis method should not be simply glorified, and it has to be judged carefully according to region and yield realities. But it shows that agriculture outside standard categories often stands among science, philosophy, ecology, and life practice.\n\nThe details left by this scene remind researchers that soil, water, disease, behaviour, and season carry consequences into the next round. The question shifted its center: which life conditions make results keep improving or keep getting worse, instead of throwing unusual cases away as exceptions?\n\nWhat later became learnable was exactly field experiments, breeding, ecological care, and long-term management. They let the next similar scene avoid beginning again from scratch. This person was Masanobu Fukuoka. He proposed natural farming, and through The One-Straw Revolution influenced ecological agriculture and permaculture thinking.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Agriculture outside a single category holds agricultural forms that cross planting, ecology, community, philosophy, and land practice.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "When is doing one less thing not laziness, but trust in an ecological process?"
  },
  "0911-dental-studies": {
    "title": "A Dentist Should Not Only Pull Teeth",
    "summary": "A dental book moved oral treatment from craft and pain relief toward structure, prevention, and professional training.",
    "scene": "In eighteenth-century Paris, a surgeon faced toothache, dentures, decay, and oral infection, and found that street tooth-pulling was far from enough.",
    "storyBody": "In eighteenth-century Paris, a surgeon faced toothache, dentures, decay, and oral infection, and found that street tooth-pulling was far from enough.\n\nAt the time, many dental problems were handled by barbers, itinerant healers, or tooth-pullers, often only when pain became unbearable. He organized tooth anatomy, causes of caries, periodontal problems, orthodontic treatment, dentures, and instruments into systematic knowledge, emphasizing tooth preservation, cleanliness, and professional judgment.\n\nDental studies become clear here: the mouth is not a small part outside the body. Tooth structure, pain, nutrition, infection, speech, and human dignity are all connected. Yet the pressure in the field was that bodily change is often tangled with environment, institutions, relationships of care, and dignity.\n\nWhat later became learnable was exactly observation, diagnosis, care records, institutional support, and ethical judgment. They let the next similar scene avoid beginning again from scratch. This person was Pierre Fauchard. He published Le Chirurgien Dentiste and is widely called one of the important founders of modern dentistry.\n\nDental work still stands at this turn: treating one tooth also means handling pain, fear, hygiene habits, and whether a person dares to enter the clinic again.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Dental studies attend to oral health, tooth structure, prevention, treatment, restoration, and patient experience.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "If teeth affect eating, speaking, and self-respect, why should oral health be treated as a small matter?"
  },
  "0912-medicine": {
    "title": "The Washbasin in the Maternity Ward",
    "summary": "A doctor found that handwashing could save lives, and also saw how hard it is for evidence to enter institutions.",
    "scene": "In a nineteenth-century Vienna maternity ward, a young doctor found that the death rates of mothers in two wards differed too much for comfort.",
    "storyBody": "In a nineteenth-century maternity ward in Vienna, a young doctor found a difference in maternal death rates between two wards that was too large to feel acceptable.\n\nHe did not first blame death on fate. He compared shifts, personnel, procedures, and contact with autopsies. He noticed that doctors and students came from the dissecting room into the maternity ward and might be carrying an invisible deadly substance to the women in labour.\n\nAfter he required handwashing with chlorinated lime, the death rate fell sharply. But the finding was not welcomed immediately, because it suggested that doctors' own hands might be causing harm.\n\nMedicine here shows a painful side: correct evidence can still be resisted if it challenges professional pride and institutional habit. The trouble was that bodily change is often tangled with environment, institutions, relationships of care, and dignity.\n\nOnce that trouble was recorded seriously, the starting point of the field was no longer its name, but how to make reliable care among risk, evidence, and a person's life. This is not a search for a beautiful origin for medicine. It is a way to see how observation, diagnosis, care records, institutional support, and ethical judgment first held the problem up.\n\nThis person was Ignaz Semmelweis. He argued that hand disinfection in obstetrics could reduce deaths from puerperal fever, becoming a key figure in the history of infection control and medical evidence. Medical safety culture still returns to this washbasin: behind one simple action are evidence, authority, habit, and the difficulty of admitting error.\n\nWhat remained later was not only a field name. What the scene forced into being was work around observation, diagnosis, care records, institutional support, and ethical judgment.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Medicine studies disease, diagnosis, treatment, prevention, body systems, and how clinical evidence protects life.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "When evidence says the problem may be on your own hands, can you still accept it?"
  },
  "0913-nursing-and-midwifery": {
    "title": "The Lamp in the Night",
    "summary": "Behind the lamp on night rounds was the beginning of nursing as trained care, sanitation, and sustained observation.",
    "scene": "In a military hospital in the 1850s, the corridors were damp, beds were crowded, and the wounded soldiers' problems came from more than the battlefield.",
    "storyBody": "In a military hospital in the 1850s, corridors were damp and beds were crowded. The problems on wounded soldiers' bodies did not come only from the battlefield.\n\nWhen she first arrived, what she saw was not the heroic scene of legend, but a chain of concrete troubles: dirty sheets, poor ventilation, bad drainage, chaotic supplies, and patients sometimes dying not from the wound itself but from the conditions after the wound. She led people in cleaning, organized supplies, improved sanitation, and repeatedly recorded causes of death and ward conditions.\n\nAt night, she carried a lamp on rounds not only to comfort the soldiers, but to see whether breathing, pain, fever, and fear had changed. What mattered most was not the romantic light, but that she turned care into a disciplined profession: observation, records, sanitation, training, and institutions.\n\nThe details left by this scene remind researchers that bodily change is often tangled with environment, institutions, relationships of care, and dignity. The question shifted its center: how can care be made reliable among risk, evidence, and a person's life, instead of throwing unusual cases away as exceptions?\n\nLater courses would name it. What was more urgent at the time was turning observation, diagnosis, care records, institutional support, and ethical judgment into repeatable practice. This person was Florence Nightingale. She established an important tradition in modern nursing training and used statistics and public-health reform to change the professional status of nursing and midwifery.\n\nWhat remained later was not only a field name. What the scene forced into being was work around observation, diagnosis, care records, institutional support, and ethical judgment.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Nursing and midwifery attend to continuous observation, care, hygiene, safety, life processes, and dignity in vulnerable moments.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "Is real care waiting for orders, or noticing change before it becomes an emergency?"
  },
  "0914-medical-diagnostic-and-treatment-technology": {
    "title": "The Hand Bones First Appeared in a Photograph",
    "summary": "An accidental glow brought medical diagnosis into the age of imaging and introduced new responsibility for technical safety.",
    "scene": "In a German laboratory in 1895, a physicist studying cathode-ray tubes suddenly found that a coating some distance away glowed in the dark.",
    "storyBody": "In a German laboratory in 1895, a physicist was studying cathode-ray tubes when he suddenly noticed that a coating some distance away glowed in the dark.\n\nHe did not throw the anomaly away as interference. He repeatedly shielded, tested, and recorded, and discovered an unknown ray that could pass through cardboard and soft tissue, but was blocked by bone and metal. He photographed his wife's hand; the bones and ring appeared clearly.\n\nOlder diagnosis was not useless. Questioning, touch, and experienced judgment had already helped doctors handle many diseases. But that photograph of hand bones pushed the question to another level: could the inside of the body become checkable evidence through devices, imaging, quality of operation, and rules of protection?\n\nMedical diagnostic and treatment technology was therefore not only machines entering hospitals. It required devices, images, dose, safety, and interpretation to be trained together. The person taking the image had to position the body, the doctor had to read the image, the hospital had to preserve it, and the patient also bore radiation risk.\n\nIf any link was careless, the photograph could turn from evidence into misdirection. Technology also brought new risks; early X-ray use caused harm because radiation injury was not yet understood.\n\nSo this field has always included equipment, images, quality control, and safety boundaries at the same time. This person was Wilhelm Conrad Rontgen. He discovered X-rays and received the first Nobel Prize in Physics in 1901.\n\nEvery imaging examination still asks the same question: seeing more does not automatically mean greater safety. Technology must advance together with protection, interpretation, and quality. Medical technology moved from one astonishing photograph into a whole body of clinical work that can be trained, calibrated, and held accountable.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Medical diagnostic and treatment technology attends to devices, tests, imaging, treatment support, quality control, and safe use.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "When technology makes the body visible, what risks must also become visible?"
  },
  "0915-therapy-and-rehabilitation": {
    "title": "The Patient Is Not Finished at Discharge",
    "summary": "A physician made rehabilitation more than auxiliary care: it became a modern medical field helping people live again.",
    "scene": "After the Second World War, many wounded soldiers and patients survived, only to find that surviving did not mean they could walk, work, and live again.",
    "storyBody": "After the Second World War, many wounded soldiers and patients survived, only to find that surviving did not mean they could walk, work, and live again.\n\nHe saw that hospitals often placed treatment's focus on the disappearance of disease or the healing of wounds, but did not answer fully what came after. A person might need to retrain muscles, learn to use assistive devices, manage pain, adjust family and work environments, and regain dignity.\n\nHe promoted rehabilitation medicine, placing physical therapy, occupational therapy, psychological support, social arrangements, and long-term goals inside one plan. Therapy and rehabilitation were therefore not only about returning someone to the past, but about reorganizing the ability to live under new bodily conditions.\n\nThe details left by this scene remind researchers that bodily change is often tangled with environment, institutions, relationships of care, and dignity. The question shifted its center: how can care be made reliable among risk, evidence, and a person's life, instead of throwing unusual cases away as exceptions?\n\nWhen observation, diagnosis, care records, institutional support, and ethical judgment entered training, judgment in the field no longer depended only on the intuition of a few people. This person was Howard A. Rusk. He advanced the development of modern rehabilitation medicine and is called one of the important founders of the field. Rehabilitation plans still begin here: improvement on a chart is truly tested only when it enters stairs, kitchens, buses, and workplaces.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Therapy and rehabilitation attend to functional recovery, training, adaptation, pain management, assistive technology, and long-term support.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "Is recovery a return to the past, or learning to keep living with new bodily conditions?"
  },
  "0916-pharmacy": {
    "title": "The Pharmacy Was Not Only a Counter for Selling Medicine",
    "summary": "A pharmacist pushed pharmacy toward education, standards, and professional responsibility.",
    "scene": "In nineteenth-century Philadelphia, a young pharmacist compounded medicines behind the counter and also saw that drug quality, dosage, and training were not always reliable.",
    "storyBody": "In nineteenth-century Philadelphia, a young pharmacist compounded medicines behind the counter and also saw that medicine quality, dosage, and training were not always reliable.\n\nMedicines can save people, and they can harm people. If powders, tinctures, plant extracts, and prescriptions have no standards, patients have a hard time knowing what they truly received.\n\nHe was not satisfied with pharmacists depending only on apprenticeship experience and commercial sales. He promoted pharmacy education, professional organizations, pharmacopoeial standards, and ethical responsibility. Pharmacy here moved from handing medicine out to becoming a profession that protects the effect and safety of medicines: ingredients, dose, interactions, storage, instructions, and patient understanding all matter.\n\nYet the pressure in the field was that bodily change is often tangled with environment, institutions, relationships of care, and dignity. This person was William Procter Jr. He advanced American pharmacy education and professionalization and is called one of the important founders of American pharmacy. The role of pharmacists is still expanding: handing over the box is not the end. They help medicines be used correctly and safely in real life.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Pharmacy studies drug action, dosage, safety, interactions, quality standards, and medication guidance.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "When a pill truly enters life, what knowledge protects it from being misused?"
  },
  "0917-traditional-and-complementary-medicine-and-therapy": {
    "title": "Long Revisions in the Herbal Book",
    "summary": "A Ming physician spent decades organizing materia medica, making traditional medicine an ongoing dialogue among experience, text, and safety.",
    "scene": "In sixteenth-century China, a physician visited mountains, markets, and old books, finding many medicine names, origins, and uses confused with one another.",
    "storyBody": "In sixteenth-century China, a physician visited mountains, markets, and old books, and found many drug names, places of origin, and methods of use tangled with one another.\n\nHe did not treat tradition as an unchanging authority. On the contrary, he repeatedly checked older books, recorded places of origin, distinguished different things with the same name, added folk experience, and corrected errors from earlier writers.\n\nThis process shows that the most serious part of traditional and complementary medicine is not mystification. It is long accumulation, distinguishing the false from the reliable, dosage, indications, and boundaries of risk. To look at traditional therapies now requires respect for historical experience, and also modern evidence and safety assessment.\n\nThis was not a moment when the old way had completely failed. Reducing a health problem to one symptom, one treatment, or one act of aid could still let people act first.\n\nWhat pushed back was that bodily change is often tangled with environment, institutions, relationships of care, and dignity. When that difficulty returned again and again, the new question became: how can care be made reliable among risk, evidence, and a person's life?\n\nLater courses would name it. What was more urgent at the time was turning observation, diagnosis, care records, institutional support, and ethical judgment into repeatable practice. This person was Li Shizhen. He compiled Bencao Gangmu, systematically organizing medicinal knowledge, and became an important figure in the history of Chinese materia medica and traditional medicine.\n\nWhen facing traditional therapies, the most responsible attitude may be exactly this patience: neither mocking experience too quickly, nor stopping the checking of risk and evidence. What remained later was not only a field name. What the scene forced into being was work around observation, diagnosis, care records, institutional support, and ethical judgment.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Traditional and complementary medicine attends to traditional therapies, bodily experience, safety boundaries, textual inheritance, and dialogue with modern evidence.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "When respecting tradition, how can you also keep the courage to ask for evidence and protect safety?"
  },
  "0919-health-not-elsewhere-classified": {
    "title": "Why the Rats Got Sick",
    "summary": "An unusual laboratory reaction helped health research see stress as a bodily problem.",
    "scene": "In the 1930s, a young researcher injected laboratory animals with different extracts and found that they developed similar bodily reactions.",
    "storyBody": "In the 1930s, a young researcher injected laboratory animals with different extracts and found that they developed similar bodily reactions.\n\nAt first he thought he was studying the effect of one specific substance. But no matter what was injected, the animals developed similar reactions: stomach ulcers, changes in the adrenal glands, and atrophy of immune tissue.\n\nHe began to suspect that the body might be making a general response to many kinds of harmful stimulus. This idea later developed into physiological research on stress, and it also went through conceptual expansion and debate.\n\nHealth outside a standard category often appears this way. The problem does not belong completely to one disease, and is not only psychological or social. Body, environment, emotion, and long-term load are interwoven. This was not a moment when the old way had completely failed.\n\nReducing a health problem to one symptom, one treatment, or one act of aid could still let people act first. What pushed back was that bodily change is often tangled with environment, institutions, relationships of care, and dignity.\n\nWhen that difficulty returned again and again, the new question became: how can care be made reliable among risk, evidence, and a person's life? What remained at the site was not only that observation, diagnosis, care records, institutional support, and ethical judgment moved from personal experience into transmissible training.\n\nThis person was Hans Selye. He proposed the general adaptation syndrome and helped bring stress into modern health research.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Health outside a single category holds health phenomena that do not fit standard medical categories but still affect the body and quality of life.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "When you say you are only tired, could your body already be sounding a long-term alarm?"
  },
  "0921-care-of-the-elderly-and-of-disabled-adults": {
    "title": "He Wanted to Decide His Own Bedtime",
    "summary": "A wheelchair-using university student rewrote care as a question of independent living and autonomy.",
    "scene": "In 1960s California, a young man with severe disabilities wanted to attend university but was assigned to live in the campus hospital instead of an ordinary dormitory.",
    "storyBody": "In California in the 1960s, a young man with a severe disability wanted to attend university, but was placed in the campus hospital rather than an ordinary dormitory.\n\nOthers often understood his needs as nursing and protection. He kept asking: why must help come at the cost of losing autonomy? He and others fought for campus accessibility, personal assistants, housing choice, and self-determination, and later helped advance the independent living movement.\n\nCare of elderly and disabled adults took an important turn here. Care is not only doing things for people, and not placing people wherever they are easiest to manage. It is supporting a person as much as possible in controlling the rhythm, relationships, and choices of his own life. The details left by this scene remind researchers that bodily change is often tangled with environment, institutions, relationships of care, and dignity.\n\nThe question shifted its center: how can care be made reliable among risk, evidence, and a person's life, instead of throwing unusual cases away as exceptions? When observation, diagnosis, care records, institutional support, and ethical judgment entered training, judgment in the field no longer depended only on the intuition of a few people.\n\nThis person was Ed Roberts. He advanced the Berkeley Independent Living Movement and became an important figure in disability rights and the independent living movement. When people discuss accessibility and long-term care now, the question remains sharp: if help does not increase choice, it may only be another way of managing someone.\n\nThe complete system would come later. At the beginning, the more important point was that the scene had already forced observation, diagnosis, care records, institutional support, and ethical judgment to become fixed bit by bit.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Care of elderly and disabled adults attends to dignity, ability support, safety, quality of daily life, and autonomy.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "When helping someone, how do you make sure you have not quietly taken away that person's right to decide?"
  },
  "0922-child-care-and-youth-services": {
    "title": "Children Also Have Their Own Republic",
    "summary": "A pediatrician and educator moved child care from managing children toward respecting children as rights-bearing persons.",
    "scene": "In early twentieth-century Warsaw, a doctor caring for orphans set up a children's parliament, court, and newspaper inside the home.",
    "storyBody": "In Warsaw in the early twentieth century, a doctor caring for orphans set up a children's parliament, a court, and a newspaper inside the home.\n\nHe did not see children only as unfinished adults waiting to be shaped by grown-ups. Children feel fear, make mistakes, need rules, and also have the dignity of being listened to seriously.\n\nIn the orphanage, he let children take part in self-government, handle conflict, express opinions, and practice responsibility. Later, under Nazi occupation and the extreme conditions of the Jewish ghetto, he still tried to protect children's dignity.\n\nChild care and youth services here were not simple supervision. They meant creating an environment where young people could be protected, heard, and able to learn responsibility. The details left by this scene remind researchers that bodily change is often tangled with environment, institutions, relationships of care, and dignity.\n\nThe question shifted its center: how can care be made reliable among risk, evidence, and a person's life, instead of throwing unusual cases away as exceptions? This person was Janusz Korczak. Through his ideas about children's rights, orphanage practice, and his final choice to accompany children to Treblinka, he became an important figure in child care and educational ethics.\n\nChild services still need this reminder: protection does not mean keeping young people silent forever. It means giving them room to speak, make mistakes, repair them, and be taken seriously.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Child care and youth services attend to protection, development, companionship, boundaries, participation, and growth environments.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "When adults say it is for the child's good, where is the child's own voice?"
  },
  "0923-social-work-and-counselling": {
    "title": "She Drew the Family and the Neighbourhood First",
    "summary": "A social worker turned help from charity into careful understanding of the person, family, and resource system.",
    "scene": "In a late nineteenth-century American city, a charity organization worker facing families in need found that simply handing out supplies was often not enough.",
    "storyBody": "In American cities at the end of the nineteenth century, a worker in a charity organization faced families asking for help and found that simply handing out supplies was often not enough.\n\nShe saw that behind poverty there might be unemployment, illness, kinship relations, housing, debt, shame, and gaps in institutions. If help looked only at the immediate request, it could easily misunderstand people and repeat failure.\n\nShe emphasized investigation, interviews, records, family and community resources, and turned casework into a professional practice with method. We are now more sensitive in criticizing the class perspective and moral judgment in early charity work, but one turn she advanced remains important: social work and counselling must understand the network of relations in which a person lives, rather than only evaluating the individual.\n\nYet the pressure in the field was that bodily change is often tangled with environment, institutions, relationships of care, and dignity. This person was Mary Ellen Richmond. Through Social Diagnosis and other works, she laid an important methodological foundation for modern social casework.\n\nCasework should still not stop at the surface request. It needs to place a person's difficulty back inside the web of family, community, institutions, and available resources.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Social work and counselling connect personal difficulty, family relations, resource systems, support processes, and professional ethics.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "When someone asks for help, can you see the relationships and institutions behind the problem?"
  },
  "0929-welfare-not-elsewhere-classified": {
    "title": "The Red Cross Armband on the Battlefield",
    "summary": "A traveler organizing relief beside a battlefield moved welfare practice across national borders, armies, and ordinary charity categories.",
    "scene": "Near the battlefield at Solferino, Italy, in 1859, a Swiss businessman accidentally saw thousands of wounded soldiers left without care.",
    "storyBody": "Near the battlefield of Solferino in Italy in 1859, a Swiss businessman happened to see tens of thousands of wounded soldiers left without care.\n\nHe had not come there to found an organization, but he was trapped by what he saw: soldiers from different countries bled in the same way, medical forces were far from enough, and civilians took part in relief temporarily. He organized local people to care for the wounded, later wrote a book about the experience, and proposed creating neutral relief organizations and international rules.\n\nWelfare outside a standard category looks like this kind of practice. It is not only a hospital, not only an army, and not only charity. It opens a protective path for vulnerable people among disaster, war, law, and humanitarian responsibility. Yet the pressure in the field was that bodily change is often tangled with environment, institutions, relationships of care, and dignity.\n\nWelfare outside fixed categories would later have courses and institutions. In this scene, it first unfolded against observation, diagnosis, care records, institutional support, and ethical judgment.\n\nThis person was Henry Dunant. He helped advance the formation of the International Committee of the Red Cross and the Geneva Convention, and became an important founder of modern humanitarian relief.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Welfare outside a single category holds practices that cross relief, humanitarian action, community, law, and emergency support.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "When a person is wounded, why should that person's side decide whether he deserves help?"
  },
  "1011-domestic-services": {
    "title": "Chemistry Lessons in the Kitchen",
    "summary": "A chemist turned household cleaning, food, and ventilation into domestic service knowledge that could be studied.",
    "scene": "In late nineteenth-century America, a woman chemist entered kitchens, sinks, and dining tables and found scientific problems everywhere in domestic life.",
    "storyBody": "In the late nineteenth-century United States, a woman chemist entered kitchens, sinks, and dining tables and found scientific problems everywhere in domestic life.\n\nShe did not treat housework as a natural female instinct. Water quality, sewage, ventilation, food nutrition, cleaning agents, kitchen movement, and household budgets all required knowledge and standards.\n\nShe advanced domestic science and home economics, bringing household operation into education and public-health attention. We should be alert to domestic knowledge being used to fix gender divisions, but her work also reminds us that whether a home is safe, healthy, and usable rests on chemistry, hygiene, nutrition, and management.\n\nThe trouble was that waiting, space, information, permission, and bodily feeling determine whether a service can hold. Once that trouble was recorded seriously, the starting point of the field was no longer its name, but how the whole path lets people remain safe, clear, and truly seen.\n\nBefore the name became fixed, process design, frontstage and backstage cooperation, physical evidence, and experience correction had already connected the scene to judgment. This person was Ellen Swallow Richards. She was an early American woman chemist and one of the important founders of home economics.\n\nDomestic service can still be understood this way: not as labour that disappears quietly, but as knowledge that makes household systems safer, healthier, and more sustainable.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Domestic services attend to cleaning, organization, care support, household operation, nutrition, safety, and the quality of living environments.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "Does a home become usable because someone naturally knows how, or because there is a whole body of overlooked knowledge?"
  },
  "1012-hair-and-beauty-services": {
    "title": "She Made Hair Care into an Enterprise",
    "summary": "An entrepreneur who had worked as a washerwoman connected hair and beauty service with skill, dignity, and economic opportunity for Black women.",
    "scene": "In early twentieth-century America, a woman long troubled by hair loss began testing haircare products and went door to door explaining them to customers.",
    "storyBody": "In the early twentieth-century United States, a woman who had long suffered from hair loss began experimenting with hair-care products and explaining them door to door to customers.\n\nShe knew hair was not only appearance. It was connected to work, self-respect, racial pressure, and mutual support among women. She developed products, trained sales agents, and opened beauty schools, allowing many Black women to gain income and community status through hair and beauty services.\n\nWe can also discuss the complexity of beauty standards and racial politics at the time. But her story shows that hair and beauty service is not simply making someone look better. It is an industry where technique, body, identity, business, and social opportunity are interwoven. The details left by this scene remind researchers that waiting, space, information, permission, and bodily feeling determine whether service can hold.\n\nThe question shifted its center: how does the whole path make people safe, clear, and truly seen, instead of throwing unusual cases away as exceptions? This person was Madam C. J. Walker. She built a hair-care and beauty enterprise and training system, becoming a symbolic figure in the history of Black women's entrepreneurship and beauty services in the United States.\n\nHair and beauty services still stand on this line: technique happens close to the body, so it also happens close to dignity, beauty pressure, and economic opportunity. Origins like this are often not grand. A scene that the old method cannot carry remains first; only later do process design, frontstage and backstage cooperation, physical evidence, and experience correction slowly become methods.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Hair and beauty services attend to image, body, aesthetics, technique, communication, and trust.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "When does a hairstyle service also handle dignity, identity, and economic opportunity?"
  },
  "1013-hotel-restaurants-and-catering": {
    "title": "The Kitchen Was Organized Like an Army",
    "summary": "A chef reorganized a luxury kitchen into a modern system of roles, menus, and service rhythm.",
    "scene": "In a late nineteenth-century European hotel kitchen, stoves, pans, servers, and orders crossed one another, and a chef found that disorder could ruin the best dishes.",
    "storyBody": "In a European hotel kitchen at the end of the nineteenth century, fire, pans, waiters, and orders crossed one another, and a chef saw that chaos could ruin even the best dish.\n\nHe did not pursue refinement alone. He also cared about how a kitchen could deliver steadily under pressure. Who handled sauces, who handled roasts, who prepared cold dishes, how the menu was simplified, and how service arrived at the table in rhythm all required organization.\n\nHe connected the brigade de cuisine with modern menus and hotel-restaurant service, expanding dining from individual craft into a team system. Hotels, restaurants, and catering become clear here: food is only part of the experience. Hygiene, timing, division of labour, frontstage and backstage cooperation, and customer feeling also decide memory.\n\nThis was not a moment when the old way had completely failed. Seeing service as completing one reception, one act of protection, one trip, or one response could still let people act first.\n\nWhat pushed back was that waiting, space, information, permission, and bodily feeling determine whether service can hold. When that difficulty returned again and again, the new question became: how does the whole path make people safe, clear, and truly seen?\n\nThis person was Auguste Escoffier. He reformed professional kitchen organization and modern French restaurant service, and is regarded as an important figure in modern catering management and culinary systems. Any restaurant service still shows this system: what guests remember is often not one dish, but how chaos was quietly organized.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Hotels, restaurants, and catering attend to hospitality, food, process, hygiene, team roles, and experience.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "In a good meal, which parts are not taste, yet decide whether you remember it?"
  },
  "1014-sports": {
    "title": "A Ball That Could Be Played Indoors in Winter",
    "summary": "A physical education teacher used two peach baskets and a ball to invent a sport that balanced rules, bodies, and fair competition.",
    "scene": "In the Massachusetts winter of 1891, a physical education teacher faced a group of energetic students who could not always train outdoors.",
    "storyBody": "In the Massachusetts winter of 1891, a physical education teacher faced a group of energetic students who could not always train outside.\n\nHe needed an indoor sport that could use the body without turning into the collisions and injuries of football. He nailed peach baskets high, used a soccer ball for passing, and wrote thirteen rules emphasizing passing, space, a goal, and limits on physical contact.\n\nSport here was not random competition. It was the use of rules to let bodies, teamwork, fairness, and safety exist at the same time. A good sport does not only let people win. It makes people want to practice repeatedly, cooperate, respect boundaries, and create within limits.\n\nYet the pressure in the scene was that waiting, space, information, permission, and bodily feeling determine whether service can hold. This person was James Naismith. In 1891 he invented basketball, which became a major sport around the world.\n\nThe same principle still matters when designing physical activities: good limits do not reduce freedom. They allow bodies, cooperation, and fairness to appear safely.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Sports focus on training, rules, bodily performance, teamwork, fair competition, and safety boundaries.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "Does a good rule limit play, or make better play possible?"
  },
  "1015-travel-tourism-and-leisure": {
    "title": "A Travel Agency Inside a Train Ticket",
    "summary": "A temperance meeting trip turned travel from private adventure into an industry of routes, prices, and organized experience.",
    "scene": "In Britain in 1841, a missionary who had once been a carpenter organized hundreds of people to travel by train to a meeting, and had to handle price, time, and order.",
    "storyBody": "In Britain in 1841, a missionary who had once been a carpenter organized hundreds of people to travel by train to attend a meeting. He had to handle fare, time, and order.\n\nHe was not facing distant scenery first. He was trying to let a group of ordinary people reach a destination safely, cheaply, and according to plan. Train tickets, group prices, itineraries, lodging, instructions, and accompanying service slowly connected into a new industry.\n\nTravel, tourism, and leisure here were no longer only the private journeys of the wealthy. They became organized experiences: how routes were designed, how risks were reduced, how local culture was introduced, and how tourist freedom depended on arrangements made in advance by others. If people stayed on the old path and treated service as completing one reception, one act of protection, one trip, or one response, things could appear to continue.\n\nBut paths, waiting, and contact points were not that obedient. Waiting, space, information, permission, and bodily feeling determine whether service can hold. So the next step could not be only another explanation added afterward. It had to develop process design, frontstage and backstage cooperation, physical evidence, and experience correction.\n\nWhat remained at the site was not only that process design, frontstage and backstage cooperation, physical evidence, and experience correction moved from personal experience into transmissible training. This person was Thomas Cook. He organized early group travel and founded a travel-service enterprise, becoming an important pioneer of modern tourism and travel-agency service.\n\nTravel service still balances this same thing: making people feel free while routes, information, insurance, and emergency arrangements hold invisible risks. What remained later was not only a field name. What the scene forced into being was work around process design, frontstage and backstage cooperation, physical evidence, and experience correction.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Travel, tourism, and leisure focus on destinations, itineraries, experience design, cultural contact, safety, and service coordination.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "Why does freedom in travel so often depend on order someone else has already designed?"
  },
  "1019-personal-services-not-elsewhere-classified": {
    "title": "A Stranger Helped Him See the Label",
    "summary": "A volunteer assistance service crossed standard categories, joining digital tools, disability support, and small everyday difficulties.",
    "scene": "In the twenty-first century, a blind user picked up a food can in the kitchen and was unsure what the label actually said.",
    "storyBody": "In the twenty-first century, a visually impaired user picked up a can of food in the kitchen and was not sure what the label said.\n\nTraditional service windows have trouble covering this kind of small and urgent need. It is not medical care, not tourism, not domestic service, and not ordinary customer service. One person simply needs another reliable person to look through a phone camera and say what colour, word, button, or route is there.\n\nThis kind of service connects volunteers, video calls, accessibility, and personal daily support. It also reminds us that service value does not necessarily come from complex processes. Sometimes it comes from adding one piece of human perception at exactly the right moment. Yet the pressure in the scene was that waiting, space, information, permission, and bodily feeling determine whether service can hold.\n\nWhat remained at the site was not only that process design, frontstage and backstage cooperation, physical evidence, and experience correction moved from personal experience into transmissible training. This person was Hans Jorgen Wiberg. He founded Be My Eyes, enabling volunteers to assist visually impaired people with everyday visual questions through video, making it a modern case of personal services outside standard categories.\n\nAs digital services multiply, this kind of small help becomes more important. Technology feels truly warm most often when it supplies the perception a person happens to be missing.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Personal services outside a single category hold practices that improve personal life but do not fit standard service categories.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "What kind of help is too small to name easily but just enough to let someone keep living independently?"
  },
  "1021-community-sanitation": {
    "title": "The Drain in the Poor District",
    "summary": "A report on labouring people's sanitation moved community health from personal cleanliness toward urban infrastructure.",
    "scene": "In a nineteenth-century British industrial city, a reformer investigated workers' neighborhoods and saw sewage, crowded housing, and disease tightly connected.",
    "storyBody": "In nineteenth-century British industrial cities, a reformer investigated workers' housing districts and saw sewage, crowded homes, and disease tightly connected.\n\nHe found that it was easy to blame poor people for not being clean, while ignoring the streets, water sources, and drainage conditions they lived with. Sewage running through streets, garbage piling up, polluted drinking water, and crowded housing made the spread of disease a structural consequence.\n\nHis report advanced public-health reform, while also carrying the class assumptions and control-oriented thinking of its time and therefore needing critical reading. But the core of community sanitation had become clear: cleanliness does not depend only on personal habits. It depends on water supply, drainage, waste treatment, housing, and public institutions.\n\nThis was not a moment when the old way had completely failed. Seeing service as completing one reception, one act of protection, one trip, or one response could still let people act first.\n\nWhat pushed back was that waiting, space, information, permission, and bodily feeling determine whether service can hold. When that difficulty returned again and again, the new question became: how does the whole path make people safe, clear, and truly seen?\n\nA field does not begin with its name. It begins with practicable actions such as process design, frontstage and backstage cooperation, physical evidence, and experience correction. This person was Edwin Chadwick. His 1842 Report on the Sanitary Condition of the Labouring Population advanced public-health and urban sanitation reform in Britain.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Community sanitation focuses on waste, water, cleanliness, public space, housing conditions, and group health.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "When a place is dirty, do you first blame individuals, or examine the conditions the system has given them?"
  },
  "1022-occupational-health-and-safety": {
    "title": "Lead Dust on the Worker's Clothes",
    "summary": "A doctor entered factories and turned occupational illness from personal misfortune into workplace risk that could be investigated and prevented.",
    "scene": "In early twentieth-century America, a woman doctor entered lead plants, rubber factories, and paint workshops, asking workers about headache, numbness, and poisoning symptoms.",
    "storyBody": "In the early twentieth-century United States, a woman doctor entered lead plants, rubber factories, and paint shops, asking workers about headaches, numbness, and symptoms of poisoning.\n\nShe did not wait in the clinic for patients to arrive. She went to the places where patients worked. Where were toxins produced? How was dust inhaled? Was ventilation enough? Did workers have protection? Were employers hiding risks?\n\nThese questions made occupational health and safety a field science. Workplace injury could not be explained by the word carelessness alone. It often came from materials, equipment, pace, power, and lack of regulation.\n\nIf people stayed on the old path and treated service as completing one reception, one act of protection, one trip, or one response, things could appear to continue. But paths, waiting, and contact points were not that obedient. Waiting, space, information, permission, and bodily feeling determine whether service can hold.\n\nSo the next step could not be only another explanation added afterward. It had to develop process design, frontstage and backstage cooperation, physical evidence, and experience correction. Later courses would name it. What was more urgent at the time was turning process design, frontstage and backstage cooperation, physical evidence, and experience correction into repeatable practice.\n\nThis person was Alice Hamilton. She pioneered occupational medicine and industrial toxicology investigation in the United States and advanced workplace health and safety reform. Occupational safety still has to resist a weightless blame: if danger repeats in the same place, the problem may already be written into the process and the power relation.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Occupational health and safety focuses on workplace risks, prevention, equipment, protection, institutions, and safe behaviour.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "If the same workplace injury keeps happening, is it individual error, or is the site repeatedly making danger?"
  },
  "1029-hygiene-and-occupational-health-services-not-elsewhere-classified": {
    "title": "The Exit Door After the Factory Fire",
    "summary": "A disaster revealed regulations, labour rights, and public responsibility at the boundary of hygiene and occupational safety.",
    "scene": "After the Triangle Shirtwaist Factory fire in New York in 1911, a young social reformer stood between grief and anger and asked why the doors had been locked.",
    "storyBody": "After the Triangle Shirtwaist Factory fire in New York in 1911, a young social reformer stood between grief and anger and asked why the doors had been locked.\n\nThe fire exposed not only one factory accident, but failures in escape routes, working hours, child labour, fire inspections, employer responsibility, and government regulation. She later took part in investigations and reforms that advanced factory safety, minimum wages, unemployment insurance, and other labour protections.\n\nHygiene and occupational health services outside standard categories often appear at this crossing. The problem is not one sanitary measure or one safety training, but how law, the worksite, public administration, and the value of human life are rearranged together. Yet the pressure in the scene was that waiting, space, information, permission, and bodily feeling determine whether service can hold.\n\nWhat remained at the site was not only that process design, frontstage and backstage cooperation, physical evidence, and experience correction moved from personal experience into transmissible training. This person was Frances Perkins. After the Triangle fire, she advanced labour and safety reforms, later became the first woman cabinet member in the United States, and took part in the building of New Deal social-security systems.\n\nWhat remained later was not only a field name. What the scene forced into being was work around process design, frontstage and backstage cooperation, physical evidence, and experience correction.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Hygiene and occupational health services outside a single category handle mixed public-health, workplace-safety, regulatory, and field-protection practices.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "When an exit door is locked, is only the passage closed, or also a society's imagination of workers' lives?"
  },
  "1031-military-and-defence": {
    "title": "Calculate the Cost Before Victory",
    "summary": "An ancient military text moved defence from heroic battle narrative toward strategy, information, and avoiding needless exhaustion.",
    "scene": "In ancient China's age of warfare, a military thinker saw how armies, grain supplies, terrain, spies, and a ruler's emotions could decide life and death.",
    "storyBody": "In a time of war in ancient China, a military thinker saw how armies, grain supplies, terrain, spies, and a ruler's emotions could decide life and death.\n\nHe did not write war as simple courage. Older narratives easily ask who is stronger and who dares to charge harder.\n\nThat question was not useless in war, but it covered a colder fact: grain, terrain, spies, morale, the ruler's emotion, and political goals decide life and death together. A real commander has to calculate cost first, preserve morale, use information, avoid being driven by anger, and know that subduing the enemy without battle can sometimes be higher than collision.\n\nMaps, granaries, marching speed, and judgments about the enemy and oneself can decide the result earlier than momentary bravery. The question therefore shifted from how to win to what action is worth its cost, and what victory might drag the state into greater danger.\n\nMilitary and defence reveals its methodological boundary in this scene. Power is only one part. Organization, supply, intelligence, training, restraint, and risk preparation decide security together. Ancient texts cannot replace modern ethics and international law, but they remind later military learning that knowing how to act matters, and knowing how to avoid needless action matters just as much.\n\nThis person was Sun Tzu. The Art of War became a classic text in the history of military strategy, organizational competition, and security thought. These judgments may sound like lines from a book, but they fall on hard ground: how far supply carts can travel, whether soldiers can rest, whether intelligence is reliable, and whether retreat preserves more strength than attack.\n\nMilitary and defence is therefore not worship of conflict. It is training in cost judgment before conflict may happen.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Military and defence focus on security, organization, strategy, training, resources, intelligence, restraint, and risk preparation.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "Is real defence only having power, or knowing when not to use it?"
  },
  "1032-protection-of-persons-and-property": {
    "title": "Every Contact Leaves a Trace",
    "summary": "A forensic laboratory made protection of people and property depend not only on patrols, but on evidence and verifiable investigation.",
    "scene": "In early twentieth-century Lyon, France, a young forensic scholar studied dust, fibers, glass, and fingerprints in the laboratory.",
    "storyBody": "In Lyon, France, in the early twentieth century, a young forensic scholar studied dust, fibres, glass, and fingerprints in the laboratory.\n\nHe believed the crime scene was not silent. Mud is carried away on a sole, a sleeve leaves fibres, broken glass exchanges particles, and whenever people and things touch, they leave traces on each other.\n\nBut these traces pushed the problem to another level. If judgment relies only on experience and confession, omission, coercion, and bias enter the conclusion as well. Protecting persons and property therefore meant more than responding faster. It included preserving the scene, analyzing evidence, reconstructing events, and making judgment withstand examination in court.\n\nThe value of dust, fibres, and glass fragments was not that they were dramatic, but that they forced investigators to explain where every step of reasoning came from. The question changed from who did this to what chain of evidence can show it, and how investigative power can be kept from harming innocent people.\n\nEvidence work must be bound by procedure and rights, or technical power can become a new injustice. This person was Edmond Locard. He established the Lyon police laboratory and proposed Locard's exchange principle, becoming an important figure in modern forensic science and criminal investigation.\n\nThe laboratory and the street became tightly connected here. Investigators could not only say what they believed. They had to explain how samples were obtained, preserved, and protected from contamination. Protection of people and property therefore began to depend on chains of evidence, and also on constraints placed on investigators themselves.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Protection of persons and property attends to risk recognition, prevention, evidence, response, and the design of safe environments.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "If every contact leaves a trace, why must safety judgment respect both evidence and rights?"
  },
  "1039-security-services-not-elsewhere-classified": {
    "title": "The Criminal Became a Detective",
    "summary": "A morally complex figure mixed criminal experience, investigation, files, and private security into a new security practice.",
    "scene": "In nineteenth-century Paris, a man who had been imprisoned many times and knew the underground world began helping the police identify scams, disguises, and criminal networks.",
    "storyBody": "In nineteenth-century Paris, a man who had been imprisoned several times and knew the underground world began helping the police recognize tricks, disguises, and criminal networks.\n\nHis experience is not suitable for simple praise and is morally complex. Older public security relied on patrols, informers, and familiar judgment, and it could handle some street crime.\n\nBut disguise, fraud, underground networks, and movement across districts made that method increasingly insufficient. Precisely because he knew the language and habits of crime scenes, he could read disguise in details, build files, use undercover work and informants, and turn investigation from simple patrol into information work.\n\nFiles and informants can make risk visible earlier, but they can also create dangers of abuse of power, invasion of privacy, and entrapment. Later he founded a private detective agency, causing security service to enter a grey zone among policing, business investigation, intelligence, and personal commission.\n\nThe question changed from how to arrest someone to what information may be used legally, who has the right to investigate, and where the boundary lies between privacy and safety. Security services outside standard categories need to handle this boundary carefully. Effective experience may be useful, but only after being constrained by law, ethics, and supervision can it avoid harming people.\n\nThis person was Eugene Francois Vidocq. He moved from criminal to detective and founded a detective agency, and is regarded as an important figure in the history of modern detectives and private investigation. This grey zone is exactly why the work is outside standard categories: it is not ordinary policing and not simple commercial service, but moves among protection, investigation, intelligence, and commission.\n\nWith every step forward, it must ask at the same time about effectiveness, legality, and the rights of the person being investigated.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Security services outside a single category hold practices that cross investigation, protection, intelligence, field support, and nonstandard risk management.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "When security work depends on grey experience, who draws the line between effectiveness and overreach?"
  },
  "00-the-library-of-mirrors": {
    "title": "The Library of Mirrors",
    "summary": "A traveler learns to study by noticing how he gets lost, not by collecting more maps.",
    "scene": "A traveler entered a city where every gate led to a different library.",
    "storyBody": "A traveler entered a city where every gate led to a different library. On the first day, he copied every map and wrote street names all over his sleeve, but by dusk he had still circled back to the same fountain.\n\nThe method was not foolish. In a strange city, one does need maps first. But every time he got lost, he only blamed the map for not being detailed enough.\n\nOn the second day, he memorized the names of the famous roads and chose only wide avenues, but at the third square he was fooled by similar arches and lost his direction. On the third day, he brought a compass, yet still retreated in front of an unmarked alley, because whenever he saw blankness, he hurried to choose another road.\n\nThe old librarian did not give him a new map. He handed him a thin booklet and told him to write three lines every night: where he had thought he was going, where he had actually turned, and what sign had changed his judgment. At first the traveler was angry. This did not feel like learning. It felt like admitting clumsiness.\n\nOn the fourth day, he followed a merchant's route. The morning went smoothly, but in the afternoon he got lost again. The booklet showed that he did not fail to read maps; whenever he reached a crowded intersection, he followed the person who looked most confident.\n\nOn the fifth day, he deliberately slowed down. At every intersection, he wrote down his own judgment before walking over to test it. On the sixth day, he spread the old maps on the table and marked every failed route in a different colour. Only then did he discover that he often pretended to understand symbols he did not understand, and that when tired, he chose the nearest wide road.\n\nAfter a week, clearer repeated marks appeared beside the little booklet: he always skipped unfamiliar symbols, always treated wide roads as correct, and always gave up where the map was blank. So by day he still searched for roads, but at night he began comparing his ways of searching.\n\nIn the second week, he deliberately entered an unmarked alley, drew a new mark at a corner, then turned back to check why he had dared to continue. In the third week, the old librarian asked him to bring a newly arrived child into the city.\n\nThe traveler did not first hand over a map. He asked the child to say the guess aloud first. After a wrong turn, they looked back together at where the judgment had shifted. By the end of the third week, when someone asked which map was best, he no longer answered immediately. Instead, he first asked where that person most often got lost.\n\nThe city had not become simpler, and the maps had not suddenly multiplied. What changed was that he could now search while also seeing how he searched. Near the last gate, he gave this ability a name: metacognitive regulation, the ability to monitor one's own understanding, choose strategies, and change route when learning fails.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Metacognitive regulation means planning, monitoring, evaluating, and adjusting one's own learning process. At graduate level, learning is not only knowing more content; it is knowing how your attention, confusion, evidence, and strategies are operating.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "When you get stuck, do you only look for more material, or do you also observe how you are looking?"
  },
  "01-the-bridge-too-short": {
    "title": "The Bridge Too Short",
    "summary": "A mountain teacher discovers that real help must stop at exactly the right distance.",
    "scene": "In a mountain village, children crossed a stream on stones to reach school.",
    "storyBody": "In a mountain village, children went to school every day by stepping on stones across a stream. When the water was shallow, even the smallest child could follow the older brothers and sisters.\n\nAfter rain, the stream rose. At the middle, she stopped, gripping her schoolbag tighter and tighter as the sound of the water frightened her. The carpenter said they should simply carry her across every morning.\n\nThat method was fast, and her shoes stayed dry. But three days later, whenever she saw the stream, she still could not move. A merchant then said it would be easier to build a bridge from bank to bank.\n\nThe big bridge let everyone pass safely, but it also meant the children no longer had to look at the current, stones, and depth. The teacher did not tear down the bridge, and she did not carry the child.\n\nShe placed one narrow board only across the hardest part, letting the child choose the first and last stones herself. The teacher stood beside her and, only when the child hesitated too long, reminded her: first look at where the current splits. In the first week, the child still had to hold the teacher's elbow.\n\nIn the second week, the board became a foot shorter, and she began counting the stones herself. In the third week, only a small piece of board remained in the middle of the stream. She slipped once, and the teacher did not pull her up immediately. Instead, she asked the child to look back and say which step had been too hurried.\n\nThe villagers worried she would fall and suggested lengthening the board again. The teacher spread out the daily crossing records: when the child needed only one reminder, when she needed a hand, and when she could already judge for herself. In the fourth week, the teacher put the board on the bank and gave her only a short branch, asking her to test the depth first.\n\nHalfway across, the child stopped again and looked back at the teacher. The teacher only pointed to the brightest stone. In the fifth week, the water rose faster. The teacher did not cancel practice, but made the task smaller: today they would practice only the first three stones, and tomorrow connect them with the middle part.\n\nLater, the board was taken away. The child still walked slowly, but she could now name the safe stones one by one for the children behind her. A few days later, another child stopped at the stream. She did not carry him across. She handed him the branch and asked where he wanted to place the first step.\n\nThe teacher also said less and less: first holding the arm, then reminding about the current, then only waiting for the child to state her judgment. Only then did the village see that what was useful was not the longest bridge, but support that knew how to withdraw as ability formed.\n\nThe support did not disappear. It became hints, tools, waiting, and room for the learner to say the judgment aloud. This is the zone of proximal development and scaffolding: temporary support is placed between what learners can do alone and what they can do with help, and then gradually withdrawn as ability forms.",
    "knowledgePoint": "The zone of proximal development is the space between what learners can do independently and what they can do with help. Scaffolding provides temporary support in that space, then gradually withdraws as ability forms.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "Where are you carrying someone across the river instead of placing a board that can later be removed?"
  },
  "02-the-tapestry-without-a-front": {
    "title": "The Tapestry Without a Front",
    "summary": "A museum apprentice discovers that the whole image and each thread keep changing one another.",
    "scene": "A museum received an unlabeled old tapestry. As soon as the crate opened, dust and loose threads spread across the restoration table.",
    "storyBody": "A museum received an old tapestry with no label. When the wooden crate was opened, dust and loose threads scattered across the restoration table. The apprentice was eager to hang it, but no one could say which side was the front.\n\nFrom far away, it looked like a storm at sea. Up close, one thread looked like a road, another like a river, and a small patch of colour like the sleeve of someone bending down. Following the habit of the catalogue, he numbered each patch of colour first, assuming that once every local part was identified, the whole picture would naturally become clear.\n\nBut the next day, when he stepped back to the wall, he found that the blue thread he had marked as a river might also be a fold of clothing, and the grey thread marked as a road now looked like the shadow of a mast. He then started from the whole and provisionally treated the tapestry as a storm scene, but when he looked closely, several details refused to obey: there were ears of wheat beside the sleeve, and in one corner there was a bird whose thread had almost broken.\n\nOn the third day, the exhibition lead urged him to write a wall label. The apprentice wrote, \"Shipwreck scene.\" But as soon as he posted it, a gold thread revealed under the restoration lamp looked again like a festival banner. He had to tear down the label and turn \"shipwreck\" into a temporary hypothesis.\n\nOn the fourth day, he asked two companions to describe the image, one from the doorway and one from beside the restoration table. The person at the door saw a migrating procession. The person by the table saw fragments of ceremonial clothing.\n\nThe two accounts conflicted, but both sent him back to re-examine lines he had ignored. The curator did not give an answer. He only asked the apprentice to walk between the wall and the fabric three times a day: first recording the image seen from far away, then the thread ends seen up close, and then which local detail had changed his judgment of the whole.\n\nA month later, he changed the label into three columns: current overall judgment, details supporting it, and clues that could still disturb the judgment. When visitors asked what the tapestry really was, he no longer hurried to defend his pride. Instead, he showed them how the judgment changed when a new thread end appeared.\n\nHe also kept the abandoned explanations in the archive, because old explanations showed where he had once seen wrongly. A few weeks later, the apprentice no longer asked for the one true front.\n\nHe would first let the whole give the parts a direction, while also allowing one thread, one patch, or one worn place to overturn the whole. When he wrote the catalogue, the tapestry still had not been solved once and for all, but it was more readable than on the first day.\n\nThe label no longer carried only one conclusion. It listed the details that kept rewriting the judgment. This is the hermeneutic circle: understanding moves back and forth between parts and whole; meaning is not lifted directly from one side, but deepens through repeated correction.",
    "knowledgePoint": "The hermeneutic circle is a core idea in hermeneutics: we understand parts through the whole, and then understand the whole again through the parts. In advanced humanistic inquiry, understanding is not one-time decoding, but a repeated movement of return and revision.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "What are you trying to understand that remains unclear because you are looking either too closely or too far away?"
  },
  "03-the-village-paths-that-walked-back": {
    "title": "The Village Paths That Walked Back",
    "summary": "A village learns that paths are made by footsteps, and footsteps are then guided by paths.",
    "scene": "Between two mountains there was a village, and the well stood at the far side of the grassland.",
    "storyBody": "Between two mountains there was a village, and the well stood on the far side of the grassland. At first there was no road, only the footsteps of every morning.\n\nPeople in a hurry took shortcuts. Cautious people avoided the wet ground. Children followed the adult who seemed most certain. The method was natural: everyone only wanted to bring water back.\n\nAfter one season, several faint lines appeared in the grass. Newcomers treated the lines as rules, though no elder had ever written a notice.\n\nThe first dispute came from the miller. He disliked the path passing too close to his door, so he set several pots of flowers at the edge. No one announced a change of route, but footsteps slowly bent away.\n\nThe second change was even less obvious. A young woman placed a bread stall beside the bend, and people fetching water in the morning bought a piece of hot bread on the way. The bend became deeper and wider. The third time, a cart came to the village; the driver noticed that he could stop by the bend to change a rope, so wheel tracks were pressed into the same place.\n\nThe \"proper road\" the children later learned already contained the wetland, the flowerpots, the smell of bread, and the wheel ruts at once. After the rainy season, the old faint lines were washed pale by mud. The villagers could have chosen again, but they still followed the bend in memory, because there were stalls there, places to stop, and familiar ways of giving way to one another.\n\nLater, when the village built a fence, the elder wanted to draw the road straight and wrote \"Please use the new road\" on a wooden sign. Three days later, the grass beside the new road was still high, while the bend was brighter than before: old people needed to pass the bread stall, the cart driver needed to stop at the bend, and the miller's flowerpots had already become a boundary.\n\nOnly then did the elder see that rules were not written only on wooden signs. They were also written into daily convenience, mutual expectations, and available resources. The next year, young people proposed moving the market to the other side, and the road began to fork again.\n\nBut the old bend did not disappear. It carried past habits into the new arrangement. Even those who opposed the old road first had to use it to move timber and stalls to the new site.\n\nThe villagers began to argue: did the path force people to walk that way, or did people themselves wear the path into the grass? They spread the old map on the table and looked out the window at the grass lines polished by footsteps. Only then did they see that the answer did not belong to either side alone.\n\nFootsteps made the road, and the road then gave later footsteps ease, expectation, and limits. The flowerpots, the bread stall, the wheel ruts, and the fence were not background; they were resources that changed action.\n\nYears later, scholars would call this mutual production structuration theory: social practice is produced by human action, and at the same time becomes rules and resources that shape future action.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Structuration theory is commonly associated with Anthony Giddens. It holds that social structures are both the medium and the outcome of social practice. People act within rules and resources, while repeated action also reproduces or changes those rules and resources.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "Which \"obvious\" path in your life exists only because many people have kept walking that way?"
  },
  "04-the-market-with-three-doors": {
    "title": "The Market with Three Doors",
    "summary": "A town discovers that the price tag is not the whole cost of a choice.",
    "scene": "A small town had to prepare thick winter coats for all its children before winter arrived.",
    "storyBody": "A small town needed to prepare thick winter coats for all the children before winter arrived. The first door led to an open market, where sellers shouted the lowest prices and cloth was piled like small hills.\n\nAt first, the mayor chose the cheapest stall, because the budget was limited and the children were indeed cold. When the first coats arrived, they looked fine.\n\nBut two weeks later, cuffs split and buttons fell off. The seller said the children were too rough; parents said the stitching was too shallow. No one could prove where responsibility lay. The second door led to a guild workshop. The coats were more expensive, and every stitch was checked.\n\nQuality became stable, but the town was trapped by one very slow workshop, and the late coats left the children on the north slope cold first. The mayor tried giving half the order to the market and half to the guild. The result was that size charts did not match, restocking dates failed to line up, and the warehouse keeper spent every day running between different promises.\n\nBehind the third door was a long corridor where clerks wrote commitments, penalties, delivery dates, cloth standards, inspection methods, and what would count as genuinely warm. At first the mayor thought the papers were too thick. Only after calculating did she see that what was expensive was not only the listed price: it also included finding reliable sellers, inspecting quality, handling disputes, preventing delay, and writing promises strongly enough to withstand bad weather.\n\nWinter came earlier than forecast. One seller tried to replace wool with a thin lining, saying no one could tell from the outside; the inspection sheet stopped that shipment.\n\nAnother workshop demanded a sudden price increase, and penalties plus backup suppliers kept the town from having to accept it. Another time, parents found that the sizes were too small. The old contract had listed only quantity; the new contract included fittings, returns, exchanges, and a second delivery date, so the argument did not drag on while children stayed cold.\n\nIn the end, she asked clerks, sellers, parents, and tailors to sit at one table. She neither worshipped the lowest price nor gave all the work to a single workshop. The inspection sheet, sample coat, penalties, restocking window, and dispute record all became part of the coat.\n\nWhat the town learned was not that the market was bad and the guild good, nor that more paper was always better. It learned that every form of exchange carries hidden friction. The value of institutions often appears only in bad weather, information asymmetry, and moments when someone tries to exploit a loophole.\n\nTransaction cost economics speaks to exactly this: institutions exist partly because exchange requires search, negotiation, monitoring, enforcement, and protection against opportunism.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Transaction cost economics studies why firms, contracts, markets, and institutions take different forms. It looks beyond price to the costs of exchange: search, negotiation, monitoring, enforcement, asset specificity, uncertainty, and opportunism.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "What hidden work is required before a seemingly cheap choice can become a reliable promise?"
  },
  "05-the-lighthouse-and-the-fog": {
    "title": "The Lighthouse and the Fog",
    "summary": "A harbour keeper learns to revise judgment before absolute certainty arrives.",
    "scene": "The harbor keeper had an old notebook that recorded storms.",
    "storyBody": "The harbour keeper had an old booklet recording storms. When clouds gathered over the western cliff, boats would usually delay departure.\n\nIf the clouds dispersed quickly, the fishing boats could still leave before afternoon. Young sailors liked to demand one blunt answer: will there be a storm?\n\nThe harbour keeper refused to pretend that the sea owed them a clear answer. One morning, the cliff was hidden by fog, and the old rule in the booklet first pushed his judgment toward caution.\n\nBut the wind carried a dry smell, and the gulls were flying low; the signs were not moving in the same direction. He laid a handful of small stones on the table: black stones represented the share of past seasons in which storms had appeared, white stones represented today's new signs, and small shells represented how reliable each sign had been in the past.\n\nDark clouds pushed several stones toward closing the harbour. Dry wind pushed several back toward opening it. Falling pressure moved three stones together. The sailors complained that the stones gave no answer.\n\nAt ten in the morning, sunlight suddenly lit a patch of sea, and several boat owners urged him to let them go. He did not treat the brightness as evidence that overturned the whole judgment; he only moved a few white stones gently back toward the middle.\n\nAt noon, a messenger from the outer island arrived and said the far sea was growing rough. The harbour keeper checked the booklet, found that this signal had been more reliable in the past than low-flying gulls, and moved the stones again.\n\nIn the afternoon, a second messenger said the north bay was calm. He looked at the wind direction and realized that the north bay was sheltered from the wind and could not be weighed the same as the open sea. Another old captain offered his own experience, saying fog like this often cleared quickly.\n\nThe harbour keeper did not reject him. He only asked whether that experience came from near shore or open water, spring or late autumn, a calm bay or an exposed channel. Once the experience was put back into its conditions, its weight changed.\n\nIn the end, he closed the harbour to large boats, allowed only small boats to remain near shore, and wrote on the board how each signal had changed the judgment. By evening, the storm brushed the coast but did not strike it directly.\n\nThe sailors thought he had guessed correctly. The harbour keeper put the stones back in the bag: he was not prophesying, and he was not treating the old booklet as an oracle. He was continually updating an earlier judgment as new evidence arrived. The next day, he also wrote the error into the booklet, because a storm that did not hit would also change the next judgment.\n\nReliable judgment does not only reward hits; it also punishes overconfidence. Slowly, the harbour learned to hear him speak in probabilities instead of forcing him to speak in guarantees.\n\nThis is Bayesian inference: begin with a prior belief, then adjust that belief according to new evidence and its reliability, and make decisions under uncertainty.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Bayesian inference treats knowledge as an updatable degree of belief. Prior belief is revised by new evidence, and the impact of evidence depends on how likely it is under different hypotheses. It is an important foundation for modern statistics, machine learning, scientific modelling, and decision-making under uncertainty.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "Which judgment are you treating as a fixed answer, when it should actually be updated as new evidence arrives?"
  },
  "06-the-islands-with-one-ledger": {
    "title": "The Islands with One Ledger",
    "summary": "Several islands try to maintain one shared ledger while delayed, duplicated, and missing messages keep disrupting trust.",
    "scene": "Five islands shared one ledger of fish catches.",
    "storyBody": "Five islands shared one fish ledger. Every evening, boats returned to different ports, and each port wrote down how many fish had been caught, who had bought them, and which family was still owed salt money.\n\nAt first, the islanders trusted the fastest messenger: whoever rowed to the central island first would announce the day's total. This worked well on clear days, and it saved everyone effort.\n\nThen a storm delayed one messenger, another copied seventy as seventeen, two islands sold fish according to different ledger pages, and a third island refused to deliver. The elders first tried sending messengers with louder voices, but shouting across the sea could not cure delay.\n\nThey also tried keeping every version, and merchants soon stopped trusting any record. One merchant took advantage of the confusion and used two different ledger pages to demand payment, forcing the islands to admit that the problem was not who had the loudest voice, but who could keep everyone on the same page while messages were incomplete.\n\nAt last, the elders established a heavy ritual: one island would propose the next page number and a summary of the previous page; the other islands would first confirm that they had seen the same earlier text, then send back agreement or objection. Only after enough islands accepted it would the page receive the sea-salt seal.\n\nIf the proposer disappeared into fog, another island had to wait two bell rings before taking over and proposing the same page. In the first week, everyone complained it was slow.\n\nIn the second week, one boat went missing, but the ledger did not split. In the third week, the island that copied a number wrongly was stopped by the majority replies.\n\nLater, two islands proposed the next page at the same time. Under the old method, this would have become two ledgers.\n\nThe new ritual required each island to compare previous text, page number, and number of replies. In the end, only the page that first gained majority confirmation remained, while the other was copied into the book of discarded pages. Each night when accounts were closed, the farthest island might still lag half a page behind, but it knew which page to catch up from.\n\nThe central island also could not rewrite everyone's record merely because it arrived first. Later, when a new island joined, the first thing it learned was not the fish price, but which page had already been accepted by enough islands.\n\nTo join the record, it had to accept this slow but reliable rhythm, and accept that sometimes it would have to wait for others to confirm. Trade became possible again, not because messages became faster, and not because every island could see the whole sea, but because the ledger could finally withstand delay, error, competing proposals, and partial vision.\n\nThis ritual is the shape of distributed consensus: separated machines can still agree on one shared state under delay, failure, and incomplete information.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Distributed consensus refers to a class of problems and algorithms in which multiple nodes still agree on the same state when messages are delayed, duplicated, reordered, or when some nodes fail. It supports replicated databases, blockchains, coordination systems, and fault-tolerant services.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "Which team you know needs a reliable shared record more than it needs the fastest voice?"
  },
  "07-the-mill-that-listened-to-wind": {
    "title": "The Mill That Listened to Wind",
    "summary": "A miller learns that power without correction can tear a machine apart.",
    "scene": "On the ridge stood the strongest mill in the valley.",
    "storyBody": "On the ridge stood the strongest mill in the whole valley. In mild weather, it ground grain fine and even, and the villagers said the miller knew his craft.\n\nBut whenever sudden strong winds came, the millstones spun too fast, the flour scorched, belts snapped, and the beams trembled with them. The villagers first blamed bad wind, and the miller thought the same.\n\nHe replaced the belts with thicker ones. The belts did break later, but when they broke, they tore the shaft with them. He then replaced the millstones with heavier ones, thinking weight would mean stability.\n\nThe result was that in a light breeze the stones would not move, while in strong wind they still overshot. Later he hired a boy to stand at the door and shout whenever the sails turned too fast.\n\nThe boy shouted in time, but by the time the shout reached the miller's hands, the stones had already overshot, and the smell of scorched flour entered the room first. After the third accident, the miller did not strengthen the mill again. Instead, he watched and listened to the shaft for several days.\n\nHe hung the flour sieve on the wall, recorded which speeds made coarse flour and which speeds made the flour heat up, and put wind direction, sail angle, and belt tension on the same wooden board. The records showed him that the danger was not wind itself, but that the mill learned too late that it had already drifted away from the right speed.\n\nOne winter, he tied a set of swinging weights to the shaft. When the shaft sped up, the weights swung outward and pulled the sails back a little.\n\nWhen the shaft slowed, the weights came inward again, letting the sails catch wind once more. During the first trial, the mill did not become stronger, but it became more responsive.\n\nHe soon discovered, however, that weights that were too heavy could also cause trouble. After a gust passed, the sails were pulled too low, and the stones became too slow to grind wheat. So he changed to lighter weights and adjusted the rods so that the correction would not be rougher than the deviation itself.\n\nLater, as the wind rose and fell, the weights opened and closed with it, as if a hand had been left inside the mill. By harvest season, the flour was no longer sometimes coarse and sometimes scorched, and the boy no longer had to shout himself hoarse.\n\nThe miller also left one rule: every time the weights were changed, the flour from one sack of wheat had to be checked first, instead of looking only at how elegantly the machine turned. If the flour got worse, that meant the controller also needed to be controlled, and the target itself had to be measured clearly again.\n\nThe miller finally saw that stability does not come from hardening once and for all. It comes from continuously sensing differences and sending those differences back into action, while also keeping the correction itself from going too far. This is feedback control: measure the system output, compare it with the target state, and use the difference to adjust the input.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Feedback control is a core idea in engineering and automation. A controller observes output, compares it with a target state, and then adjusts input to reduce error. It appears in thermostats, engines, robots, industrial process control, and biological regulation.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "Which system around you keeps being reinforced, when what it really needs is better feedback?"
  },
  "08-the-orchard-that-kept-notebooks": {
    "title": "The Orchard That Kept Notebooks",
    "summary": "An orchard keeper learns to treat each action as an experiment when managing living land.",
    "scene": "An orchard grew at the edge of a dry plain.",
    "storyBody": "An orchard grew at the edge of a dry plain. In some years the apples were very sweet, in some years they split before harvest, and in some years insects arrived suddenly as if they had received a secret invitation.\n\nAt first, the orchard keeper wanted one permanent rule: always water on the same day, always prune in the same month, and spray as soon as the first leaf appeared. The idea was not absurd. When there are many trees, people need rules to save effort.\n\nIn the first year, the rule seemed effective. In the second year, spring rain came early, and fixed watering rotted the roots of several rows.\n\nIn the third year, insects did not follow the old calendar. The spray came too early, and the helpful insects near the flowers were reduced instead. The town buyer pressed him to give a stable yield, and the workers also wanted to follow the same booklet every year.\n\nA neighbour reminded him not to treat trees like furniture. So he divided the orchard into small plots: one plot was covered early with grass clippings, one delayed pruning, one planted flowers to draw insects away from the fruit, and one kept the old method for comparison.\n\nHe began recording weather, soil moisture, pests, yield, and which mistakes were worth trying again more cautiously. At the end of the first season, the plot covered with grass clippings had held water, but it had also hidden several patches of mould.\n\nIn the second season, he did not simply copy the result. He cut the covering thickness in half and marked the low-lying areas separately. In the third season, an unusual heatwave arrived, and last year's best method suddenly became unstable. He had to treat even \"successful experience\" as a hypothesis that needed to be checked again.\n\nThe apprentice asked why he could not simply announce the best method. Pointing at the four plots, he said that without keeping comparisons, they could not even tell whether change came from weather, soil, or human decision. After each harvest, he no longer asked only which rule was best, but which action had taught the next action.\n\nAfter several seasons, the orchard had not given a perfect answer, but it had become an open-air classroom: the trees' responses, the soil's moisture, the insects' paths, and human decisions corrected one another. Even the buyer learned to look at the records instead of only demanding one number, because behind the number stood the conditions of that season.\n\nIn the end, he changed the rule book into a trial book. The old rules remained, but behind each one there was space for observations, trigger conditions, and questions to check next season. Adaptive management names exactly this practice: in uncertain ecological systems, manage through deliberate action, monitoring, learning, and adjustment, instead of pretending one rule can govern every season.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Adaptive management is a structured approach for complex ecological and resource systems. It accepts that uncertainty cannot be fully removed and treats decisions as learning opportunities: act, monitor results, compare them with expectations, and then adjust the next step.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "In which living system are you demanding one fixed rule, when it can only teach you slowly through its responses?"
  },
  "09-the-town-with-three-fevers": {
    "title": "The Town with Three Fevers",
    "summary": "A clinic discovers that when hardships connect diseases, the diseases can worsen one another.",
    "scene": "The town clinic put coughs in one room, grief in another, and hunger beside the relief table at the back door.",
    "storyBody": "The town clinic put coughing in one room, sadness in another, and hunger at the relief table by the back door. Each room kept tidy records: the cough room counted infections, the quiet room counted sleepless nights, and the relief table counted empty cupboards.\n\nAt first, this division was useful. Nurses could schedule shifts, medicines could be restocked, and doctors knew what they had to handle that day. But by winter, the same families began appearing again and again in all three lines.\n\nA child coughed and missed school, the mother missed work, rent fell behind, meals grew thinner, and the grandmother's old illness worsened too. The doctors first improved each room separately: more cough medicine helped for a few days, more counselling helped for a few nights, and more food parcels helped for a few weeks.\n\nThe problem did not disappear. It only returned through another door. In the second month, a nurse noticed that the damp-housing list, night-shift table, and infection records contained many of the same family names.\n\nIn the third month, volunteers at the relief table wrote reasons for late medical visits on small notes: no money for transport, fear of losing work, no one to watch the children. In the fourth month, the school sent an absence list, and the names overlapped again.\n\nChildren stayed sick longer, mothers had fewer hours, tables were emptier, and the next infection became easier to catch. At the budget meeting, someone asked whether they could simply increase pharmacy funding, because coughing was easiest to count.\n\nThe nurse brought three ledgers to the meeting: beside the same address were mouldy walls, night shifts, rent arrears, sleeplessness, and missed follow-up visits. Later, the clinic pinned all the records to one wall and connected damp housing, unstable work, infection, stress, hunger, absence, and delayed care with lines.\n\nThe diagram on the wall made the staff stop. These illnesses were not merely adjacent; under social pressure, they were feeding one another. So the clinic kept cough medicine, counselling, and food parcels, while also putting housing repair, transport tickets, school communication, and follow-up reminders into the same care plan.\n\nThe wall also changed the conversations inside the clinic. Doctors no longer asked only which day symptoms began; they also asked whether the roof leaked, who could accompany the patient, and whether taking leave would cost a job. A few months later, change did not arrive as a neat miracle, but the families who had queued most repeatedly had fewer doors to run between, and nurses saw earlier which line was tightening again.\n\nSyndemic theory looks at exactly this relationship: how multiple diseases or health hardships gather, interact, and intensify one another within social structural forces.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Syndemic theory studies how two or more diseases or health hardships gather, interact, and worsen one another under social conditions such as poverty, discrimination, housing instability, violence, and limited access to care.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "Which problem are you treating on its own, while nearby problems are actually making it worse?"
  },
  "10-the-restaurant-with-no-menu": {
    "title": "The Restaurant with No Menu",
    "summary": "A restaurant owner discovers that value is not handed over like a finished plate.",
    "scene": "A restaurant owner believed that service meant carrying out perfect dishes.",
    "storyBody": "A restaurant owner believed that service meant carrying out perfect dishes. He polished the plates, trained the servers to move quietly, and printed a menu so thick it looked like a small book.\n\nThe kitchen was indeed careful. Soup temperature, meat doneness, and dessert plating were checked again and again. Yet guests were still often confused: someone wanted a quiet conversation but was seated by the door.\n\nSomeone rushing for a train only wanted to eat quickly, but was recommended the slowest stew. Someone worried about allergies felt embarrassed asking questions inside a menu full of pages.\n\nThe owner was angry. He felt the kitchen had clearly done everything right. The first warning came from a tired father. He ordered the signature dish, but what he really wanted first was a bowl of hot soup to calm his child.\n\nThe second came from two travellers. They praised the flavour but left half the table untouched because they had to leave in fifteen minutes. The owner thought the problem was unclear explanation, so he made the servers memorize the menu. Guests still could not ask for what they needed.\n\nHe also tried discounts and more signature sets. After a brief bustle, complaints did not decrease, because discounts could not solve hurry, allergies, conversation, or remembered taste. One evening, the menu printer broke, and the head server had to ask each table: what kind of meal do you need tonight?\n\nThe answers pulled the kitchen back toward the table. The father needed soup first. The travellers needed dishes they could share and finish. An older guest wanted the taste he remembered, but with less salt. A student dining alone wanted only a seat where the light was not sharp.\n\nThe kitchen did not become less professional because of this. It moved closer to real use. A few weeks later, the menu was printed again, but the first page was no longer the signature dishes. It was a few small questions about time, restrictions, mood, and the relationship at the table.\n\nServers could also carry guests' answers back to the kitchen, instead of carrying in only dish names. The owner also realized that guests were not coming to manage the kitchen; they were bringing their own situation into a meal, and the restaurant had to know how to receive those situations.\n\nLater, when regular customers brought friends, what they recommended was no longer only a certain dish, but that this place would first ask clearly what the evening needed. At closing time, the owner looked at empty plates, changed seats, and the small notes servers had written, and finally saw that a meal was not made by the kitchen alone.\n\nIt came from ingredients, staff, room, time, memory, choice, and the guest's own purpose. This is service-dominant logic: value is not packed inside a product and handed to a passive customer, but co-created through use, interaction, and relationships.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Service-dominant logic is an important idea in service and marketing theory. It holds that the basis of exchange is not an isolated product but a service process. Value is co-created by users through context of use, interaction, knowledge, and relationships.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "Where are you rushing to deliver value before you understand how the other person will use it?"
  },
  "well-runs-low": {
    "title": "The Well Runs Low",
    "summary": "When the well grows shallow, the town first fights over water and later discovers that shared attention is the scarce resource.",
    "scene": "The well did not disappear on a single morning.",
    "storyBody": "The well did not disappear on a single morning. First the taps slowed. Then the stones beside the old pipe were always damp. The vegetable gardens needed more and more buckets.\n\nThe town's way of doing things could keep matters moving at first: whoever lacked water first went to the well first; whoever had the more urgent matter spoke a few more sentences.\n\nThat could barely keep one day running, but it pushed maintenance, priorities, and shared memory to the side. Only when the bakery alarm rang and the water pressure was too low to connect the fire hose did the old method fail.\n\nToma wanted to save water for seedlings. Sana first asked how long the clinic could last. Niko unfolded the repair drawing he had carried for weeks. Aya asked everyone to put their own buckets under the table and first trace the pipe, well mouth, gardens, and hydrant together. The most dangerous part of the old method was that it made everyone think they were only protecting one bucket of water.\n\nBut the well was not a private object. It tied kitchens, the clinic, gardens, fire protection, and road work together. As long as those relationships were not drawn, the next alarm would still push everyone back into fighting over water.\n\nAya also asked people to write the dates of the past three repairs, two water stoppages, and fire drills on the stone board beside the well. Once those dates that had once been only complaints stood in a row, the repeated delay of maintenance became visible.\n\nThe question was no longer only \"who needs water most right now,\" but \"how does this well support food, health, livelihood, and safety at the same time?\" When the leak points, water-use peaks, and repair delays were placed on the same diagram, the well changed from background into evidence: the crisis had not arrived suddenly; the system had been whispering for a long time.\n\nSo water allocation stopped being temporary goodwill and became a public arrangement that had to be recorded, maintained, and examined together.",
    "knowledgePoint": "A visible crisis is often the last chapter of an invisible system. The well can be seen as a crossing point of resources, maintenance, health, agriculture, fire protection, and trust; the real judgment is not who is more urgent, but which relationship has gone unseen for too long.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "When a shared resource runs low, should a community first limit demand, repair supply, or redesign the rules?"
  },
  "bread-price-debate": {
    "title": "The Hidden Bill in a Cheap Lunch",
    "summary": "Fairness, price, and cost structure ask who benefits behind a price, who carries the cost, and whether the arrangement is truly fair.",
    "scene": "In the school cafeteria, a new lunch set cost only three euros. Students stood in a long line, and the menu board said, \"Affordable for everyone.\"",
    "storyBody": "In the school cafeteria, a new lunch set cost only three euros. Students stood in a long line, and the menu board said, \"Affordable for everyone.\" But during a break, one kitchen worker said, \"Cheap is cheap, yes, but this week they scheduled two fewer of us.\"\n\nFrom the students' point of view, the low price felt fair. Everyone could buy a hot meal for less money, and students under little financial pressure and students under heavy pressure paid the same price. The lower the price, the more it seemed to show that the service was taking care of more people.\n\nBut the bill had not disappeared. It had only been moved elsewhere. Ingredient suppliers were asked to lower prices, kitchen staffing was compressed, portions were quietly made smaller, and cleaning time was shortened. The part students paid less might be carried by worker intensity, ingredient quality, supplier margins, or the future stability of the service.\n\nLater, the cafeteria manager wrote the cost of the lunch set on paper in separate parts: ingredients, labour, energy, cleaning, equipment maintenance, and waste loss. Only after seeing this did the student representatives realize that price was not a single number, but a set of distribution decisions. A three-euro lunch was not impossible, but it had to explain who was subsidizing it, how long the subsidy would last, and which costs could not be pressed down.\n\nThe discussion became more specific. Some proposed targeted subsidies for low-income students instead of one uniform low price for everyone. Some suggested reducing waste and using the savings to keep kitchen staff. Others asked for the cost structure to be made public, so that \"cheap\" would no longer be only an advertising phrase.\n\nThe difficulty of fairness, price, and cost structure lies here. A price that looks friendly does not mean costs are being carried fairly. A price that looks high does not necessarily mean someone is overcharging. The real questions are how the price is formed, how costs are shared, who sees the benefits, and who carries pressure that remains unseen.\n\nA few weeks later, the cafeteria kept the low-price meal, but added an explanation of the subsidy and restored part of the kitchen schedule. As students left carrying their trays, the price board still said three euros. What had changed was that more people now knew there was another bill behind those three euros, and it had to be looked at carefully.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Fairness, price, and cost structure focus on how prices are formed, how costs are shared, how subsidies work, which external costs are displaced, and how fairness is distributed across different groups.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "When something looks very cheap, do you ask who is carrying the cost of the part you are not paying?"
  },
  "school-curriculum-debate": {
    "title": "The School Curriculum Debate",
    "summary": "A school meeting asks a harder question than what to teach: what should a learner be able to notice?",
    "scene": "Lina brought three lesson plans and expected the meeting to end with a quick vote.",
    "storyBody": "Lina brought three lesson plans and expected the meeting to end with a quick vote. The old method looked reliable: arrange the course by chapters, write the goals clearly, and use exams to check what students had remembered.\n\nA school needs this kind of order; otherwise every person will pull the classroom toward whatever they personally care about. But Ren did not bring another lesson plan. He brought a stack of small records: students could recite definitions, yet stopped in front of a broken bus timetable.\n\nThey could state health concepts, yet could not read a medicine label. They could repeat media literacy, yet did not know what to check first when a rumour spread through the class chat.\n\nSomeone said school should not become real life itself. Sana did not answer the slogan. She simply placed several records on the whiteboard.\n\nLina erased the original agenda and wrote, \"What should a child be able to notice?\" The limit of the old method was not that facts did not matter, but that facts had been arranged too neatly.\n\nIn real life, students never meet a problem labelled \"Chapter Number.\" They meet mixed situations that contain words, numbers, bodies, trust, and judgment at the same time. If the curriculum does not train this transfer, answers stay on paper.\n\nRen did not use the phrase \"life is complex\" to overpower everyone else. He read aloud, one by one, the three moments where students had become stuck: unable to read, unsure how to check, afraid to judge. The meeting therefore gained pressure from evidence.\n\nThe question was no longer only \"should this chapter be added to the curriculum,\" but \"what does the curriculum train students to notice, connect, and check first inside disorder?\" Facts still mattered, and tools still mattered.\n\nBut they no longer lay flat inside a list. They had to be able to follow students out of the classroom. At that moment, the timetable did not become an answer, but it began to look like a map: it should tell children where to look first when they meet confusion.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Learning is not only storing answers; it is also building attention. Curriculum quietly decides what is worth noticing, what may be ignored, and whether learners can carry facts, tools, and judgment into real situations.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "If school time is limited, what should a curriculum protect first: facts, tools, judgment, or character?"
  },
  "broad-street-pump": {
    "title": "Black Dots Beside the Pump Handle",
    "summary": "A neighbourhood map made disease no longer only a matter of sickbeds.",
    "scene": "In 1854 London Soho, the streets were narrow, the houses crowded, and the air held the smell of sewage and dampness.",
    "storyBody": "In 1854 London Soho, the streets were narrow, the houses crowded, and the air held the smell of sewage and dampness. Within a few days, many people suddenly suffered diarrhoea and dehydration, then died quickly. Neighbours closed doors and windows, scattered lime, and avoided bad smells, because many people at the time believed cholera came from foul air.\n\nThat understanding was not absurd in its own time. City drainage was poor, the air smelled terrible, and patients often appeared in the dirtiest places. People could smell the stench, but they could not see what was in the water. Blaming disease on bad air at least matched the world they could feel in front of them.\n\nBut John Snow did not look only at smell. He began collecting the addresses where deaths had occurred and marking them on a neighbourhood map. One black dot represented one place of death. As more and more black dots were drawn, a dense area gradually appeared on the map, and many cases clustered around the public water pump on Broad Street.\n\nThe map did not give the whole answer immediately. Snow still had to check exceptions: why had some people who lived nearby not become ill? Why had some people who lived farther away been infected? He found that some who lived far away had drunk water from that pump, while some nearby people, because they drank water from elsewhere, had not fallen ill. The cases were no longer only scattered tragedies; they were connected by a path of fetching water.\n\nPublic health evidence became powerful through this kind of checking. It did not look only at one patient, and it did not listen to only one explanation. It placed addresses, behaviour, environment, and exceptions together. The map, visit records, water-fetching habits, and anomalous cases allowed an invisible risk to begin taking shape.\n\nLater, the handle of the Broad Street pump was removed. That action did not instantly explain every cholera problem, and it could not replace the more complete microbiological knowledge that came later. But it made one important point clear: when disease spreads through a population, evidence can grow out of streets, addresses, and daily habits.\n\nThe black dots on that map looked at first like records of where deaths had happened. But when they gathered around the pump, the map became a public health tool. It led people to ask: disease does not begin simply where things \"smell worse,\" but where people share, touch, and drink something in common.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Public health evidence examines how population data, spatial distribution, behavioural pathways, exception checking, and environmental clues work together to support health decisions.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "When an explanation matches intuition, will you still look for the exceptions that do not match it?"
  },
  "challenger-launch-decision": {
    "title": "The Challenger Launch Decision",
    "summary": "Before the 1986 Challenger launch, engineers warned that cold could keep the O-rings from sealing, but the organization still found a way to say yes.",
    "scene": "On the night of January 27, 1986, before there was any flame on the launch pad, the argument had already crowded into a teleconference.",
    "storyBody": "On the night of January 27, 1986, before there was any flame on the launch pad, the argument had already crowded into a teleconference. On the table were temperature forecasts, old flight records, and several diagrams of O-rings.\n\nThe old method looked like the routine action of an engineering meeting: present data, explain risk, and let management judge whether to continue. It was not without order.\n\nSpaceflight programmes had to make choices every day between complex evidence and schedule pressure. But this time, low temperature pressed against the old order.\n\nMorton Thiokol engineers worried that under unusually cold conditions, the rubber O-rings would not seal the joints of the solid rocket boosters in time, and they recommended not launching below the previous experience boundary of 53 degrees Fahrenheit. Then the question quietly changed direction.\n\nThe meeting no longer asked, \"Has the system proven it is safe?\" Instead, engineers were asked to prove, \"It is certainly unsafe.\" After management reconsidered offline, the recommendation was overturned. The next day, Challenger lifted off and broke apart 73 seconds later.\n\nThe later investigation identified the right-side solid rocket motor joint seal failure, and also identified failure in the decision process itself: warnings existed, but they did not receive a path clear enough, protected enough, and strong enough to stop action. The frightening part of the old process was that it still looked like a normal process.\n\nSomeone presented data, someone asked for evidence, someone carried responsibility for schedule; every step could be explained as a work requirement. Once the burden of proof was shifted, risk no longer had to prove that it did not exist.\n\nInstead, the warning had to prove that disaster was inevitable. That reversal turned risk management from a technical judgment into an organizational problem: who can carry bad news to the person truly able to stop the button?",
    "knowledgePoint": "Challenger was not only a machine failure, but also a failure in the pathway of knowledge. In a high-risk system, the real question is not whether someone knows the danger, but whether the warning has the authority to interrupt momentum.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "In a high-risk decision, who should carry the burden of proof: the person warning, or the system wanting to proceed?"
  },
  "cuban-missile-crisis-excomm": {
    "title": "Thirteen Days at the Nuclear Edge",
    "summary": "In October 1962, Kennedy's advisers argued among air strike, invasion, and blockade options as the world moved close to nuclear war.",
    "scene": "In October 1962, U-2 reconnaissance photographs lay spread across a conference table, showing launch sites still under construction in black and white.",
    "storyBody": "In October 1962, U-2 reconnaissance photographs lay spread across a conference table, showing launch sites still under construction in black and white. The original question seemed direct: how should the Soviet missiles in Cuba be removed?\n\nThe question was not naive, because the missiles were real and time was tightening. But every fast answer carried the danger of the next step.\n\nAir strikes might miss missiles. An invasion might kill Soviet personnel. A hard public statement might close the exit for negotiation, while weakness might make deterrence lose credibility. Kennedy did not immediately go public. He convened ExComm to compare military action, wording, timing, and the room the other side would still have to step back.\n\nThe danger in the original question was that it also treated the opponent as a piece on a board with no internal pressure. What made the meeting room truly difficult was that every action would be read at the same time by Moscow, Havana, allies, the military, and the public.\n\nCrisis management was therefore not only choosing a tool, but designing a sequence of signals that the other side could still accept and one's own side could still explain. The photographs were only the entry point.\n\nAdvisers also had to compare fleet positions, public speeches, private channels, and the tone of Khrushchev's letters. Each item could change how the next step would be read.\n\nThe problem was no longer only \"how to remove the threat,\" but \"how to apply pressure while still leaving the opponent an acceptable way out.\" The eventual choice of a naval \"quarantine\" was one level lower than direct attack, while still pushing the crisis into the public arena.\n\nThe later settlement included Soviet removal of missiles from Cuba, a US pledge not to invade Cuba, and the secret removal of Jupiter missiles from Turkey. After the crisis ended, a hotline and nuclear test limitation talks continued to appear, because both sides had seen how fragile command, language, and time could be inside a nuclear crisis.",
    "knowledgePoint": "The deepest achievement of the crisis was not victory, but keeping escalation within a range where negotiation remained possible. Military capacity, political signals, historical memory, language, time, and public legitimacy acted at once; no single viewpoint was enough to explain the choices in the room.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "When a crisis requires both firmness and an exit, how should leaders decide what to make public and what to keep private?"
  },
  "000-general-starter-course": {
    "title": "A Night With a List of Questions",
    "summary": "A night discussion in the Junto turned experience from the print shop, the street, and books into a method people could practice together.",
    "scene": "In Philadelphia in 1727, a young printer finished the day's work and brought a list of questions into a night meeting of the Junto.",
    "storyBody": "During the day, most problems in the print shop had clear shapes: had the type been set correctly, was there enough paper, had the accounts been collected? At night, the problems became more scattered. Several people left their counters, workshops, and businesses and brought the troubles of the week to one table: how to prevent fires, where books could be borrowed, how to keep currency shortages from crushing small shops, and how young apprentices could continue reading.\n\nThese matters could originally have remained inside familiar relationships. Masters taught apprentices; friends introduced friends; experience moved slowly through trust and access. But each week, the trouble returned in a slightly different form. One person's method could handle one matter, yet it was hard for that method to become something others could also take up.\n\nThe key to the Junto was not the meeting itself, but the list of questions. Once questions were written down, they were no longer only complaints. Someone went back to check books, someone compared practices on the street, and someone brought back accounts, observations, or material they had read. At the next meeting, the same question might be opened again, or broken into smaller actions.\n\nLearning therefore left the head of a single clever person. It became a repeatable practice: bring experience forward so others can add to it; write daily troubles clearly enough to be checked; place personal difficulties inside public affairs and ask whether they require a library, fire prevention, education, or city improvement.\n\nThe young printer was Benjamin Franklin. The Junto is often seen as one important early entrance into American public learning, associational education, and civic improvement. General learning here was not the name of a course, but an ability to handle recurring problems: when life keeps raising similar questions, people need to ask together, verify together, and revise answers together.",
    "knowledgePoint": "General learning focuses on organizing personal experience, public problems, and cross-field methods into sustainable learning capacity. It emphasizes questioning, discussion, verification, cooperation, and turning experience into public method.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "When a problem appears again and again in different people's lives, is it still only personal experience?"
  },
  "001-birkbeck-evening-lecture": {
    "title": "The Mechanics Class After Work",
    "summary": "Workers brought the tools they had touched during the day into evening class, and practical experience first came close to formal scientific language.",
    "scene": "Around 1799 in Glasgow, a teacher noticed that the people who truly used tools during the day were often kept outside the room where science was explained.",
    "storyBody": "In the daytime factory, machines did not speak in academic terms. They jammed, heated, wore down, and shifted. Workers heard changes in sound, felt the resistance of materials with their hands, and knew from experience where trouble might appear. Knowledge was already in their movements; it simply had not yet been formally recognized.\n\nGeorge Birkbeck saw the contradiction there. The people who touched machinery and materials every day often had no chance to enter the room where mechanics, heat, chemistry, and natural philosophy were explained. Scientific language seemed to be on another floor, while the people downstairs were handling scientific problems with their bodies.\n\nSo the class was scheduled after work. Workers arrived at the lecture after a tiring day, but also with tool experience still fresh in their hands. Instruments and demonstrations pulled abstract terms back into a familiar scene: why force passed this way, why heat changed that way, why a machine could not be explained by feel alone.\n\nThe important part of the class was not that it immediately turned workers into scholars. It first opened a door: you already have experience, so you can keep learning; you do not need complete credentials before you deserve to understand knowledge. Formal learning no longer only stood at the door screening people; it also began to build a first step for existing experience.\n\nLater, mechanics' institutes, evening courses, libraries, and experimental apparatus continued to expand this entrance. Basic programmes and qualifications here were not a cold certificate, but a passage that let real experience enter a world of knowledge that could be explained, practiced, and developed further.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Basic programmes and qualifications build a first recognized bridge between practical readiness and formal learning. They help learners turn existing experience into capacity that can continue, be recognized, and develop.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "Who around you already has real experience, but still needs the first step into formal knowledge?"
  },
  "002-braille-raised-dots": {
    "title": "Six Raised Dots Beneath the Fingertip",
    "summary": "A boy repeatedly tested a cell the fingertip could read, turning reading and writing from something assisted into something independent.",
    "scene": "Between Coupvray and Paris in the 1810s, a blind boy touched heavy embossed books and discovered that reading and writing were still controlled by others.",
    "storyBody": "There were books at the school for blind students, but they were very thick. Raised letters could be touched by the fingers, yet they moved slowly, each page like a heavy board. Reading happened, but it did not yet feel as if it truly belonged to the student. Worse, students could rarely write their own words back easily.\n\nLater, a form of night writing reached the school. It had originally been designed for soldiers to pass messages in the dark by pressing dots into paper, letting fingers read symbols instead of eyes. The idea mattered: writing did not have to be seen. It could also be touched.\n\nLouis Braille tried the method, but met a concrete obstacle: the dots were too large for one fingertip to read a whole unit easily at once. If reading always had to stop and assemble fragments, it could not become fluent action. So he kept shrinking, arranging, and testing until six raised dots formed one small cell.\n\nThat small cell looked simple, yet it could express letters, punctuation, and numbers, and later music as well. It let the fingertip receive one symbol at a time, turning reading from slow recognition into continuous movement. More importantly, it made writing possible too.\n\nThe six raised dots changed more than reading and writing technology. A person could read quietly, write privately, and return to a line again and again without always waiting for another person's voice to carry them into knowledge. The Braille literacy system later became a major foundation for literacy among blind and visually impaired people around the world, and its starting point was a very specific question: can one fingertip independently read one small cell?",
    "knowledgePoint": "Literacy and numeracy are not only school basics; they let people independently enter information, symbols, quantity, memory, and social participation. Accessible writing systems can change the relationship between learners and knowledge.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "When a tool lets someone read without asking another person, what kind of freedom has quietly appeared?"
  },
  "003-carnegie-speaking-class": {
    "title": "Standing Up to Say the First Sentence",
    "summary": "An evening public-speaking course placed personal development between nervousness, practice, listening, and the next attempt.",
    "scene": "In early twentieth-century New York, a young man from a rural background discovered that many adults were not defeated by lack of knowledge, but by the moment when they had to speak.",
    "storyBody": "Many adults did not lack substance. They knew their work, had met customers, handled trouble, and carried plenty of experience. But once they stood before others, the body spoke a different sentence first: the throat tightened, the hands had nowhere to go, and the opening they had prepared suddenly disappeared.\n\nDale Carnegie had worked in sales, tried acting, and taught classes. In his New York evening courses, he saw clerks, salespeople, engineers, and managers come after work. During the day, they could do things. At night, they practiced something harder: saying what they knew to other people.\n\nThe course did not begin with grand theory. One person stood up and told a small real story. Others listened, then the next person spoke. Some practiced remembering names, some practiced giving specific praise, and some learned to move attention away from their own nervousness and toward the audience. Each action was small, but small enough to repeat.\n\nFear was not chased away by one sentence of encouragement. It was broken into actions that could be practiced: open your mouth, pause, look at people, listen, respond, come back next week. Personal skills here were less like personality labels and more like a set of actions that could be trained slowly in social situations.\n\nCarnegie's later courses in public speaking and human relations, together with How to Win Friends and Influence People, influenced modern personal development training. Personal development at this entrance was not about becoming another person. It was about letting experience that could not be spoken find a form that others could receive through repeated public practice.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Personal skills and development focus on self-management, communication, confidence, listening, adaptation, and abilities people can practice in social settings. They emphasize that ability is not gained only by understanding; it also needs repeated practice in concrete situations.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "Which ability in your life would change fastest if it were practiced gently in public every week?"
  },
  "009-brownsea-scout-camp": {
    "title": "The Island Without a School Bell",
    "summary": "The Brownsea Island experimental camp let outdoor tasks, peer responsibility, and civic learning happen in the same day.",
    "scene": "In August 1907, boys from different social backgrounds came to Brownsea Island to camp, cook, observe, signal, play games, and learn through patrols.",
    "storyBody": "There was no ordinary classroom bell on the island. Learning was not divided into separate lessons; it unfolded with the tasks of the day. Tents had to be put up, meals had to be made, routes had to be observed, signals had to be sent, and someone in each patrol always needed help from someone else.\n\nRobert Baden-Powell had been a soldier, but this camp was not only military training. He wanted to test something else: could ordinary young people learn courage, service, outdoor judgment, teamwork, and civic responsibility through practice, instead of only hearing adults explain those words?\n\nThe patrol method made it hard for anyone to hide completely at the side. If one person forgot a task, the patrol felt the effect. If one person cared only for himself, others saw it. Knots, tracking, first aid, and outdoor skills looked like concrete techniques, but they continually pushed people back toward discipline, trust, observation, and responsibility.\n\nThis educational form also needs to be viewed with historical awareness. Some early contexts require careful criticism today. Yet the learning shape left by the Brownsea Island experimental camp remains clear: some abilities are hard to name separately in an ordinary timetable, but they form through shared living, task pressure, and peer feedback.\n\nThe experiment helped launch the Scout movement and opened many general youth programmes that do not fit ordinary school categories. Generic programmes and qualifications not elsewhere classified are not a messy leftover here; they leave room for learning that combines skills, character, community, and self-reliance.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Generic programmes not elsewhere classified preserve hybrid forms of learning, bringing practical skills, character, access capacity, and social participation together. They focus on life abilities and public abilities that no single discipline can fully contain.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "When every lesson must belong to a neat subject, which important life ability becomes harder to learn?"
  },
  "011-dewey-lab-school": {
    "title": "When the Dough Was Too Sticky",
    "summary": "When flour, cloth, and wooden blocks entered the classroom, knowledge began to be needed by real activity.",
    "scene": "In Chicago in 1896, the tables at the Lab School held flour, measuring cups, cloth, wooden blocks, and materials the children were working with.",
    "storyBody": "The flour on the table did not first become a definition. Children measured water, poured flour, kneaded dough, and then found that the dough could be too dry, too sticky, or slow to take shape. At that moment, ratio was no longer a number on the blackboard. It was a demand made by the material in their hands.\n\nCloth was not only for finishing a craft object. It led children toward cotton, spinning, dyeing, and the path by which clothing appears from materials, labour, and tools. Wooden blocks brought a different problem. They tilted, loosened, or failed to support anything because the length was wrong. Measurement, structure, and cooperation therefore entered the same table.\n\nIn a more traditional classroom, the teacher could explain the answer first and students could write it down afterward. That can make knowledge orderly, but it can also leave children remembering sentences without knowing what those sentences are meant to handle. The Lab School experiment reversed the order: first encounter the material, then encounter the difficulty, and only then need disciplinary knowledge to explain and revise action.\n\nIn this way, mathematics was not forced into dough, and history was not pasted onto cloth. Real activity created the problem first; disciplinary knowledge entered afterward. Ratio, production, measurement, verbal expression, and shared discussion were all called up by the same task.\n\nThe University of Chicago Laboratory School, co-founded by John Dewey, became an important experimental site in the history of progressive education. It did not raise a simple question such as whether children enjoy activities. It asked how schools arrange experience so that students form judgment through action, reflection, and shared tasks.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Education studies learning experience, curriculum design, teaching relationships, child development, and how schools organize understanding. Dewey's experience-based learning ideas emphasize that students construct understanding through action, reflection, and social interaction.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "If children meet real materials first and then need knowledge, how should the classroom change?"
  },
  "018-reggio-emilia-school": {
    "title": "A School Built Beside the Ruins",
    "summary": "Postwar Reggio Emilia turned children's learning from a care problem into a project involving community, materials, art, and documentation.",
    "scene": "After the Second World War, a group of parents near Reggio Emilia wanted first to build a school for their children, even though they did not yet have a complete school system.",
    "storyBody": "After the war, a school did not first appear in an institutional document. Parents near Reggio Emilia wanted to build a school for their children. Available materials were brought over, craft skills were used, and what appeared beside the ruins was not a complete system, but a community's insistence on a future.\n\nWhen Loris Malaguzzi heard about the parents' action in the village, he went to see it. What attracted him was not a mature method, but a more basic educational question: if children were to begin again after the war, could school do more than watch over them? Could it help the whole community relearn how to listen to them?\n\nThe school that slowly grew did not divide learning into neat boxes. Children drew, built, argued, listened, shaped, measured, performed, and then returned to revise their own ideas. Materials were not decoration, and environment was not background. Classroom light, walls, tools, and children's work all participated in learning.\n\nThe teacher's work was not only explanation. Teachers observed, documented, and organized the process so that children's thinking could be seen again. Parents entered the school for discussion, and the atelier became an important space for expression and inquiry. Art was not an extra activity; it was one of the languages of children's thinking.\n\nThe Reggio Emilia approach later became known for project learning, process documentation, parent and community participation, and children's many languages of expression. It gives interdisciplinary education a clear image: when children understand the world in more than one way, schools cannot respond in only one way.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Interdisciplinary programmes related to education connect different learning goals so learners use knowledge together rather than storing it separately. The Reggio Emilia approach emphasizes children's expression, project learning, environment design, process documentation, and community participation.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "If a child thinks in more than one language, which disciplines need to stand nearby in order to truly hear them?"
  },
  "020-family-photo-meaning": {
    "title": "Gestures on the Black Cloth Board",
    "summary": "As photographs moved across black cloth boards, the visual memory behind single works became hard to ignore.",
    "scene": "In Hamburg in the late 1920s, a scholar pinned photographic images onto black cloth boards, then removed, shifted, and rearranged them.",
    "storyBody": "When a painting is placed alone in a book, the questions are usually stable: who made it, what year is it from, which style does it belong to, and what story does the image tell? This way of reading protects the details of the work and keeps interpretation from drifting too far.\n\nThe black cloth board changed the viewing distance. Photographs were pinned up one by one, and a single work no longer faced the viewer alone. A raised arm, a tilted body, or a mourning posture might appear again and again across ancient reliefs, Renaissance paintings, and modern images. They were not the same, but they made one realize that certain gestures travel across time.\n\nAby Warburg did not arrange these images into a neat chronology. He pinned photographs up, removed them, and moved them beside another group. Once the neighborhood changed, the question changed as well: was this a continuation of classical tradition, or the reuse of an old form in a new scene? Was the image preserving memory, or changing the use of memory?\n\nThe black cloth board was therefore not a background fabric, but a workbench. It forced viewers to move back and forth among images, watching how forms migrate, how emotion borrows gestures, and how cultural memory hides in repeated actions.\n\nThe Mnemosyne Atlas was never completed and did not organize meaning into a single conclusion. What it left was a humanities practice: remove works from isolated positions, place them inside relationships, time, and context, and watch how images change seeing through adjacency.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Arts and humanities study how images, texts, forms, symbols, and historical contexts generate meaning together. Warburg's image research reminds us that works can be understood not only by author and date, but also through visual memory, migrating gestures, and cultural transmission.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "When two images far apart in time are placed together, are we seeing similarity, or a route of cultural memory?"
  },
  "021-bauhaus-workshop": {
    "title": "The Lamp on the Workbench",
    "summary": "When art returned to materials, tools, and everyday objects, form no longer existed only to be viewed; it also had to be tested by life.",
    "scene": "In Weimar after the First World War, a workshop held paper, metal sheets, fabric, wood, and a lamp sketch that was not yet finished.",
    "storyBody": "In postwar Europe, many things seemed to have been placed apart. Painting and sculpture belonged to the museum, craft belonged to the workshop, machines belonged to the factory, and architecture belonged to another profession. When students learned art, they were often first led toward styles, schools, and works, but not necessarily toward how a piece of wood bears weight, how paper folds, or how a lamp lights a desk.\n\nWhen Walter Gropius founded Bauhaus in Weimar, he was not facing only a question of art curriculum. Modern life was being changed by machines, cities, housing, transportation, and industrial products. People needed chairs, lamps, type, posters, rooms, and buildings, and they needed these things to be useful, clear, and durable in everyday life. Leaving art only on the wall was no longer enough to answer that life.\n\nThe workshop therefore became important. Students did not begin by imitating a fixed style. They first met materials and tools. Paper could fold into new structures, metal could reveal strength through bending, fabric could change its surface through stretching and weaving, and color could lose its stability under different light. Once the hand touched material, imagination was no longer completely free. It had to answer how the material would cooperate and how it would refuse.\n\nA chair, a poster, a lamp, and a building all pushed the question back toward life. The line of a chair may be beautiful, but is it stable when someone sits down? A poster's color may be striking, but can it be read from far away? A lamp may have a novel form, but does its light fall where work is being done? Art was no longer only the expression of private feeling. It began to participate in function, production, reading, dwelling, and public space.\n\nBauhaus was not an ideal space without contradictions. It was shaped by political pressure, financial limits, and the pressures of its age, and it also had its own limits of gender, hierarchy, and educational belief. But it changed the basic imagination of modern art education: art can think through making, craft can meet industry, and design can place beauty, function, and social life on the same workbench.\n\nFounded in 1919, Bauhaus later deeply influenced modern design, architecture, and art education. The image it left is not a room for quiet admiration of works, but a scratched workbench. On it lie materials, sketches, tools, and unfinished objects. Style does not descend from the air. It slowly forms among material resistance, the needs of life, and formal judgment.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Art studies how form, material, image, sound, movement, making, and perception shape human experience. Bauhaus workshop education emphasized the connections among art, craft, design, architecture, and industrial production, testing form through materials, function, and scenes of use.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "Which everyday object around you would change if it were designed at once as art, tool, and life problem?"
  },
  "022-petrarch-mountain-letter": {
    "title": "The Little Book Opened on the Summit",
    "summary": "A climb made for the sake of seeing the landscape drew classical reading, inward examination, and human self-understanding onto the same height.",
    "scene": "In the traditional account, in the spring of 1336, Petrarch and his brother climbed Mont Ventoux; wind moved over the rocks, and he carried a small book of Augustine with him.",
    "storyBody": "Many roads are meant to reach somewhere else. Merchants travel, soldiers march, pilgrims move toward holy places, and farmers cross mountain land to finish the work of the day. On such roads, a mountain is often an obstacle, terrain to be crossed, not a purpose in itself. But in the letter tradition about Petrarch's climb of Mont Ventoux, the reason for going up looks different: he wanted to see the world from above.\n\nThat action seems simple, yet it changed the place of landscape. Landscape was no longer only background, nor only terrain one had to pass through on the way. It became something worth seeking. Standing high up, a person saw lowlands, rivers, distant cities, and roads already traveled enter the field of vision together. The outside world suddenly widened, and attention was forced to lift away from daily affairs.\n\nPetrarch had long loved classical texts, copying letters and searching for the voices of ancient authors. When he faced old books, he did not treat them only as dead material. The words of the past could enter the questions of the present, as long as the reader brought his own desire, confusion, and judgment before the text. An old book was therefore not locked far away. At some moment, it could speak again.\n\nIn the letter about the climb, summit and page overlap. He opened the small book of Augustine that he had brought with him and read a reminder about people pursuing the external world while neglecting themselves. The landscape before him did not disappear, but it received another direction: look far outward, and also look back into oneself. The wide view from the summit became a trigger for inward examination.\n\nScholars can still debate whether every detail of the letter fully meets modern historical standards. More safely, as a text, it clearly presents an interweaving of landscape, classical memory, Christian self-examination, friendship, ambition, and self-understanding. A climb was not written merely as an outdoor experience. It became a way of understanding the human person.\n\nPetrarch is usually called one of the important figures of Renaissance humanism. The humanities here are not only the preservation of old books, nor only talk about distant history. They ask how people use texts, places, memory, and belief to understand themselves. The little book on the summit is like a fine thread, drawing together the outside world, ancient voices, and inner life.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Humanities research studies history, religion, philosophy, ethics, cultural memory, and inner life, asking how people inherit, interpret, and revise meaning. Petrarch's letter about climbing Mont Ventoux is often discussed as an important symbolic text linking classical reading, self-consciousness, and humanism.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "Which old book, place, or memory has let you see yourself again while looking at the outside world?"
  },
  "023-rosetta-cartouche": {
    "title": "The Name Inside the Oval Frame",
    "summary": "When royal names appeared again and again in different scripts, the images on stone were no longer only symbols to be viewed; they began moving back toward sound and history.",
    "scene": "In nineteenth-century France, a desk held copies of the Rosetta Stone, Greek records, Coptic materials, and a string of signs enclosed by oval frames.",
    "storyBody": "The Rosetta Stone was like a door with several locks. The Greek layer was easier to open, and scholars could know that it roughly contained a decree. Another layer of writing also offered clues. But hieroglyphs still looked like a row of silent images: birds, eyes, objects, and lines had clear shapes, yet did not readily become a readable sentence.\n\nIf these signs were treated only as decoration, they could remain only on the surface. Stelae could be collected, tomb walls copied, and patterns admired, but history would still be blocked behind the signs. The problem was not that people could not see these signs. It was that after seeing them, they did not know how they worked: were they drawing things, marking meanings, or recording sounds?\n\nJean-Francois Champollion placed his attention on the royal names enclosed by oval frames. Names were a particularly useful entry point because they appeared repeatedly in different scripts and could also be compared with the royal names in Greek. When the same name left traces in different systems, comparison was no longer only a guess. It had a handle that could be checked again and again.\n\nAs the comparison deepened, the identity of the signs became complex. Some signs that looked like pictures behaved like sounds inside royal names; other signs retained semantic functions. Coptic also provided an important clue for understanding the ancient Egyptian language, letting a language tradition that seemed broken show connection again. Hieroglyphs were no longer only mysterious images, but a system able to record language.\n\nThis process was not completed by one person from blankness. Earlier research, materials in different scripts, competing explanations, and linguistic knowledge all participated. But Champollion's announced breakthrough in 1822 brought the understanding of Egyptian hieroglyphs into a new stage. Stelae, tombs, prayers, names, and official records were therefore no longer only antiquities; they gradually became readable historical materials.\n\nLanguage study here appears as a very concrete action: watch repetition, compare differences, and search for rules between sound and meaning. The royal name inside the oval frame was like a small key. It opened not only a few names, but the way a writing system preserved sound, power, memory, and time.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Language study connects writing, sound, grammar, meaning, translation, and historical context. Champollion's decipherment of Egyptian hieroglyphs shows that writing systems may contain both phonetic and semantic elements, and that decipherment requires cross-language comparison, repeated patterns, contextual materials, and related linguistic knowledge.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "When a sign changes from decoration into readable language, what happens to our relationship with the past?"
  },
  "028-black-mountain-studio": {
    "title": "The Classroom Beside the Dining Table",
    "summary": "In a very small college, materials, labor, poetry, performance, and shared life were placed together, making the boundaries of learning less tidy.",
    "scene": "In North Carolina in the 1930s, at a small college, students moved among classrooms, kitchens, workshops, and temporary performance spaces.",
    "storyBody": "Some colleges have very clear boundaries. The classroom is where class happens, the dormitory is where rest happens, the kitchen is where people eat, and the workshop is where things are made. A timetable cuts knowledge into separate boxes. Students enter different rooms by the hour and then carry the content of each course away separately.\n\nBlack Mountain College was small, small enough that these boundaries were hard to keep intact. Students did not only sit in class and listen. They also took part in school affairs, lived with teachers, worked, discussed, cooked, and built. Learning did not happen only before a blackboard. It also happened while moving materials, preparing meals, arranging space, watching performances, and arguing over a decision.\n\nJosef Albers brought material and form training from the Bauhaus workshop tradition. His course did not rush to begin with the explanation of famous works. It asked students to face paper, color, glass, leaves, wire, pressure, balance, and habits of seeing. Materials did not automatically obey concepts. Folded paper produced new structures; colors placed beside one another changed each other; weight and light changed how an object was perceived.\n\nLater, the college attracted dancers, poets, composers, painters, textile artists, architects, and thinkers. Different practices were not simply arranged as a row of course names. They collided through shared life and shared making. One work might involve sound, body, space, words, and material at the same time; one discussion might move from art toward education, politics, labor, and human relationships.\n\nInterdisciplinarity here was not choosing a few extra courses, nor placing several field names on the same poster. It was an arrangement of learning: making, reading, perceiving, performing, and shared labor were placed in the same site. Boundaries became unstable not because order was missing, but because many important questions actually happen between categories.\n\nBlack Mountain College is known for experimental, interdisciplinary arts and liberal education. What it left was not a neat model that can be copied easily, but a reminder: if tools, books, bodies, dining tables, arguments, and performances can all become classrooms, then arts and humanities are not only content to be learned. They also become a way of living together and understanding the world together.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Interdisciplinary programs related to arts and humanities place making, interpretation, history, language, performance, material, and lived experience inside one field of inquiry. They emphasize that artistic and humanistic knowledge often forms where material, body, text, space, and shared life meet.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "If class happened not only in classrooms but also at dining tables, workshops, performances, and arguments, how would you understand learning differently?"
  },
  "030-neighbor-notice-board": {
    "title": "After Poverty Was Painted in Color",
    "summary": "Hull-House's neighborhood maps turned stories of need into urban evidence that could be discussed.",
    "scene": "In Chicago in the 1890s, the streets, factories, and tenements near Hull-House were marked square by square on maps.",
    "storyBody": "Near Hull-House, poverty was not a distant statistical term. Children ran down crowded stairways, workers moved in and out by shifts, and immigrant families cooked, mended, and took casual work in cramped rooms. Every family had its own story, but after hearing many stories, one could also end up seeing only immediate requests for help.\n\nCharity could bring food, clothing, and short-term aid, but it struggled to answer another question: why did low wages, illness, language barriers, and high rents keep appearing again and again in neighboring streets? If many families were surrounded by similar pressures, the problem was not only one family's character or luck.\n\nJane Addams and her Hull-House colleagues began to do another kind of work. They visited homes, recorded occupation, income, nationality, and living conditions, and then painted those data onto neighborhood maps. Once the colors spread, poverty was no longer a series of scattered pleas for help. It was pressed onto one map together with factory locations, housing density, migration paths, schools, and public health.\n\nThe map changed the direction of the question. It pushed \"who needs help\" toward \"what conditions place many people in difficulty at the same time.\" The colors were not meant to judge people, but to make urban structures visible, comparable, and debatable.\n\nHull-House Maps and Papers became an important early case of social investigation and public reform. The power of social science here was not turning human suffering into cold data. It was giving sympathy evidence to stand on, so public problems no longer had to be handled only through moral judgment.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Social science studies how populations, institutions, cities, relationships, and public problems can be understood and improved through evidence. Social investigation turns individual experience into comparable public material, making social problems discussable, explainable, and reformable.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "When poverty appears across a map in clusters, does responsibility still belong only to one family?"
  },
  "040-kitchen-repair-budget": {
    "title": "After the Ledger Left the Counter",
    "summary": "When ledgers began to involve railroads, contracts, and public responsibility, business education entered the university.",
    "scene": "In Philadelphia in 1881, a university began placing factory accounts, contracts, finance, and public policy inside business education.",
    "storyBody": "In small shops and workshops, business experience often hid behind the counter. Masters taught apprentices how to keep accounts, how to read people, when to bargain hard, and when to honor trust. Much judgment did not come from books, but from repeated transactions, debts, and promises.\n\nThis kind of experience was powerful in familiar markets. But when railroads, steel, insurance, banking, and interstate trade stretched transactions longer, a ledger no longer recorded only the income and spending of one shop. It connected to loans, inventory, wages, freight rates, tariffs, contractual responsibility, and public rules. One mistaken judgment could affect suppliers, workers, and investors.\n\nThe question therefore shifted from \"how do you make a good deal\" to \"how do you understand an organization within society.\" Joseph Wharton wanted universities to cultivate people who understood business, political economy, and public responsibility, not only shopkeepers trained to make money. Business education needed to put ledgers, contracts, finance, and law on the same table.\n\nThe Wharton School was founded at the University of Pennsylvania in 1881 and is usually regarded as one of the earliest university business schools in the United States. The turn it represented was not replacing experience with classrooms, but making experience subject to more systematic training and examination.\n\nBusiness, administration, and law were thereby connected. How resources are allocated, how rules are made, how responsibility is carried, and how value is created cannot be answered by personal tricks alone. After the ledger left the counter, business began to become a public method that could be taught, debated, and held accountable.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Business, administration, and law focus on how organizations allocate resources, carry responsibility, make rules, and create value in society. Modern business education trains experience, accounts, organization, law, and public responsibility within one framework.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "When one ledger affects workers, capital, and public rules, is business still only personal experience?"
  },
  "050-balcony-plant-observation": {
    "title": "The Mountain Was No Longer Only Background",
    "summary": "Humboldt placed plants, altitude, and air pressure on the same chart, turning nature from names into relationships.",
    "scene": "On the Andean slopes around 1802, Humboldt wrote plant names, altitude, temperature, and air pressure into the same notebook.",
    "storyBody": "Pick a leaf, press it into a specimen folder, write down its name and location: this was reliable and important work in natural history. Specimens were preserved so later observers could compare shapes, identify species, and trace where they had come from.\n\nWhen Alexander von Humboldt explored the Americas, the question did not stop at names. As he moved up the mountainside, the plants kept changing. Plants in the lowlands, plants near the clouds, and plants in the thin air above were not merely different species. Their appearance seemed to move together with altitude, temperature, humidity, air pressure, and terrain.\n\nThe mountainside therefore was no longer only background. Humboldt added altitude, air pressure, and position to his notes, turning observation into a set of comparable data. Numbers stood beside plant names; environmental conditions stood beside specimens. Nature no longer looked like a row of collected objects, but like a set of variables pulling on one another.\n\nIn images such as the Chimborazo Naturgemalde, the mountain body, plant zones, and environmental information were placed on the same page. Readers did not see a single plant, but the distribution of plants as altitude and climate changed. The image turned the distant mountain into a structure of relationships that could be examined.\n\nNatural sciences, mathematics, and statistics meet here: observation provides material, measurement makes the material comparable, and images and models present relationships. Naming remains important, but after naming, the question continues: with which conditions does this phenomenon appear? When conditions change, how does it move?",
    "knowledgePoint": "Natural sciences, mathematics, and statistics combine observation, measurement, comparison, and models to find patterns in natural phenomena. Humboldt's synthetic images of nature show a turn from classification to relationships, and from specimens to networks of variables.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "If the same plant always appears with certain altitudes, temperatures, and humidity, is a specimen still only a name?"
  },
  "061-phone-backup-help": {
    "title": "That One Choice in the Noise",
    "summary": "When a message passes through a telephone line, the first test is not its meaning, but whether the receiving end can distinguish exactly which one it was.",
    "scene": "At Bell Labs in the mid-twentieth century, the table held circuit diagrams, telephone-line records, switch symbols, and a sequence of 0s and 1s waiting to be sent.",
    "storyBody": "A sequence of symbols comes through from the other end of a telephone line. It may be a sentence, a set of instructions, or only a signal agreed upon by machines. When people read a message, they often first ask what it means: what it announces, what it changes, whom it comforts, whom it commands. But before lines, switches, and receivers, an earlier question appears: is the received symbol really the one that was sent?\n\nNoise does not care about meaning. Small fluctuations in current, interference in the line, and errors in equipment can all make a symbol blur. The sender sends 1011, and the receiver may see 1001. To a person, this is only one digit different; to a communication system, the difference is already serious enough. If the receiving end cannot distinguish reliably, later understanding has no reliable entrance.\n\nClaude Shannon temporarily moved the problem away from \"what does the message say\" toward \"how many possibilities does the message exclude.\" If the receiver originally faces two possible outcomes, 0 or 1, then receiving one excludes the other. That smallest two-way choice can be represented as 1 bit. The more possible outcomes there are, the greater the uncertainty before receiving; the more a message reduces uncertainty, the more information it carries.\n\nIn this way, information quantity is no longer the same as word count. A short signal may be very \"heavy\" if it locks one result among many possibilities. A long string of repetition may be very \"light\" if it adds almost no new distinction. Communication technology began to gain a calculable language: a message is not first treated as meaning, but first as a narrowing of a space of choices.\n\nBut counting choices is not enough. Noise can disturb them, so a system needs coding, repetition, checking, and error-correction structures. Sending something that looks redundant is meant to let the receiver still judge where an error may have occurred under interference. Channel capacity is like the load limit of a line: under given conditions, it defines how much information can be transmitted reliably per unit of time.\n\nShannon's 1948 paper, A Mathematical Theory of Communication, made concepts such as bit, entropy, and channel capacity foundational to modern information theory. Information and communication technology gained a clear engineering route from this point: first count uncertainty, then encode the message into a transmissible form, and then consider how to recover it under noise. Meaning still matters, but it must first pass through a channel that can be recognized, protected, and restored.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Information and communication technology studies how information is encoded, transmitted, stored, recovered, and made to flow reliably through systems. Information theory understands a message as a reduction of uncertainty, uses bits to measure choice, uses entropy to describe uncertainty, and studies how noise, redundancy, coding, and channel capacity affect communication reliability.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "When a message must pass through noise, should the system first protect its meaning, or first protect its identity as a distinguishable choice?"
  },
  "070-wobbly-shelf-repair": {
    "title": "The Drawing Beneath the Iron Bridge",
    "summary": "When bridges, tunnels, and great ships became too large, building could no longer rely only on hand feel; it had to accept the shared constraints of drawings, materials, and verification.",
    "scene": "In nineteenth-century Britain, an engineering drawing crowded together a riverway, bridge towers, iron plates, rivets, steamship compartments, and dimensions waiting to be calculated.",
    "storyBody": "When a wooden shelf leans, someone can steady it by hand and add another nail. Small bridges, sheds, and houses can often be corrected gradually through experience. How far timber bends, how stones bite into one another, where support should be placed for stability: the eye and hand of an old craftsperson are continually trained on the site. The material is in the hand, and error remains close to the person.\n\nBut when a bridge has to cross a wider valley, a tunnel has to pass under a riverbed, or an iron ship's hull becomes large enough to require rows of rivets, compartments, and steam power, experience begins to be pushed to the edge by scale. One change in dimension may change weight, tension, buoyancy, cost, and safety at the same time. Failure on site is no longer only \"the place that was not fixed well.\" It can become systemic risk.\n\nThe nineteenth-century Britain of Isambard Kingdom Brunel was exactly such a period of expanding ambition. The engineering represented by the Thames Tunnel, Great Western Railway, Clifton Suspension Bridge, and large steamships was not only a matter of building things. Before work began, it required engineers to face whether materials could bear the load, how structures transmitted force, how workers should be organized, how funding could continue, and how accidents could be prevented.\n\nA drawing was therefore not only beautiful lines. It was like a construction site opened in advance, breaking imagination into dimensions, angles, materials, forces, processes, and boundaries. If a line was wrong, the site might answer with deformation. If a calculation was missed, the structure might remind people with cracks. If the wrong material was chosen, both cost and safety would be pulled along. Engineering had to accept constraints on paper before it accepted verification on site.\n\nExperience was not cancelled. On the contrary, it was placed inside a stricter cycle: design, calculate, manufacture, build, test, and then bring field results back into the next design. The craftsperson's eye still had value, but it no longer carried the whole judgment alone. Bridges, tunnels, and great ships showed that the larger building becomes, the more human imagination must be handed to systems that can be checked.\n\nThe core responsibility of engineering, manufacturing, and construction forms here. They do not only turn a bold idea into a physical thing. They make that thing stand among materials, tools, organization, cost, and safety. A drawing holds ambition back not to shrink it, but to give ambition a chance to become a structure that does not easily fall.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Engineering, manufacturing, and construction focus on turning needs into reliable structures or systems through verifiable design, material choice, calculation, organization, and construction process. They emphasize that imagination must be tested by physical conditions, resource limits, safety requirements, and field feedback together.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "When a building or structure becomes too large to judge by experience alone, what responsibilities do drawings, calculations, and tests each carry?"
  },
  "080-community-garden-seedlings": {
    "title": "Wheat Still Standing After Wind and Rain",
    "summary": "Whether a row of wheat succeeds is not judged only by the weight of the heads, but by whether it can endure fertilizer, disease, wind, rain, and repeated tests on different land.",
    "scene": "In mid-twentieth-century experimental fields in Mexico, researchers moved among rows of wheat, checking stalk height, rust spots, and yield records.",
    "storyBody": "In an experimental field, the eye easily falls first on the heads of wheat. Which row is fuller, which plot yields more, which variety looks better on the record sheet: these are unavoidable questions in agricultural research. In the face of food shortage, yield is not an abstract indicator. It is the weight on many families' tables.\n\nBut a field never asks only one question. If wheat stalks are too tall, fertilizer may make them grow stronger, but it may also make them fall in wind and rain. If rust spots appear on leaves, yield is quietly weakened. A variety that performs well in one season may become unstable on another piece of land, under another water condition, or with another planting practice. If high yield cannot be repeated, it is not yet a reliable answer.\n\nWhen Norman Borlaug and his team worked on wheat breeding in Mexico, this was the kind of multiple pressure they faced. They kept crossing, sowing, screening, eliminating, and comparing varieties under different conditions. The research was not only looking for the plant that seemed strongest, but for a combination that could still maintain yield after fertilizer, disease, and environmental change.\n\nThe meaning of semi-dwarf wheat hides in the fact that it can \"stand.\" Shorter stalks lowered the risk of lodging, and the plant could direct more growth strength toward the head after fertilization. Disease resistance also made yield less easily taken away by rust. Success in the field was no longer only \"growing more,\" but \"still harvesting under pressure.\"\n\nThis change later became linked with the Green Revolution. High-yielding, disease-resistant semi-dwarf varieties increased food production capacity in some regions, while also raising continuing debates about irrigation, fertilizer dependence, ecological effects, and social distribution. Agricultural answers rarely exist only inside one seed. The seed must work together with soil, water, disease, technology, farmer practice, and social conditions.\n\nSo wheat that can stand is not a simple pose of victory. It reminds people that agriculture optimizes a living system. Yield matters, but stability, adaptation, disease resistance, and long-term effects will also return to the field. The moment the wheat stands, behind it lies repeated adjustment among biological traits, environmental conditions, and human management.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Agriculture, forestry, fisheries, and veterinary fields study relationships among biological resources, environmental conditions, production techniques, and social needs. In crop breeding, agricultural research does not pursue only one-time high yield; it also considers disease resistance, lodging risk, environmental adaptation, resource input, and long-term impact.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "If a crop yields highly but easily fails under disease, wind, or rain, is it truly suited to agricultural production?"
  },
  "090-medicine-schedule-care": {
    "title": "The Heat Beyond the Sickbed",
    "summary": "An epidemic investigation pushed the doctor's gaze from symptoms toward housing, food, education, and institutions, so disease no longer stopped inside the body.",
    "scene": "In Upper Silesia in 1848, Rudolf Virchow examined patients in a typhus epidemic area and also recorded crowded housing, hunger, and poverty.",
    "storyBody": "When doctors approach the sickbed, they first see the body. Fever, rash, weakness, and the number of deaths all pull judgment back toward diagnosis and treatment. The patient's suffering is concrete and urgent, and no broad social word can replace care and medical judgment in that moment.\n\nBut in the Upper Silesian typhus investigation, the symptoms kept pushing the question beyond the sickbed. People lived in crowded housing, food was insufficient, educational opportunities were limited, transportation and public conditions lagged behind, and poverty repeatedly weakened bodily resistance. Disease occurred in the body, yet it was tangled with living conditions outside the body.\n\nRudolf Virchow recorded illness in the investigation, and also the conditions people lived under. His report connected the epidemic with food, schools, local governance, and political representation. Arrangements that seemed far from the consulting room began to enter medical vision. A prescription could handle one patient's suffering, but it could hardly explain by itself why a whole population remained exposed to similar risks.\n\nThis does not push medical responsibility onto another field. On the contrary, medicine was forced to face more material. Treating individuals remained important, and public health could not leave clinical knowledge behind. But when many people were driven toward disease by the same set of environments, a doctor who looked only at spots on the skin would miss the conditions that made the spots keep appearing.\n\nThe heat on the sickbed was connected to housing, tables, roads, schools, and public institutions. One person's fever can be caused by a pathogen, but the vulnerability of a whole region often has to be explained through living conditions. Health is not only the absence of disease. It also includes whether a person has enough nutrition, shelter, knowledge, care, and basic capacity to participate in public life.\n\nVirchow is later often linked with the tradition of social medicine. Health and welfare thereby show a wider range: they include diagnosis, treatment, and care, and also public health, social conditions, and institutional arrangements. The patient lies in bed, but the cause may sometimes stand outside the door, in the street, in the school, and beside the granary.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Health and welfare focus on disease, care, public health, social conditions, and people's basic capabilities for living. Social medicine emphasizes that disease is related not only to biological factors, but also to poverty, housing, education, food, governance, and public institutions.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "When the same disease repeatedly appears together with poverty, crowded housing, and insufficient food, where should medicine draw the boundary of observation?"
  },
  "100-rainy-event-service-desk": {
    "title": "The Moment of Truth at the Gate",
    "summary": "The minutes a passenger spends waiting at a counter or gate move service quality from back-office process into the moment when a customer judges the company.",
    "scene": "At Scandinavian Airlines in the 1980s, passengers repeatedly judged the company at counters, on phone calls, at gates, and in delay announcements.",
    "storyBody": "Passengers do not first see an airline's hangars, shift schedules, or process manuals. They see a line in front of the counter, whether someone answers on the phone, where their luggage is being asked about, and whether anyone explains the next step after a delay. However complex the back office may be, it has to be felt by passengers in these brief contacts.\n\nThe problem often appears in a few minutes of waiting. Announcements are vague, the line grows longer, and counter staff look down at the system but do not have permission to make a decision. For the company, this may be only a small node in the process. For the passenger, these few minutes are already enough to judge whether the company is reliable.\n\nWhen Jan Carlzon led Scandinavian Airlines, he called these customer contacts moments of truth. The phrase has power not because it works like a slogan, but because it pushes management's attention from the office back to the gate. Service does not occur only after the back office has finished. It is tested in the moment when customer and employee face one another.\n\nIf the person at the gate can only repeat \"please wait for notification,\" passengers see not only the limits of one employee, but a whole system that has not handed judgment to the front line. Training, authorization, information systems, and organizational levels all need to be rearranged around these contact points.\n\nThe difficulty of service lies here: what people remember may be only a few sentences, one decision, or one explanation. But behind those small moments stands the whole company. Back-office processes must support front-line judgment, and front-line experience also exposes whether the back office truly understands customers.",
    "knowledgePoint": "Service focuses on how people and organizations create value together through contact points, processes, experience, and trust. Service quality comes not only from back-office efficiency, but also from whether customers feel understood, answered, and reliably handled in front-line contact.",
    "reflectionQuestion": "If customers know a company only through a few moments of contact, whom should the back-office system be designed for?"
  }
};
